<HR>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#990000"><FONT SIZE="4">Environmental Leadership
Demonstrated in Oregon</FONT></FONT></H2>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><I>Two WMX facilities and the <A HREF="http://www.deq.state.or.us/deqhome.htm">Oregon Department of Environmental Quality (ODEQ)</A>
  are  participating as a pilot project of the <A HREF="http://es.inel.gov/elp"> U.S.
EPA's Environmental Leadership Program.</A>  Ten  businesses and two federal
facilities were selected to take part in the program, designed  to encourage and
recognize innovative and effective environmental management systems.</I></P>
<P><I>To demonstrate WMX environmental management systems, ODEQ and EPA staff
have  participated in WMX training programs, inspections, self-audits and
corporate audits at two  adjacent landfills in Arlington, Oregon - the Columbia
Ridge Landfill and Recycling Center  for non-hazardous waste, and Chemical Waste
Management of the Northwest. Agency  officials have been given access to the
computer-based compliance tools described in this  section to evaluate how they
function as part of a compliance management system.</I></P>
<P><I>The facilities are also demonstrating environmental leadership beyond
compliance. For  example, Columbia Ridge is working with the Oregon Graduate
Institute on a biodiversity  project investigating how to restore native habitat
in areas of the 12,000-acre property  that are disturbed by landfill
construction. The biodiversity project is also looking at ways to  enhance the
wildlife habitat value of the property and protect a threatened plant species 
found at the site.</I></P>
<P><I>EPA is evaluating all of the pilot projects to identify the essential
elements and recognize  facility-level environmental leadership. </I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="center"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/group.jpg" ALT="Group Picture" WIDTH="408" HEIGHT="162">
