<TABLE ALIGN="LEFT"><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./art/report/bar12.gif" ALT="Wetlands Affected North America 1995"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 12</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./art/report/bar13.gif" ALT="WMI: Total Trees Planted"></TD></TR><TR
><TD ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 13</TD></TR>             

</TABLE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Conserving Wetlands and
Biodiversity</FONT><BR>WMX has made a unique commitment to "no net loss of
wetlands or other biological diversity" on its properties.  No models for
pursuing such a commitment on private lands existed, so WMI and Rust developed a
systematic approach embodied in a detailed guidance manual for biodiversity
planning at Company facilities. About 50 sites were identified for preparation
of systematic inventories and plans before major new construction or expansion.
Plans have been completed for 15 sites and are under development at eight more
in the U.S. and Australia.</P></BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
Results demonstrate the value of the WMX approach for voluntary conservation of
biological resources: the studies found opportunities to conserve, and in some
cases, restore or enhance biological resources while allowing economic activity
to proceed. At the Springhill Landfill in Northeast Florida, for example, the
biodiversity inventory identified wetlands and old-growth live oak trees as
priority resources. Facility management dedicated a conservation easement on 12
acres of the wetlands to the state of Florida. They also built a 1,000-foot
boardwalk of recycled plastic through the wetlands and natural areas and
preserved several old-growth trees.</P>
<P>
The year 1995 also marked the 10-year anniversary of a conservation agreement
protecting the threatened Bay Checkerspot Butterfly at the Kirby Canyon landfill
near San Jose, California. WMI entered into the agreement with the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service in 1986 establishing a trust fund to support habitat
restoration and monitoring. Over a 10-year period, the Stanford University
Center for Conservation Biology has studied the butterfly habitat and
populations and published 26 scientific papers on the subject. At the end of
1995, WMI voluntarily renewed  its support for the Trust fund for a period of
three years. This will allow research and monitoring activities to continue and
provide for a focus on restoring closed landfill areas as additional butterfly
habitat.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
During 1995, WMX companies in North America met their goal of &Ograve;no net
loss&Oacute; of wetlands, creating or restoring 7.7 acres of wetlands for each
acre filled. The two-year average is 2.7 to one (see Figure 12) areas are
considered  to have been protected if they were acquired for permanent
preservation of their wetlands resources. Internationally, wetlands impacts are
not currently tracked because of the lack of consistent definitions and
regulations.</P>
<P>
In 1990, WMI pledged to plant 1 million trees by the year 2000. To date, WMI
divisions working with community groups have planted or sponsored the planting
of over 811,200 trees (see Figure 13). Waste Management of Ohio received the
Ohio Department of Natural Resources Governor's TreeSource Award for its efforts
in planting nearly 125,000 trees. At the Countywide Recycling and Disposal
Facility in Boliver, Ohio, for example, more than 120 student and adult
volunteers planted 11,700 seedlings on three tracts of reclaimed strip mine
land.
</P>
<P><BR><BR><BR></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
SRC="./art/report/meddow2.jpg" ALT="Meadow"></TD>
<TD COLSTART="2" WIDTH="150">At the Woodland Recycling and Disposal Facility in
South Elgin, Illinois, 16 acres of wetlands were created to compensate for the
filling of seven acres of wetlands that had developed in a former gravel pit. 
The Wildlife Habitat Council, a non-profit conservation organization, certified
the site for this and other measures to improve wildlife habitat, including
restoration of native vegetation.</TD></TR></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="1"></A></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Buying Recycled</FONT><BR> WMX opened or
designed three offices in 1995 featuring recycled and environmentally preferable
materials and systems. The WMI/Recycle America office in downtown Los Angeles
opened in July featuring walls made with recycled newspaper and steel, carpets
of recycled soda bottles, furniture from waste cardboard and lumber salvaged
from movie sets, a variety of recycled office supplies, non-toxic paint, and air
and water purification systems. Designers of new offices in downtown Chicago and
Washington, D.C. have followed suit and, indeed, added to the list of attractive
and functional recycled materials used. The offices serve as a demonstration to
their many visitors that construction with recycled and environmentally friendly
materials is practical and can be accomplished at a cost comparable to
conventional materials. 
</P> 
<P>
In 1995, WMX's Purchasing Department spent $113,498,000, about the same as in
1994, on goods containing recycled material, including steel in trucks and
roll-off containers, plastic in recycling and trash containers and office paper<B>
(see Table 3).  </B>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>  
<CENTER><IMG
SRC="./art/report/table3.gif" ALT="1995 WMX Purchase of Goods and Recycled Content"></CENTER>
<P ALIGN="center"> <BR>
