<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
<TITLE>1995 Annual Environmental Report</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="./art/report/paper.gif">
<P ALIGN="center"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/banner.jpg" ALT="Banner" WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="150"></P>
<P ALIGN="center"><A HREF="pg15.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/previous.gif" ALT="Previous Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="pg16.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/next.gif" ALT="Next Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="contents.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/index.gif" ALT="Index" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A>
</P> 
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><BR><BR><A NAME="1"></A></P>
<TABLE ALIGN="RIGHT"><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/bar14.gif" ALT="Energy Generation"></TD></TR><TR><TD
 ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 14</TD></TR>       

</TABLE>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR="00994d">Saving and Generating Energy</FONT></B><BR>WMX
companies produce power from various unconventional fuels. Facilities in North
America, Sweden, Germany and the United Kingdom generated 6 billion
kilowatt-hours of electricity (see Figure 14) and sold more than 8 million cubic
feet per day of landfill gas for heating and other purposes.
</P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="00994d">Landfill Gas to Energy</FONT></B>   WMX companies
worldwide operate 35 landfill gas-to-electricity plants - more than any other
company. In addition, four facilities in the United States process landfill gas
and sell it as a medium-Btu fuel to industries as a replacement for natural gas,
coal or oil. In Sweden, the Kovik Landfill uses its gas-to-energy plant to power
the BRINI&#170; system at the adjacent recycling facility. At the Pescantina
Landfill in Italy, landfill gas is used to run the leachate treatment plant.
Four new landfill gas plants and three expansions are planned for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Two projects begun in 1995 will help extend landfill gas utilization to smaller
facilities where it has not been  cost-effective. WMI, Rust, and Caterpillar,
WMI's landfill gas joint venture partner, joined forces to adapt a standard
reciprocating engine to run on landfill gas. The new engine, dubbed BRUTUS, uses
technologies and computer controls perfected in diesel and natural gas engines
to maximize energy production and control emissions such as nitrous oxide and
carbon monoxide, two common by-products of landfill gas combustion. Because
landfill gas naturally varies in its energy content, earlier engines have not
always been able to work at peak efficiency. The new engine, however, uses
computer technology to continually adjust the mix of air and gas, allowing the
system to wring maximum energy value from the landfill gas. A WMI process
improvement team also examined the variety of potential uses - from space
heating to electricity generation - for landfill gas, and is working with
landfills of varying sizes and ages to identify cost-effective opportunities. 
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
<B><FONT COLOR="00994d">Trash to Energy </FONT></B>In 1995, Wheelabrator's 16
trash-to-energy plants in the United States processed 7.5 million tons of trash,
generating four billion kilowatt-hours of electricity - enough to light a city
the size of San Francisco. During 1995, Wheelabrator brought on line its newest
trash-to-energy facility in Lisbon, Connecticut, handling 500 tons per day of
trash to produce 110 million kilowatt-hours of electricity per year.
Wheelabrator's Falls Township, Pennsylvania plant won the 1995 Power Plant Award
from Power Magazine for its energy-efficient design, advanced environmental
controls and incorporation of a materials recovery facility into its operation.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="2"></A></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><FONT COLOR="00994d">Small Power Production</FONT></B>  
Wheelabrator operates seven small power production facilities using a variety 
of fuels, including waste wood, waste coal, tires and landfill gas to produce
energy. The Ridge Generating Station in Polk County, Florida completed its first
full year of operation, converting more than 331,000 tons of waste wood and
tires into 200 million kilowatt-hours of electricity. Sherman Station, a
wood-burning power plant in Maine, has developed a program to reuse all of the
ash produced by the facility. Depending upon the nutrient content of the ash, it
is used by local farmers as fertilizer, added to compost or used as fill by an
adjacent lumber company. Also in 1995, Wheelabrator bought and re-started a
wood-burning power plant that had closed in Martell, California.</P> 
<P><B><FONT COLOR="00994d">
Alternative Fuels</FONT></B>   For several years, Waste Management of Argentina
has run a fleet of 65 light duty trucks on natural gas in Buenos Aires. In the
U.S., 17 vehicles ranging from collection trucks to landfill equipment are
running on natural gas or a combination of diesel and natural gas. In 1995, WMI
formed an Alternative Fuels Users Council to evaluate the Company's experience
with demonstration and pilot projects and plan further steps to use alternative
fuels in its fleet of nearly 19,000 collection vehicles and heavy equipment. In
addition to cleaner emissions, the use of natural gas fuels reduces maintenance
requirements and increases engine lifetimes. The Council is considering several
proposals to demonstrate how landfill gas captured at Company landfills can be
purified, compressed or liquefied and used as fuel.
</P>
<P>
Waste Management of the Desert in Palm Desert, California introduced Southern
California's first EPA-certified 100 percent natural gas waste collection and
recycling truck. The truck rolled out in September of 1995 was the first of 14
to be converted to natural gas with assistance from a grant from the South Coast
Air Quality Management District.
</P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="00994d">Energy-Efficient Transportation</FONT></B>  
During 1995, 91 WMI hauling divisions (about 40 percent of the total) began
implementing the STARS computer-assisted routing system for commercial
collection routes. The system helps to determine the most efficient pattern for
commercial collection, thereby cutting miles traveled, fuel consumed and air
pollution generated. By the end of 1995 the participating divisions had
eliminated 3,382 hours per week of truck operation, equivalent to about 9
percent of total hours and 68 trucks on the road. Fuel savings over the year
totaled about 157,000 gallons. At the year-end level of implementation, fuel
savings will total 500,000  gallons in 1996 and cost savings $7 million. The
savings are expected to be even greater, however, as additional divisions use
the system and additional routes are analyzed at participating divisions.</P>
<P>
In Seattle, WMI operates the nation's first containerized rail-haul system,
shipping the city's trash to WMI's Columbia Ridge Landfill in Oregon. Rail-haul
is more fuel efficient and generates significantly less air pollution than truck
transportation.
</P>
<P>
<B><FONT COLOR="00994d">Buildings and Operations </FONT></B>   During 1995,
WMX completed the <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/docs/GCDOAR/GreenLights.html">&quot;Green Lights&quot;</A> retrofit of its headquarters
buildings by installing new lighting in one of the older headquarters buildings.
A more efficient, CFC-free air conditioning system was installed at the same
time. Despite a brutally hot summer, the improvements saved nearly 140,000
kilowatt-hours.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="3"></A></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="00994d">Soil and Water Conservation</FONT></B>
<BR> WMX facilities use a variety of methods to conserve soil and water.
Landfill operations require the use of considerable amounts of soil for daily,
interim and final cover of filled areas. Daily covering of trash is a key
requirement for maintaining sanitary conditions. In several states, WMI has
worked with authorities to permit the use of &quot;alternative daily cover&quot;
- ranging from tarps to treated soil from bioremediation facilities - to
conserve clean soil. These efforts have saved more than a million cubic yards of
soil and also helped to extend the life of the landfills. 
</P>
<P>
In arid regions, water must be used in landfill operations to prevent blowing
dust that could impact local air quality. Several WMI facilities use reclaimed
water for this purpose. For example, at the Altamont Landfill in California, a
wastewater treatment plant handles runoff and leachate from the 550 acre site.
The water is treated to exacting regional water quality standards and then used
on site for dust control and landscaping.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE> 
<P ALIGN="center"> <BR>
<B>Conserving Nature and Natural Resources Continues...</B><BR><A
