<HTML>
<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
<TITLE>1995 Annual Environmental Report</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="./art/report/paper.gif">
<P ALIGN="center"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/banner.jpg" ALT="Banner" WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="150"></P>
<P ALIGN="center"><A HREF="pg20.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/previous.gif" ALT="Previous Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="pg22.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/next.gif" ALT="Next Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="contents.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/index.gif" ALT="Index" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A>
</P>
<TABLE ALIGN="LEFT"><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./art/report/pie15.gif" ALT="Superfund Sites"></TD></TR><TR><TD
ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 15</TD></TR>              

</TABLE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Remediation at WMX Facilities</FONT><BR>Most
non-permitted releases for which WMX subsidiaries have some responsibility have
occurred at land disposal facilities in the United States. Virtually all of
these have occurred at older facilities acquired from other companies, or at
facilities not owned by WMX but to which WMX or its predecessors lawfully
transported waste. In general, environmental considerations in landfill location
and design were much less stringent when these facilities were developed than
they are today.</P>
<P>
At sites acquired by WMX, the Company has assumed responsibility for
investigating contamination and  implementing appropriate remedial measures. At
sites not owned by WMX, the Company either takes a lead role or works with other
responsible parties to investigate and remediate contamination.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
Some of these sites are on the EPA Superfund National Priority List (NPL).
Claims have been made against  WMX subsidiaries at 105 sites on the NPL where
these subsidiaries are alleged to be potentially responsible parties (PRPs).
None of the 105 NPL facilities were originally developed by WMX. Nineteen were
acquired by WMX subsidiaries from other owners. The remaining 86 have never been
owned by WMX, but received some waste transported by a firm, the liabilities of
which are currently owned by the Company, typically as one of many waste haulers
serving an area <B>(see Figure 15). </B></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
At each of the 19 WMX-owned facilities on the NPL, the Company lends its
technical expertise and works with  the government to characterize or remediate
problems. In addition, the Company has either agreed, or is seeking agreement,
with other liable parties to share the costs of remediation or is pursuing
resolution of an allocation formula. Sites subject to state &quot;Superfund&quot;
laws are treated by the Company in the same way as NPL sites. Internationally,
WMX has upgraded and cleaned up a number of acquired facilities.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
WMX net expenditures for remediation of closed sites (after recovery of costs
from other parties) are shown  in Figure 16. In 1991, the Company recorded a
charge of $296 million before tax and minority interest, to reflect its
then-current estimate of Superfund environmental remediation liabilities. The
Company continues to evaluate and provide for the costs of remediating other
sites that may pose a potential threat to public health, welfare or the
environment. It also provides for costs expected to be incurred after a facility
ceases to accept waste. At the end of 1995, WMX had accrued $762 million to
provide for environmental responsibilities, including remediation, closure and
post-closure monitoring costs. No significant judgments or settlements were
entered in 1995 with respect to private civil actions against WMX concerning
pollutants released from disposal facilities. WMX carries environmental
impairment liability insurance in amounts that meet or exceed legal
requirements.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="1"></A></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Management Accountability
and Employee Involvement</FONT></B>
</P>
<P>
From division presidents to the Chief Executive Officer, all managers with
environmental responsibilities have incentives for environmental performance
through compensation systems.
</P>
<P>
The WMX Executive Environmental Committee is the principal management committee
for oversight of  environmental performance and for strategic reporting to the
Chief Executive Officer of WMX. Its members include executives from each of the
operating groups and major corporate functions. During 1995, the Committee 
 approved environmental management program standards applicable to the operating
groups and established  a process and guidance for annual planning under the WMX
Environmental Policy and Principles.</P> 
<TABLE ALIGN="RIGHT"><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/bar16.gif" ALT="Expenditures for Remediation of Closed Sites"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 16</TD></TR>            

</TABLE>
<P>
Within most of the operating groups, committees or other mechanisms have been
established to coordinate  environmental policies and programs across business
units. For example, WTI has established a President's Environmental Management
Council made up of representatives of the various business units.</P> 
<P>
Environmental considerations are inherent in decisions made by the WMX Board of
Directors. In addition, the  WMX Law and Compliance group reports to the Audit
Committee of the Board on a semi-annual basis and, for the past six years,
Arthur D. Little, Inc. has presented the results of its annual environmental
assessment to the Audit Committee. None of the Audit Committee members is a WMX
employee. The Board of Directors has reviewed and approved each annual
environmental report, including this one, since reporting began in 1990.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
Environmental performance depends upon the efforts of all employees. WMX has
instituted recognition programs  to encourage and reward employee involvement in
the environmental issues. In 1995, the Chairman's Award for Environmental
Excellence was given to a team of WMI and Rust employees who developed and are
implementing a complex plan for protecting threatened species and restoring
native habitats at the Mallard Ridge Recycling and Disposal Facility in Delavan,
Wisconsin. Many operating groups also have recognition programs for individuals
or business units.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="3"></A></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Environmental Management
Certification</FONT></B> 
</P>
<P>
WMX companies have pursued certification of their environmental management
systems under various country programs. Two of the three hazardous waste
management companies in The Netherlands, for example, are certified under the
Dutch Environmental Care system and the solid waste companies are preparing for
certification. Two facilities in the United Kingdom are certified under BS 7750
<A HREF="pg22.htm">(see profile)</A>. All of these programs require independent
audits of the Company's environmental management systems.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
During 1996, WMX operating groups will assess whether to seek certification for
their facilities under the  Organization for International Standardization's new
Environmental Management Standard (ISO 14001). An initial assessment was done at
the corporate level as part of the Arthur D. Little review of WMX environmental
management systems. WMI plc formed an ISO task force in 1995 to assist
facilities in seeking certification.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="4"></A></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Annual Environmental Report</FONT></B>

</P>
<P>
This is the sixth WMX Annual Environmental Report. It was prepared by the
Executive Environmental Committee and approved by the WMX Board of Directors. 
We welcome your comments and have provided a
<A HREF="http://www.wmx.com/docs/comments.html">comment form</A> for your use.
We will make a donation of $5 for each card received to Earth Share, a coalition
of 43 environmental and conservation charities operating locally, nationally and
internationally.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
In 1995, WMI plc issued its first environmental report covering the company's
worldwide activities and setting   out goals and objectives under the WMX
Environmental Policy and Principles.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="center"> <BR>
