<HTML>
<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
<TITLE>1995 Annual Environmental Report</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="./art/report/paper.gif">
<P ALIGN="center"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/banner.jpg" ALT="Banner" WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="150"></P>
<P ALIGN="center"><A HREF="pg24.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/previous.gif" ALT="Previous Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="pg27.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/next.gif" ALT="Next Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="contents.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/index.gif" ALT="Index" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Research and Development</FONT><BR>WMX
companies conduct research and development on issues important to the
environmental management of their facilities, on environmentally sound methods
of managing wastes and on environmental issues significant to their customers.
Some of this research is coordinated through Rust's Clemson Technical Center
(CTC), a joint program with Clemson University. CTC projects in 1995 included
development of systems for radioactive soil decontamination and for treatment of
mixed hazardous and radioactive waste. Working with the U.S. Department of
Energy (DOE), Rust has formed a partnership with the Radon Institute in Moscow
to test cold crucible vitrification on DOE wastes in the United States. Rust is
also demonstrating a technology to recover usable iron and oil from steel mill
sludge. Other WMX research and development projects in 1995 included:</P>
<UL><LI>Chem-Nuclear Systems, Inc. developed the Thermex&#170; process for use
by electric utilities in managing radioactive liquids. The process reclaims
usable water and produces a concentrated solid waste that can be readily
managed. It reduces radioactive waste volumes, decreases operational exposure
and offers an alternative to dilute-and-release management of radioactive
liquids;</LI></UL>
<UL><LI> In Hong Kong, WMI plc developed a process for recovering usable fuel
from oily wastes typically discharged by ships at sea;</LI></UL>
<UL><LI> In France, WMI plc developed the Toxipole system for collecting small
quantities of hazardous wastes. The system includes bar code identification for
effective tracking; and</LI></UL>
<UL><LI>The West Edmonton Landfill in Alberta, Canada demonstrated hydraulic
fracturing of refuse to enhance leachate extraction.</LI></UL>
<P>The Company has also established the WMX Patent Society to encourage and
recognize innovative research and development efforts by employees. Twelve
employees were recognized in 1995 for 19 patents.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="1"></A></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Community Involvement</FONT>
</P>
<P>
WMX community involvement programs are guided by the Company's unique Good
Neighbor Policy that articulates its commitment to the communities in which it
operates. The policy includes a pledge to consult with host communities when
planning business activities and to provide information about facility
operations. It also commits to hiring a diverse local work force and
participating in community activities. Examples of 1995 community involvement
projects include:
</P>
<UL><LI>WMI hauling and landfill divisions worked with community leaders,
donating services to demolish and dispose of 100 &quot;crack&quot; houses in a
run-down section of Taylor, Texas;</LI></UL>
<UL><LI> One hundred volunteers from Pacific Waste Management (PWM) collected
or coordinated the collection of more than 150 tons of trash on Clean Up
Australia Day. PWM donated the services of collection trucks and drivers and
provided trash bins, including some that were floated on barges for trash
collected in waterways.</LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="2"></A></P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Environmental Education</FONT>
</P>
<P>
WMX companies sponsor educational programs, develop partnerships with schools
and non-profit organizations to promote environmental education, and volunteer
their expertise in environmental issues. WMX facilities also host open houses
and tours to educate community members and others interested about the
facilities and their environmental programs. During 1995, for example, nearly
100,000 people toured WMX facilities worldwide (see Table 4).
</P> 
<P>
The hundreds of thousands of people attending presentations by WMX people
include children reached by &quot;CYCLER&#168;<SUP>&#174;</SUP>&quot; a
remote-controlled robot in constant demand for school assemblies, trade shows,
science fairs, open houses and community hearings. It is estimated that since
the program began in 1991, CYCLER&reg; has performed before more than 2 million
people. In 1995, the Company published a musical compact disc of recycling songs
starring CYCLER&reg; featuring rock and roll, country/western and rap music
themes. 
</P>
<CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/table4.gif" ALT="Tours and Presentations 1995"></CENTER></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
In early 1996, WMX launched a five year, $250,000 Environmental Careers
Awareness Program with the United Negro College Fund. The program will provide
funds to five colleges and universities for curriculum development and
internships at WMX divisions.
</P>
<P>
Other environmental education programs included:
</P>
<UL><LI>Waste Management Argentina celebrated Earth Day '95 with a recycling
program in Rio IV, working with a municipal campaign to promote environmental
awareness. The Company installed special recycling containers and students
helped collect paper, glass and aluminum for recycling.</LI></UL>
<UL><LI> Germany held a nationwide recycling day to show what becomes of
materials collected through the &quot;Green Dot&quot; program for recycling.
Waste Management Deutschland facilities participating in the program welcomed
more than 15,000 visitors to their recycling facilities.</LI></UL>
<UL><LI> WMI plc is working with the International Chamber of Commerce and the
United Nations Environment Programme to develop Environmental Management
Training Kits for use by small- and medium-sized businesses in developing
countries. </LI></UL>
<UL><LI>WMI sponsors a program at 97 schools in the San Antonio, Texas area to
teach children about recycling by having them actively participate in recycling
milk cartons. WMI collects the cartons for recycling into printing and writing
materials.</LI></UL>
<UL><LI>In conjunction with the SOS Children's Village in Coconut Creek,
Florida, Wheelabrator designed and constructed an educational boardwalk with an
environmental theme on land adjacent to the Village.</LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="1"></A></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="center"> <BR>
<B>Leadership continues...</B><BR><A HREF="pg24.htm"><IMG
