<TITLE>1995 Annual Environmental Report</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="./art/report/paper.gif">
<P ALIGN="center"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/banner.jpg" ALT="Banner" WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="150"></P>
<P ALIGN="center"><A HREF="pg24.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/previous.gif" ALT="Previous Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="pg26.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/next.gif" ALT="Next Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="contents.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/index.gif" ALT="Index" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A>
</P> 
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Public Policy Development</FONT>

</P>
<P>
WMX promotes and supports public policy that is protective of the environment.
Company involvement in governmental policy is managed by the government affairs
programs of WMX, with staff in Washington, D.C., Oak Brook, Illinois, several
U.S. state capitals, London, Brussels and several European countries. WMX
companies also participate actively in business-environment groups that promote
sound environmental management and sustainable development, including the World
Business Council for Sustainable Development, the <A HREF="http://www.nwf.org/nwf/ccc/">National Wildlife Federation
Corporate Conservation Council</A> and the <A HREF="http://www.gemi.org">Global Environmental Management
Initiative.</A>
</P>
<P>
In Europe, WMI plc has sought to strengthen European Union standards for
landfill design and operation.  It has also participated actively in discussions
about implementation of the Basel Convention on the Control of Transboundary
Movements of Hazardous Wastes.</P> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
In the U.S., WMX has focused on several important public policy initiatives
including reauthorization and reform  of Superfund to sustain its benefits in
cleaning up waste sites and to provide incentives for proper waste handling
while making cleanups faster, less expensive and more equitably implemented.
Another important focus was on promoting public-private partnerships to allow
mutually beneficial privatization of wastewater treatment plants and other
environmental facilities. In October, 1995 the U.S. EPA issued new emissions
standards for Municipal Waste Combustors. Wheelabrator cooperated closely with
the Agency over five years in evaluating international standards, control
technologies and emissions from existing facilities.</P>
<P>
WMX also contributed actively to EPA's development of a new enforcement policy
that encourages companies to establish and maintain comprehensive environmental
management programs. Through its participation in the pilot Environmental
Leadership Project, WMX is helping to design the final project, expected to be
proposed in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
Two WMX representatives participated as members of the National Environmental
Justice Advisory Council. The Council was convened by EPA to help EPA and other
federal agencies respond to President Clinton's Environmental Justice Executive
Order, develop strategic plans for each agency and work closely with community
activists to find practical solutions to specific incidents of environmental
inequity.
</P>
<P><A NAME="1"></A></P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d">Support for Environmental Organizations</FONT>
</P>
<P>
WMX works with environmental groups in a variety of ways, ranging from
cooperation on national policy development to hands-on work in the field. CWM
volunteers, for example, planted seedlings to restore a former landing strip at
the Louisiana Nature Conservancy's Little Pecan Island. 
</P>
<P>
WMX also provides financial support to environmental organizations through
several programs. WMX and its  operating groups made grants and charitable
contributions to environmental organizations totaling more than 1 million
dollars in 1995 (see Table 5). Among these gifts was a three-year pledge of
$75,000 by Wheelabrator's Bridgeport, Connecticut plant to fund a series of
interactive exhibits at the Children's Garbage Museum and Education Center of
Southwest Connecticut, housed at a regional recycling center.  <A HREF="95grants.htm"> Press here for more information on WMX environmental grants.</A></P> 
<P>
WMX matches cash gifts from employees in all operating groups on a two-to-one
basis for environmental groups (higher education institutions also receive the
two-to-one match; most other charities are eligible for a one-to-one matching
gift). The Company also contributes a cash match for employees who volunteer
their time to non-profit organizations (the ServiceMatch program).
</P>
<P>
The WMX corporate campus participates in Earth Share, a combined giving campaign
that provides employees a convenient way to donate to environmental groups.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/table5.gif" ALT="Corporate Contributions to Environmental Organizations"></CENTER></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="center"> <BR>
