<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H2>1994 Annual Environmental Report</H2>

<HR SIZE=5>
<H3><B><CENTER>
This Report
</H3></B></CENTER>

This 1994 Annual Environmental Report honors the commitment made five
years ago by the WMX Board of Directors to describe the Company's
environmental activities, evaluate implementation of the Company's
Environmental Policy and make the findings public each year.  A report
providing additional detail is available on request.  The contents of
this report were compiled under the direction of the WMX Executive
Environmental Committee and were reviewed and approved by the Board of
Directors.

<P>

The report encompasses WMX corporate activities and operations of
subsidiaries worldwide.  We invite your comments, feedback and
questions.  Send mail to wmx@va.pubnix.com, use our
<A HREF="commnt95.htm">Web comment form</A>,
or call our toll-free number at 1-800-4WMXNEWS. To encourage your
response, we will provide a donation to Earth Share, a coalition of 43
environmental organizations, for each reply received.

<H3><B><CENTER>
Progress Reports
</H3></B></CENTER>

The report is divided into four main sections, each of which covers
the three or four principles of the Environmental Policy listed.  Each
section begins with a "progress report" summarizing major programs and
their implementation status in the WMX family of companies.  The
symbols indicating implementation status were assigned based on
information submitted by the operating groups regarding their
implementation of the Environmental Policy.  A star indicates that
substantial progress was made in 1994.  The number in parentheses
refers to the principle(s) of the WMX Environmental Policy that the
program supports.  Some programs were developed by operating groups
for their use only and some programs are simply not applicable to all
operating groups.  The absence of particular programs for a group or
limited implementation within the group should be considered with
these points in mind.  We believe that the value of providing more
specific information on programs outweighs constraints on
comparability between groups.

<H3><B><CENTER>
The Cover
</H3></B></CENTER>

Craig Pond, in Barnwell, South Carolina, is one of only two remaining
undisturbed savannah-type Carolina Bays in the state and home to
several rare plant and animal species.  The pond is located on the
property of WMX's Chem-Nuclear Systems, Inc. (CNSI).  In early 1995,
CNSI provided permanent protection for the pond by donating a
conservation easement on 264 acres of land to the South Carolina
Heritage Trust.  CNSI will preserve the pond in a natural state and
continue to use it for educational programs.  More than 700 students
have participated in programs at Craig Pond.


