<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>1995 Annual Environmental Report</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="./art/report/paper.gif">
<P ALIGN="center"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/banner.jpg" ALT="Banner" WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="150"></P>
<P ALIGN="center"><A HREF="pg5.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/previous.gif" ALT="Previous Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="pg9.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/next.gif" ALT="Next Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="contents.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/index.gif" ALT="Index" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A>
</P>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d"><B>PACT: Assessment</B></FONT> <BR>WMX
companies use several tools to assess  compliance with environmental
requirements, including daily inspections by operations personnel, annual 
facility self-audits, monthly management reviews and periodic corporate  audits.
The goal of these programs is identification of all compliance issues by the
Company -  preferably by the immediate management of the facility. Figure 2
shows that  most compliance issues in 1995 were identified by facility
management,  and the percentage of facility-identified issues has increased over
the last  several years.</P></BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BLOCKQUOTE><TABLE ALIGN="CENTER"><TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1"><IMG
SRC="./art/report/bar2.gif" ALT="Compliance Issues"></TD></TR><TR><TD
ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 2<BR><BR></TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><P>
The WMX Environmental Audit Department audits Waste Management, Inc. (WMI), CWM
and Rust International, Inc. (Rust) operations. During 1995, the Environmental
Audit Department conducted 138 audits, the WTI audit program completed 28 audits
and WMI plc conducted 43 (see Figure 3). WMI audit scores are found in Table 1.</P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN="MIDDLE" ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/table1.gif" ALT="WMI Average Environmental Audit Scores">
</TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="MIDDLE" ALIGN="LEFT" COLSTART="1" WIDTH="600"><SMALL>1
The score indicates the percentage of about 40 management areas audited that had
no significant compliance issues identified.     Other WMX subsidiaries do not
use a numerical scoring system for environmental audits.</SMALL>
<BR><SMALL>2 the small number of these facilities audited makes the scores
subject to considerable year-to-year variations.</SMALL></TD></TR>  
</TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE ALIGN="LEFT"><TR><TD COLSTART="1" WIDTH="200"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./art/report/bar3.gif" ALT="Number of Environmental Audits"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN="MIDDLE" ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 3<BR><BR></TD></TR><TR
><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./art/report/bar4.gif" ALT="Compliance Issues"></TD></TR><TR><TD
 ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 4<BR><BR></TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./art/report/bar5.gif" ALT="Penalties for Environmental Matters"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 5</TD></TR>        

</TABLE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Environmental monitoring measures success at preventing releases. WMX
facilities have monitoring programs tailored to their operations. In North
America, all WMI and CWM environmental monitoring   including leachates, surface
water, groundwater, stormwater and air   is coordinated through the WMX
Environmental Monitoring Laboratory (EML) in Geneva, Illinois. In 1995, EML
performed approximately 1.4 million tests on samples from 7,500 monitoring
locations at WMX facilities.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>EML was ranked the number one monitoring laboratory in the U.S.
by Analytical Standards, Inc., an independent testing organization, for the
second quarter of 1995. More than 250 of the nation's top environmental
laboratories have participated in double-blind studies administered by the
organization, which are used by the laboratories to evaluate their own
performance. EML's score of 98.59 out of 100 compared to an average for
participating laboratories of 86.71.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Because of the highly prescriptive regulations governing
hazardous waste  management services, Chemical Waste Management (CWM) also uses
standard division practices - formal  procedures that spell out exactly how
compliance- related tasks are to be done and what training is required.  </P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d"><B>PACT: Corrective Action</B></FONT> WMX
developed and implemented the Compliance Action Reporting System (CARS) to
ensure that compliance issues are promptly rectified. CARS is a software tool
that tracks issues and the steps scheduled to resolve them. CARS also provides
management with information on the status of corrective and preventive actions
and helps to identify common or recurring issues. More than 850 WMX facilities
in the U.S. and Canada have tracked compliance issues in CARS. WMI plc waste
handling facilities use an analogous system to track outstanding issues. </P>
<P>Some of the key indicators tracked by CARS are the percent of issues
self-identified (Figure 2), the percent of issues resolved on schedule (Figure
4), and the number of agency actions (includes administrative complaints or
citations, administrative orders, administrative notices of violation,
administrative warning letters, civil actions and regulatory inspection issues).
Company-wide, the number of agency-identified issues declined 8 percent in 1995
compared to 1994.</P> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d"><B>PACT: Training </B></FONT>
Training is a key part of WMX environmental management systems. During 1995,
nearly 70 percent of WMX operating employees received environmental training.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The WMX Leadership Development Department works with the
operating groups to identify training needs and develop and deliver courses. A
recent focus has been on providing division compliance coordinators and
front-line operations personnel with the environmental awareness training and
specific knowledge and skills needed to maintain environmental, health and
safety compliance.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P> For example, for Wheelabrator, the Leadership Development
Department developed an environmental awareness video and modified existing
courses to emphasize a broad environmental media approach to compliance. WMX
also offers &quot;Landfill University&quot; and &quot;Material Recovery Facility
University&quot;  to train managers in the wide variety of responsibilities of
managing these facilities.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d"><B>Compliance Performance</B></FONT>
 The compliance indicators outlined above show generally favorable results:
audit scores are trending upwards and the percent of compliance issues
identified by facility management has increased steadily in most of the
operating groups.</P>
<P>In 1995, WMX companies paid a total of $785,612 in penalties for 29
environmental matters and three environmentally related transportation matters
(e.g., labeling of truck contents). This is less than the amount paid in 1994
and an improvement over previous years' levels (See Figure 5). Forty-five
percent of the total related to a penalty paid for alleged violations by a
company six years ago, before it was acquired by WMX.   <A HREF="pen.htm">Press here for a description of all issues giving rise to penalties of  more than $10,000. </A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="center"> <BR>
<B>Protecting Human Health and the Environment Continues...</B><BR><A
HREF="pg5.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/previous.gif" ALT="Previous Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
