<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1995 Annual Environmental Report</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="./art/report/paper.gif">
<P ALIGN="center"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/banner.jpg" ALT="Banner" WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="150"></P>
<P ALIGN="center"><A HREF="pg10.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/previous.gif" ALT="Previous Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="pg6.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/next.gif" ALT="Next Page" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A><A
HREF="contents.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./art/report/index.gif" ALT="Index" BORDER="0" WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="30"></A>
</P>
<HR>
<TABLE ALIGN="LEFT"><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./art/report/bar8.gif" ALT="Number of Material Recovery Facilities"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 8</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./art/report/pie9.gif" ALT="Recyclable Materials Handled, North America 1995"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 9</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="RIGHT" SRC="./art/report/pie10.gif" ALT="Recyclable Materials Handled International 1995">
</TD></TR><TR>
<TD ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 10</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><IMG
ALIGN="RIGHT" SRC="./art/report/bar11.gif" ALT="WMI Recycling Marketing Partnerships">
</TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1">Figure 11</TD></TR>      

</TABLE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d"><B>Recycling</B></FONT>  1995
was a record-breaking year in recycling. WMX companies and joint venture
partners worldwide collected, processed and sold more than eight million tons of
recyclable materials.</P>
<P>In the U.S., WMI acquired two companies   Resource Recycling Technologies,
Inc. and New England CRInc   which operate 23 material recovery facilities with
capacity to process 825,000 tons of recyclables each year. Along with new plant
construction, this brought the company's North American network of material
recovery facilities to 172 (see Figure 8). These facilities processed 3,471,000
tons of materials in 1995, 73 percent more than in 1994. Revenues from recycling
increased 72 percent. Wheelabrator's trash-to-energy plants recovered an
additional 179,000 tons of ferrous metals and its Falls Township MRF processed
about 30,000 tons of recyclables (see Figure 9).
</P>
<P>Internationally, the amount of recyclable materials handled and the number
of material recycling facilities (MRFs) operated both increased by 50 percent
during 1995 (see Figures 10 and 8). WMI handled nearly 4.5 million tons of
materials   the majority of which was paper   through its recycling marketing
partnerships for paper, glass, aluminum and steel (see Figure 11).
<BR><BR><BR></P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>In December, 1995 WMI began operating four MRFs serving 750,000
households in Chicago, Illinois. WMI built the MRF's under contract to the City.</P>
<P>Recyclable materials are collected by city sanitation crews in special blue
bags along with household refuse. The  blue bag  system allowed the City to
avoid the expense of an entirely new fleet of collection trucks and work force.
The MRFs were designed to accommodate the blue bag approach and incorporate a
number of advanced features. Despite some initial skepticism about the approach,
in January 1996, the first full month of operation, 8.9 percent of incoming
waste at the processing centers was diverted from disposal. This compares
favorably to other U.S. cities and is well on the way to the 1996 goal of 14.6
percent diversion.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>In Europe and the U.S., WMX companies have developed
partnerships to recycle electronic equipment. WMI plc is working with R. Frazier
Europe and the Dutch Ministry of the Environment on a program to collect,
separate and dismantle reusable computer equipment. The first shipment of
components was sent to China in January. In the UK, WMI plc teamed with R.
Frazier Ltd. to collect, process and remanufacture redundant computers and
telecommunications equipment. Almost 90 percent of the original materials are
retained for use in other items. A similar program began in the U.S. when Sears,
a national account customer, contacted WMI with a problem - how to handle
outmoded cash registers and computer telecommunications equipment at 800 retail
outlets. Rather than offer to dispose of them, WMI teamed with R. Frazier to
develop a program to quickly pick up thousands of pieces of redundant equipment
and find buyers for the equipment or its components. The program generated
revenue for Sears rather than a cost for disposal.</P> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Composting of yard wastes, food wastes and other organic
materials continues to increase. In Sweden, for example, WMI plc expanded a
program with the supermarket chain Grona Konsum to 12 stores. At the pilot
store, recycling and composting of organic  wastes reduced the weekly number of
bags of waste going to the landfill from 70 to one.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>In Indiana, WMI's Blackfoot Recycling and Disposal Facility
operates the only commercial composting site in the state. The facility accepts
about 2,000 tons of compostable materials per month including biosolids, wood
processing and paper manufacturing wastes to produce a high-quality soil
amendment. A second compost operation uses biosolids, kiln dust and lime to
produce a compost useful for reclaiming strip mined areas. The Blackfoot
facility itself is located on land that was previously strip mined. Using the
compost product, Blackfoot managers have reclaimed 800 acres of the strip mined
area.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="00994d"><B> Treatment and Disposal</B></FONT>
 WMI plc's two facilities in Hong Kong won recognition in 1995. Enviropace Ltd.,
WMI plc's joint venture partner, won the 1995 Hong Kong Award for the Industry -
Environmental Performance. Formerly called the Governor's Award for the
Environment, it recognized environmental excellence at the Hong Kong Chemical
Waste Treatment Centre built by Enviropace to handle the hazardous wastes from
Hong Kong's 10,000 small waste generators. </P></BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>The South East New Territories landfill construction project
received the WMX  President's Award for Technical Excellence for the quality of
its construction, the outstanding safety record of the project and its creative
approach to construction challenges. The landfill is now operational and
processes up to 13,000 tons per day of waste diverted from unlined landfills in
the area.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Two WMI landfills won the Solid Waste Association of North
America's 1995 Landfill Excellence Awards. The Venice Park Recycling and
Disposal Facility in Lennon, Michigan won the Gold Award and the Mallard Ridge
Recycling and Disposal facility in Delavan, Wisconsin won the Silver Award. The
Venice Park facility has advanced liner and cover systems, a 1.5-megawatt
landfill gas plant, and an end-use plan that provides for a wildlife nature
park, ski and toboggan slopes, a tree farm, and a greenhouse powered by landfill
gas. The Mallard Ridge facility has a unique program for restoring
environmentally sensitive habitats on its property, including prairie and
wetland areas, and protecting threatened species.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="center"> <BR>
