<HEAD>

<TITLE>WMX - Letter from the Chairman</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Web Builder, 15-May-1995 -->

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.00">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H2>Letter from the Chairman</H2>

<HR SIZE=5><CENTER><IMG SRC="../art/construction.gif"></CENTER><HR SIZE=5>
<P>
To the Reader:
<P>
On March 7, 1990, our Board of Directors adopted a comprehensive
and ambitious environmental policy for our company and all of
its operations worldwide. With the passage of five years, it now
seems appropriate to take stock of the steps we have taken to
implement our Policy and its 14 Principles.
<P>
First, we have developed programs to support specific Principles.
Under our energy Principle, for example, WMX is testing refuse
collection trucks that run on alternative fuels, including landfill
gas. We joined EPA's voluntary Green Lights program to upgrade
our lighting systems to reduce energy use and air pollution. Under
our Principle of "no net loss of wetlands or other biodiversity
on company properties," we are demonstrating a unique approach
to protecting, and frequently restoring, natural ecosystems at
waste facility properties. This WMX Annual Environmental Report
outlines programs implementing each of the Principles of the Policy
in 1994.
<P>
Second, we are integrating the Environmental Policy into key business
processes. All of our top managers with line responsibility, including
myself, are evaluated for our performance in implementing the
Policy. During 1994, each of our business units began reporting
on additional performance measures under the Policy. This report
includes, for the first time, information based on these measures,
such as a summary of our impacts on wetlands. As we continue to
refine them, we will report on additional measures in the future.
<P>
Similarly, in the compliance area, we have placed considerable
importance and resources on programs that provide our front-line
managers with the tools and incentives to prevent, detect and
correct environmental compliance issues, and that hold these managers
directly accountable for compliance. In 1995 we are expanding
these systems for compliance planning, measurement and evaluation
to include the entire environmental policy. One step in this direction
is a joint project of WMX and the Oregon Department of Environmental
Quality which was selected by the U.S. EPA as an "Environmental
Leadership Project." The project's purpose is to demonstrate
our environmental compliance and excellence programs and innovative
approaches to agency enforcement.
<P>
Third, we emphasize that implementing the environmental policy
is the responsibility of all employees. We have trained employees
and conducted awareness campaigns. In 1994, for example, I presented
the first Chairman's' Award for Environmental Excellence, an award
specifically developed to recognize outstanding employee initiatives
in upholding Policy.
<P>
These steps represent important progress, but we recognize that
more remains to be done. Successful programs must spread even
further throughout our family of companies and we must continually
reexamine and refine our approaches. We will know we have really
achieved success when we have moved from managing programs to
having our Environmental Principles the foundation for our environmental
culture. In this report, we present for the first time "progress
reports" that summarize the extent of our efforts to implement
various programs under our Environmental Policy at our corporate
offices and major subsidiaries. We think they help to show the
many outstanding programs we have developed to fulfill our pledge
and also areas where we need to place more emphasis. I hope you
find this report helpful and invite your comments on it.
<P>
Dean L. Buntrock<BR>
Chairman of the Board and Chief Executive Officer
<HR>

