<HEAD>

<TITLE>WMX - Protecting Human Health and the Environment</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Web Builder, 17-May-1995 -->

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.00">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H2>Protecting Human Health and the Environment</H2>

<HR SIZE=5><I>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
This section covers WMX programs implementing principles one, two, six
and seven of the WMX Environmental Policy that address protecting
human health and the environment: 

<A HREF="#1">environmental management and compliance</A>,
<A HREF="#2">health and safety programs</A>,
<A HREF="#3">the employee hotline</A>,
<A HREF="#4">reducing wastes and emissions at our own facilities</A>, and 
<A HREF="#5">providing environmental services</A>.
</FONT>

<DL>
	<DT><B>Principles Addressed in this Section</B>
		<DD><B>1. Environmental Protection and Enhancement</B><BR>
The Company is committed to improving the environment through the
services that we offer and to providing our services in a manner
demonstrably protective of human health and the environment, even if
not required by law.  We will minimize and strive not to allow any
releases to the atmosphere, land, or water in amounts that may harm
human health and the environment.  We will train employees to enhance
understanding of environmental policies and to promote excellence in
job performance on all environmental matters.

		<DD><P><B>2. Waste Reduction, Recycling, Treatment, and Disposal</B><BR>
The Company will work to minimize the volume and toxicity of waste
generated by us and others.  We will operate internal recycling
programs.  We will vigorously pursue opportunities to recycle waste
before other management practices are applied.  The Company will use
and provide environmentally safe treatment and disposal services for
waste that is not eliminated at the source or recycled.

		<DD><P><B>6. Compliance</B><BR>
The Company is committed to comply with all legal requirements and to
implement programs and procedures to ensure compliance.  These efforts
will include training and testing of employees, rewarding employees
who excel in compliance, and disciplining employees who violate legal
requirements.

		<DD><P><B>7. Risk Reduction</B><BR>
The Company will operate in a manner designed to minimize
environmental, health or safety hazards.  We will minimize risk and
protect our employees and others in the vicinity of our operations by
employing safe technologies and operating procedures and by being
prepared for emergencies.  The Company will make available to our
employees and to the public information related to any of our
operations that we believe cause environmental harm or pose health or
safety hazards.  The Company will encourage employees to report any
condition that creates a danger to the environment or poses health or
safety hazards and will provide confidential means for them to do so.

</DL></I>

<HR WIDTH=75% SIZE=5><P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../art/report/protecting.gif" ALT="[TABLE: Progress Report: Protecting Human Health and the Environment]"></CENTER>

<A NAME="1">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Environmental Management and Compliance
</H3></B></CENTER>

WMX's organizational structure includes environmental experts
in all operating groups. Management has emphasized that all employees
are responsible for upholding and implementing the Company's Environmental
Policy. Incentives for managers reinforce this philosophy. The
compensation of WMX's chief executive officer and president, the
presidents of each principal operating group and all general managers
depends in part on the environmental performance of units for
which they are responsible.

<P>
WMX has developed detailed environmental policies, directives and
guidance and compliance programs built on the "Prevent, Assess,
Correct and Train" (PACT) framework discussed below. WMX's emphasis on
providing managers with sophisticated systems to prevent environmental
compliance issues is, we believe, unique among U.S. companies.

<P>
To provide an independent assessment of the Company's environmental
policies and management systems, WMX retained Arthur D. Little,
Inc. to review programs in place during 1994 at WMX and its principal
operating subsidiaries. The firm concluded:

<P>
<I><BLOCKQUOTE>
"In our opinion, WMX Technologies, Inc.'s corporate and
subsidiary environmental management systems place it among the
leaders of industry as a whole with regard to corporate environmental
management."
</BLOCKQUOTE></I>

<A NAME="1.1">
<P>
<B>PACT: PREVENTION</B><P>

<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig1.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 1: CMS: Total Installations]">

The cornerstone of WMX preventive compliance programs is the
Compliance Management System (CMS), installed at 534 WMX divisions,
including all WMI landfills, hauling companies and material recovery
facilities and all major CWM facilities (see Figure 1). CMS is a
personal computer software tool that translates into discrete tasks
all environmental requirements in legislation, regulations, permits or
Company policies that apply to a particular facility. CMS allows
managers to schedule tasks, assign them to facility staff and track
their completion. WMI plc uses an analogous COMPASS program, while WTI
facilities have an Obligations Management System available for their
use.

<P>
Because of the highly prescriptive regulations governing hazardous
waste management services, CWM also uses standard division practices
-- formal procedures that spell out exactly how compliance-related
tasks are to be done and what training is required.

<P>
Even more fundamental than providing compliance tools is appointing
and training front-line compliance managers. A key WMI initiative in
this area was the appointment and training of Division Compliance
Coordinators (DCCs) at all WMI divisions (in addition to environmental
experts previously assigned). More than 550 people were trained in
regulatory requirements, Company policies and the use of CMS.  Several
groups also developed DCC certification programs which include
testing.

<P>
Similarly, WMI plc assigned an environmental compliance coordinator to
each waste handling facility. Within WTI, field environmental
compliance directors were appointed for all business units, based at
facilities or regionally, depending on the scope of the operations
covered.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<A NAME="1.2">
<P>
<B>PACT: ASSESSMENT</B><P>

<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig2.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 2: Compliance Issues--Percent Identified By:]">

<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig3.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 3: Number of Environmental Audits]">

<P>
WMX uses several approaches to assess compliance with environmental
requirements. Ideally, all compliance issues should be identified and
addressed by facility management. Figure 2 shows that most compliance
issues in 1994 were identified by facility management and the
percentage of facility-identified issues has increased.

<P>
The WMX Environmental Audit Department audits WMI, CWM and Rust
operations. During 1994, the Department continued to report to the
Vice President for Law and Compliance to ensure independence from the
audited groups. The Department also reports on programs and
performance to the Audit Committee of the WMX Board of Directors,
composed of outside directors. In early 1994, the Department
established auditing standards applicable to all WMX business groups.

<P>
During 1994, the Environmental Audit Department conducted 120 audits,
while the WTI audit program did 20 audits and six legal reviews (see
Figure 3). WMI audit scores are found in table 1.  WMI plc uses its
COVER program to generate audit and inspection checklists and audit
reports. During 1994, 67 COVER audits were completed, representing 82
percent of facilities.

<P>
WMX also monitors emissions from its facilities which might impact the
environment. All land disposal facilities have well-established
groundwater monitoring programs, and water from facility monitoring
wells is evaluated periodically in the WMX Environmental Monitoring
Laboratories in Geneva, Illinois.
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<CENTER>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/table1.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[TABLE 1: WMI Environmental Audit Scores]">
</CENTER>

<A NAME="1.3">
<P>
<B>PACT: CORRECTIVE ACTION</B><P>

<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig4.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 4: Compliance Issues--Percent Resolved on Schedule]">

WMX developed and implemented the Compliance Action Reporting System
(CARS) to ensure that compliance issues are promptly rectified.  CARS,
and the analogous COVER program of WMI plc, are software tools that
track issues and the steps scheduled to resolve them.  CARS also
provides management with information on the status of corrective and
preventive actions. More than 850 WMX facilities in the U.S. and
Canada have tracked compliance issues in CARS.  COVER is used to track
the outstanding issues at all WMI plc waste handling facilities.

<P>
Some of the key indicators tracked by CARS are the percent of issues
self-identified (Figure 2), the percent of issues resolved on schedule
(Figure 4) and the number of agency actions. For both WMI and CWM, the
number of agency actions increased in 1994, 43 percent and 20 percent,
respectively (see discussion below). For WTI and WMI plc, agency
actions decreased 61 percent and 56 percent respectively.

<A NAME="1.4">
<P>
<B>PACT: TRAINING</B><P>

Recurring issues identified by CARS and other mechanisms become the
basis for focusing the training program on areas most in need of
improvement. WMX has developed a "compliance curriculum" available to
all facilities that covers the requirements of various regulatory
programs. WMX also offers "Landfill University" and "Material Recovery
Facility University" to train managers in the wide variety of
responsibilities of managing these facilities.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<A NAME="1.5">
<P>
<B>COMPLIANCE PERFORMANCE</B><P>

The compliance indicators outlined above show generally improving
trends:

<UL>
<LI>WMI audit scores are improving, especially for hauling companies.

<P><LI>The emphasis on self-identification of compliance issues
appears to be working, with improvements in all groups and a
significant increase in CWM's rate of issue self-identification.

<P><LI>There is steady progress in the rate of issues resolved on
schedule.
</UL>

<P>
However, CWM and WMI were subject to more agency actions than in 1993,
which is reflected in a higher percentage of externally identified
issues for WMI. This appears to be based on better internal reporting
by facilities of less formal agency actions and increased inspections
by regulatory agencies.

<P>
In 1994, WMX companies paid a total of $896,815 in penalties for 65
environmental matters and 10 environmentally related transportation
matters (e.g., labeling of truck contents). This is less than was paid
in 1993 and an improvement over previous years' levels (See Figure
5). We will continue working vigorously to reduce them further. A
description of all issues giving rise to penalties of more than
$10,000 is included in the more detailed Environmental Report.

<CENTER><P>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig5.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 5: Penalties for Environmental Matters]">
</CENTER>

<A NAME="2">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Health and Safety Programs
</H3></B></CENTER>

WMX facilities have comprehensive policies, procedures and programs to
identify and reduce health and safety risks. In addition, each
facility is required to maintain a comprehensive plan for response to
emergencies. Major initiatives in 1994 included:

<UL>
	<LI>WMI completed a comprehensive update of its Safety and
Health Program, including development of a new Safety and Health
Program Manual. Tasks identified in the manual were provided for use
in CMS.

	<P><LI>CWM continued progress in its Process Safety Management
program.


	<P><LI>WMI provided each of its facilities with videos and
training guides for "Employee Right To Know," "Smith System Defensive
Driving," and the "Keys To Safe Driving"-- the latter two programs
customized for the particular challenges of driving a refuse truck.
 

	<P><LI>WMI plc developed its Safety Management System during
1994. The system provides consistent measurements of health and safety
performance and implements the Company's safety policy.


	<P><LI>WTI developed a crisis management manual, distributed
it to all plants and provided corresponding training to regional
offices.
</UL>

<P>
Each WMX subsidiary collects and reports performance measurements
to senior management and reports safety statistics as required
to the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Administration. Figures
6 and 7 indicate that performance of WMX companies has been consistently
better than industry averages and has generally improved over
the past several years.

<CENTER><P>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig6.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 6: OSHA Recordable Injury Rate 1994]">

<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig7.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 7: OSHA Lost Workday 1994]">
</CENTER>

<A NAME="3">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Employee Hotline
</H3></B></CENTER>

WMX provides employees with a confidential hotline to address
workplace issues that have not been resolved by local management.
More than 1,000 calls were received on the HelpLine in 1994. Only
12 of these involved an environmental issue, and none involved
major issues or environmental releases. All callers were informed
of the matter's disposition.

<A NAME="4">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Reducing Our Own Wastes and Emissions
</H3></B></CENTER>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig8.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 8: CWM: Pounds of Hazardous Waste Generated Per Ton of Waste Managed]">
</CENTER>

<P>
WMX companies generate wastes in the course of providing environmental
services. Most locations recycle at least some portion of wastes
generated.

<P>
Eighteen CWM facilities (including all landfills, stabilization
treatment plants and transfer facilities) reduced their rate of
hazardous waste generation by 71 percent compared to 1993 (see
Figure 8). The rate for CWM facilities companywide, including
incinerators and resource recovery facilities, was tracked beginning
in 1994. This rate was 151 pounds of hazardous waste generated
per ton of waste managed, reflecting the ash produced at hazardous
waste incinerators.

<P>
Only three WMX facilities are manufacturers required to report
under the SARA Title III Toxic Release Inventory (see Table 2).
Overall emissions from WMX facilities increased during 1993 primarily
because of increased production at the Demopolis, Alabama facility
which builds waste containers. Johnson Screens recycled 30 percent
less scrap because of lower production but also reduced hazardous
waste generation by 58 percent by switching to nonhazardous solvents
and improving management of solvent waste.

<P><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/table2.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[TABLE 2: TRI Information]">
</CENTER>

<A NAME="5">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Providing Environmental Services
</H3></B></CENTER>

As stated in Principle 1, WMX "is committed to improving the
environment through the services that we offer."

<P>
Remediation and pollution prevention projects in 1994 included:

<UL>
	<LI>Rust continues to help the federal government clean up
military and nuclear weapons facilities throughout the U.S. It is a
member of the Lockheed Idaho Technologies Company that won a contract
in 1994 to manage and operate the 890-square-mile Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory and is managing all waste management and
environmental restoration programs. Rust also carried out remedial
investigation and design projects at more than a dozen military
installations under several long-term environmental services
contracts.

	<P><LI>WMI plc completed three remediation projects at oil
refineries -- the first environmental cleanups ever undertaken in
Singapore.

	<P><LI>Through its engineering and construction business, Rust
focuses on minimizing emissions from industrial facilities. One such
example during 1994 was Rust's design of an expansion for a chemical
plant which will cut vinyl chloride emissions by more than 90 percent
while increasing production efficiency and doubling plant capacity.

</UL>

<A NAME="5.1">
<P>
<B>CLEAN WATER</B>

Wheelabrator continues to provide services to manage water, wastewater
and biosolids in the United State.  In partnership with Compania
Mexicana de Aguas, S.A. de C.V. (CMA), Wheelabrator is managing the
Lecheria Wastewater Treatment Plant in the Metropolitan Area of Mexico
City. Rust is providing continuous engineering for the facility. The
project reclaims and treats wastewater, then markets the clean water
to industries and businesses in the Northern Area of Mexico City,
increasing the availability of potable water for domestic use.


<A NAME="5.2">
<P>
<B>RECYCLING</B><P>
1994 was a banner year for recycling. By year-end, WMX companies
operated 165 material recovery facilities worldwide (see Figure
9). The number of recycling customers continued to climb (see
Figure 10).

<P>
WMI handled more than 4.1 million tons of materials through its
recycling marketing partnerships (see Figure 11). Its Container
Recycling Alliance broke ground for a new 100,000-ton-per-year
glass processing facility in Franklin, Massachusetts.

<P>
Some of the innovative recycling projects pursued included:

<UL>
	<LI>WMI plc and a leading Swedish supermarket chain introduced
a pilot waste sorting program which resulted in 97 percent of the
waste generated by the supermarket being recycled.<BR>


	<P><LI>WMI and the Nova Group, Inc. formed a partnership to
create the Green Hanger Program, a convenient and cost effective way
for clothing retailers to recycle plastics. The program recycles
plastic hangers, garment bags and pallet wrap, which typically account
for 25 to 40 percent of the waste stream of a clothing retailer after
cardboard recycling.

	<P><LI>In 1994, Rust provided engineering and construction
services for five paper recycling facilities -- continuing to lead the
industry.  Its experience includes designing or building facilities
providing 63 percent of the mixed office waste paper deinking capacity
in the U.S.
</UL>

<P>
Recycling also began to fulfill its promise as a way to spur economic
development. In addition to the Davis Street Station project (see
profile), WMI is developing a partnership with GRIDCORE in Long Beach
in one of California's Recycling Market Development Zones.  WMI is
providing promotion assistance and supplying a steady stream of raw
materials to GRIDCORE, which recycles paper into a strong replacement
for fiberboard or plywood. Another facility in the zone is providing a
market for plastics.

<CENTER><P>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig10.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 10: Number of Recycling Customers]">

<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig11.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 11: Recycling: Tons Marketed]">
</CENTER>

<A NAME="5.3">
<P>
<B>TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL</B><P>
Enviropace, the chemical waste treatment plant built by a WMI plc
partnership and operated on behalf of the Hong Kong Government,
completed its first full year of operation in mid-1994. The facility
has reached its boilerplate capacity and is now processing 100,000
metric tons of waste annually from Hong Kong's 10,000 small hazardous
waste generators. Also in Hong Kong, a WMX joint venture, Green Valley
Limited, received the first shipments of waste at the South-East New
Territories Landfill in Tseung Kwan O, part of a network of new
environmental management facilities planned by the government to meet
Hong Kong's environmental infrastructure needs.

<P>
In May, Indonesia's President Soeharto officially opened the country's
first hazardous waste treatment center, designed and built by
WMI plc and owned jointly with PT. Bimantara Citra and the Indonesian
Government. The facility began receiving waste in January and
includes a secure landfill, a stabilization unit and a synthetic
fuels blending unit.

<P>
In Scotland, WMI plc officially opened the refurbished hazardous
liquid waste treatment plant at Twecher. The plant is Scotland's
first integrated facility for industrial wastes generated by the
engineering, electronics, pharmaceutical and chemical industries.

<P><HR>
<CENTER><B><I>Putting it to Work:</B>
<A HREF="protecting-work.html">Recycling in Full Swing</A></I></CENTER>
<HR>

