<HEAD>

<TITLE>WMX - Conserving Nature And Natural Resources</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Web Builder, 17-May-1995 -->

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.00">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H2>Conserving Nature And Natural Resources</H2>

<HR SIZE=5><I>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
This section covers principles three, four and five of the WMX
Environmental Policy through which WMX conserves nature and natural
resources:
<A HREF="#1">conserving wetlands and biodiversity</A>, 
<A HREF="#2">buying recycled products</A>, and 
<A HREF="#3">saving and generating energy</A>.
</FONT>

<DL>
	<DT><B>Principles Addressed in this Section</B>

		<DD><B>3. Biodiversity</B><BR> 
The Company is committed to the conservation of nature.  We will
implement a policy of a "no net loss" of wetlands or other biological
diversity on the Company's property.

		<DD><P><B>4. Sustainable Use of Natural Resources</B><BR>
The Company will use renewable natural resources, such as water,
soils, and forests, in a sustainable manner and will offer services
to make degraded resources once again usable.  We will conserve
nonrenewable natural resources through efficient use and careful
planning.

		<DD><P><B>5. Wise Use of Energy</B><BR>
The Company will make every reasonable effort to use environmentally
safe and sustainable energy sources to meet our needs.  We will seek
opportunities to improve energy efficiency and conservation in our
operations.

</DL></I>

<HR WIDTH=75% SIZE=5><P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../art/report/conserving.gif" ALT="[TABLE: Progress Report: Conserving Nature and Natural Resources]"></CENTER>

<A NAME="1">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Conserving Wetlands and Biodiversity
</H3></B></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig12.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 12: Acres of Wetlands Affected 1994]">

WMX has made a unique commitment to "no net loss of wetlands or other
biodiversity" on its properties.  No models for pursuing such a
commitment on private lands existed, so WMI and Rust developed a
systematic approach embodied in a detailed guidance manual for
biodiversity planning at Company facilities.  About 50 sites were
identified for preparation of inventories and plans before major new
construction or expansion.  Plans have been completed for four WMI
sites (including 
<A HREF="conserving-work.html">Mallard Ridge</A>); another five are in
process.  Six sites are undergoing a less formal planning process.

<P>
Results demonstrate the value of the WMX approach for voluntary
conservation of biological resources: the studies found
opportunities to conserve, and in some cases, restore, biological resources while allowing economic activity to proceed.
 For example, at the Cedar Hollow Recycling and Disposal Facility
(RDF) in Owensville, Missouri, the biodiversity study found a stand of
relatively rare transitional cedar forest that would have been cleared
for landfill expansion since it was not legally protected.  Under the
biodiversity management plan, facility managers will clear a more
common forest type, excavate soil to create the shallow soil
conditions favored by the cedars and replant trees removed from the
expansion area.  The excavated soil will be used to meet the site's
need for additional soil cover in a cost-effective way.

<P>
During 1994, WMX companies met their goal of "no net loss" of
wetlands, creating or restoring 2.4 acres of wetlands for each acre
filled (see Figure 12).  At the largest wetlands project at Outer Loop
RDF in Louisville, Kentucky, construction of a landfill resulted in
the filling of 75.8 acres of wetlands.  To mitigate the fill, WMI
consultants restored 290 farmed acres of former wetlands by recreating
wetland hydrology, building three ponds and planting 140,000
bottomland hardwood trees.

<P>
Chem-Nuclear Systems, Inc. (CNSI) in Barnwell, South Carolina donated
conservation easement to the South Carolina Heritage Trust program in
early 1995 to protect a 264-acre property that includes rare wetlands.
The area covered by the easement, which legally prevents present and
future owners from developing the property, includes one of only two
remaining undisturbed savannah-type Carolina Bays in the state.  CNSI
has also worked with schools throughout the state to create
educational programs using Craig Pond.  More than 700 students have
participated.
 
<P>
In 1990, WMI pledged to plant one million trees by the year 2000.  To
date, WMI divisions have planted or sponsored the planting of more
than 761,000 trees.

<A NAME="2">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Buying Recycled Products
</H3></B></CENTER>

In 1994, WMX's Purchasing Department spent $114 million on goods
containing recycled material, including steel in trucks and roll-off
containers, plastic in recycling and trash containers and office
paper.  The total spent on goods containing recycled material
was less than in 1993.  However, the percent of the capital budget
for containers and vehicles (which accounts for most of the recycled
content purchases) spent on products containing recycled material
increased (see Figure 13).  More than 98 percent of the paper
purchased centrally by WMX had recycled content.  

<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig13.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 13: Purchase of Goods with Recycled Content]">
</CENTER>

<A NAME="3">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Saving and Generating Energy
</H3></B></CENTER>

<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig14.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 14: Energy Generation]">

WMX companies produce power from various unconventional fuels.
Facilities in North America, Sweden and the United Kingdom have a
combined capacity of 990 megawatts.  In 1994, these facilities
generated 5.8 billion kilowatt-hours of electricity (see Figure 14)
and over one million Btus in gas sales.

<A NAME="3.1">
<P>
<B>LANDFILL GAS TO ENERGY</B><P>
WMX companies worldwide operate 34 landfill gas-to-energy plants
-- more than any other company.  In addition, six facilities in
the United States process landfill gas and sell it as a medium-Btu
fuel to industries as a replacement for natural gas, coal or oil.
 
<A NAME="3.2">
<P>
<B>TRASH TO ENERGY AND SMALL POWER PRODUCTION</B><P>
In 1994, Wheelabrator Environmental Systems' 15 trash-to-energy plants
in the United States processed 7.2 million tons of trash, generating
3.8 billion kilowatt-hours of electricity.  During 1994, Wheelabrator
opened a new 53-megawatt plant in Falls Township, Pennsylvania.  The
facility is the first privately initiated project in the solid waste
industry to provide both full-scale recycling, through a material
recovery facility and the recovery of energy on the same site.

<P>
WMI plc runs one of the only privately operated trash-to-energy
facilities outside North America.  The facility, in Hamm, Germany,
was upgraded in 1994 to meet, and, for certain parameters, operate
well below stringent emission limits scheduled to take effect
in 1996.

<P>
Wheelabrator operates six small power facilities with a total
installed capacity of 183 megawatts.  In 1994, the Ridge Generating
Station began operations in Polk County, Florida, the first power
plant in the country fueled by wood waste, scrap tires and landfill
gas.

<A NAME="3.3">
<P>
<B>ALTERNATIVE FUELS</B><P>
Waste Management is testing alternative fuels -- including landfill
gas -- for its fleet of nearly 19,000 collection vehicles and heavy
equipment.  In Buenos Aires, 65 light-duty trucks run on natural gas,
and demonstration and pilot projects are under way involving 25
collection trucks in the United States.

<UL>
	<LI> In a truly closed loop process, WMI has contracted with
ECOGAS of Austin, Texas to build, install and operate a demonstration
plant which will produce liquid natural gas and compressed natural gas
from methane gas generated at company landfills.  This waste-derived
fuel will initially power four solid waste collection vehicles, two of
which are currently running on natural gas.

	<P><LI>Waste Management of Orange County has been awarded a grant
from the South Coast Air Quality Management District to demonstrate
the use of natural gas engines in heavy duty solid waste collection
trucks.  By July 1996, the fleet of 14 trucks serving Mission Viejo,
California will be converted to natural gas engines and to compressed
natural gas fueling systems.
</UL>

<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig15.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 15: CWM Fleet Fuel Efficiency]">

<A NAME="3.4">
<P>
<B>ENERGY-EFFICIENT TRANSPORTATION</B><P>

CWM's fleet fuel economy continues to improve (see Figure 15).  WMI
developed the WMS system, which uses compact, maneuverable, collection
vehicles, exchangeable containers and long-distance "transporters" to
collect and move trash.  The system is about 40 percent more fuel
efficient than conventional equipment.  About 350 WMS units are in use
in the United States, Sweden and the Netherlands.

<P>
In Seattle, WMI operates the nation's first containerized rail-haul
system, shipping the city's trash to WMI's Columbia Ridge Landfill in
Oregon.  Rail-haul is more fuel-efficient and generates significantly
less air pollution than truck transportation.

<A NAME="3.5">
<P>
<B>BUILDINGS AND OPERATIONS</B><P>
As a partner in the U.S. EPA's Green Lights program, WMX has completed
surveys of 11 corporate and group office headquarters.  Green Lights
has been implemented at Rust's Geotech facility in Grand Junction,
Colorado, saving more than 28,000 kilowatt hours of electricity per
year.  Wheelabrator Technologies' corporate office in Hampton, New
Hampshire reduced its lighting load by more than 55 percent in 1994 by
converting to high-efficiency equipment.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P><HR>
<CENTER><B><I>Putting it to Work:</B>
<A HREF="conserving-work.html">Restoring Prairie During Landfill Construction</A></I></CENTER>
