<HEAD>

<TITLE>WMX - Restoring Prairie During Landfill</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Web Builder, 17-May-1995 -->

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.00">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H2>Restoring Prairie During Landfill</H2>
<HR SIZE=5>

<IMG SRC="../art/report/landfill.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 ALT="[IMAGE: WMI's Mallard Ridge Recycling and Disposal Facility in Delevan, Wisconsin]">

The largest prairie restoration ever attempted in the State of
Wisconsin is under way at WMI's Mallard Ridge Recycling and Disposal
Facility in Delevan.  More than 450 acres are being restored to native
plant communities to create habitat for three threatened species.

<P>
When WMI sought to expand the landfill in 1988, studies revealed
the presence of wetlands, three state-protected reptiles  -- the
Blanding Turtle, the Queen Snake and the Eastern Massasauga Rattlesnake
-- and unusual plant communities, including 166 acres of oak savannas
and three acres of calcareous fens and southern sedge meadow.


<P>
Rust consultants, working with the Wisconsin Department of
Natural Resources, developed an extensive Ecological Restoration
and Enhancement plan that calls for enhancing the savannas and
fens, restoring prairie species on land previously used for farming
and mining and establishing native grasses.  The plan also enhances
wetlands for turtle habitat, monitors migration patterns and provides
protection for the animals and their nesting sites during construction.

<P>
Landfill construction has proceeded without harm to the turtles and
snakes.  In fact, the restoration activities are increasing
biodiversity by improving the extent and diversity of native habitat
areas on the property.  This project won a WMX Chairman's Award for
Environmental Excellence.

<P><HR>
