<HEAD>

<TITLE>WMX - Leadership</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Web Builder, 17-May-1995 -->

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.00">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H2>Leadership</H2>

<HR SIZE=5><I>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
This section covers principles 9, 10, 11 and 12 of the WMX
Environmental Policy through which WMX has committed to lead by
example and through partnerships with other organizations: 

<A HREF="#1">research and development</A>, 
<A HREF="#2">community involvement</A>, 
<A HREF="#3">environmental education</A>,
<A HREF="#4">public policy development</A>, and 
<A HREF="#5">support for environmental organizations</A>.
</FONT>

<DL>
	<DT><B>Principles Addressed in this Section</B>
		<DD><B>9. Research and Development</B>
The Company will research, develop, and implement technologies for
integrated waste management.

		<DD><P><B>10. Public Policy</B><BR>
The Company will provide information to and will assist the public in
understanding the environmental impacts of our activitites.  We will
conduct public tours of facilities, consistent with safety
requirements, and will work with communities near our facilities to
encourage dialogue and exchange of information activities.

		<DD><P><B>11. Public Education</B><BR>
The Company will encourage its employees to participate in and to
support the work of environmental organizations, and we will provide
support to environmental organizations for the advancement of
environmental protection.

		<DD><P><B>12. Participation in Environmental Organizations</B><BR>
The Company will encourage its employees to participate in and to
support the work of environmental organizations, and we will provide
support to environmental organizations for the advancement of
environmental protection.
</DL></I>

<HR WIDTH=75% SIZE=5><P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../art/report/leadership.gif" ALT="[TABLE: Progress Report: Leadership]"></CENTER>

<A NAME="1">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Research and Development
</H3></B></CENTER>

WMX's research and development efforts are led by Rust's Clemson
Technical Center, a joint program with Clemson University. The
Center's projects focus on various waste management challenges,
including development of treatment methods for cleaning up military
installations contaminated with mixed radioactive and hazardous waste.
For example, the Center adapted and demonstrated a freeze purification
process for separating salts from highly radioactive waste, a
necessary step prior to final stabilization of the waste in a glassy
form.  Other projects included:

<P>
Evaluating and developing microbial mats for biological treatment of
aqueous wastes, including landfill leachate.

<P>
Installing VAC*TRAX(<B><I>sm</I></B>), a vacuum-enhanced thermal desorption
technology, at the U.S. Department of Energy's Rocky Flats Plant.

<P>
Other WMX companies carried out research and development worldwide:

<P>
WTI tested biofilters for controlling air emissions and developed an
environmentally sound system of mechanical and chemical measures to
control the growth of zebra mussels, a non-native mollusk that clogs
municipal and industrial water systems.

<P>
WMI provided grants to its operating groups to carry out research and
development on innovative technologies, including feasibility studies
at several closed landfills to examine the potential of wind power
generation.

<P>
In Italy, engineers tested a reverse osmosis system as a way to treat
hazardous wastewater and developed a cost-effective and
environmentally sound system for managing small batteries.

<P>
Rust also organizes an annual WMX technology conference that brings
together professionals from the family of companies to share
experiences with emerging technologies.

<A NAME="2">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Community Involvement
</H3></B></CENTER>

During 1994, WMX developed a "Good Neighbor Policy" to
articulate its commitment to the communities in which it operates.
The policy includes a pledge to consult with host communities when
planning business activities and to provide information about facility
operations. It commits to hiring a diverse local workforce and
participating in community activities.  For example, WMI is providing
$500,000 and other corporate resources to build a new health clinic in
Chicago's South Side Altgeld Gardens neighborhood near a WMI facility.
The new clinic will allow the programs currently operated by the
Clinic in Altgeld to expand and other needed services to be
coordinated for the community.

<A NAME="3">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Environmental Education
</H3></B></CENTER>

WMX facilities are popular destinations for educational tours
and field trips.  During 1994, for example, more than 69,000 people
visited WMX facilities (see table 3).  WMX facilities from California
to Australia have begun building education centers on-site to
better serve visitors.  

<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/table3.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[TABLE 3: Tours and Presentations 1994]">
</CENTER>

<P>
It is important to WMX, as well as to the broader community, to
develop a diverse group of young people interested in technical and
environmental careers.  For five years, WMX has supported the
Environmental Careers Organization in its programs to promote minority
student interest in the environment as a career opportunity.  WMX
employees also volunteer as school speakers, judge science and
environmental fairs, teach about recycling, work on Earth Day projects
and serve as technical consultants for environmental curriculum
development.

<P>
Our most notable ambassador to children is "Cycler," a
remote-controlled robot in constant demand for school assemblies,
trade shows, science fairs, open houses and community hearings.
Cycler uses educational tapes featuring rock and roll, country/western
and rap music themes to teach youngsters recycling in "languages"
familiar to them.  WMX companies worldwide have more than 40 Cyclers
that have reached hundreds of thousands of youngsters and robotophile
grownups.

<P>
WMX companies support many environmental education programs. 
For example, divisions throughout the U.S. sponsored more than
23,000 subscriptions to Earth Preservers, an award- winning monthly
environmental newspaper for grades four through eight.

<A NAME="4">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Public Policy Development 
</H3></B></CENTER>

WMX promotes and supports public policy that is protective of the
environment.  Company involvement in governmental policy is managed by
the government affairs programs of WMX, with staff in Washington,
D.C., Oak Brook, several United States state capitals, London and
Brussels.

<P>
The European Union has had an ambitious agenda of harmonizing,
and often strengthening, regulations governing the management
of solid and hazardous wastes, including landfill standards, incineration
of hazardous waste and packaging waste.  WMI plc has participated
actively in developing these initiatives.  WMI plc also submitted
detailed public policy recommendations to the Government of Thailand
on more stringent hazardous waste regulations.

<P>
In the United States, WMX contributed to several important public
policy initiatives:

<UL>
	<LI>WMX supports reauthorization and reform of Superfund to
sustain its benefits in cleaning up waste sites and providing
incentives for proper waste handling while making cleanups faster,
less expensive and more equitably implemented.  WMX Chairman Dean
Buntrock served on the National Commission on Superfund, a broad-based
consensus group which developed a comprehensive proposal for Superfund
reform which was the basis for the Superfund Reform Act of 1994.
Although the bill did not pass in the 103rd Congress, WMX continues to
seek practical solutions to Superfund Reform with a diverse group of
stakeholders.

	<P><LI>In 1994, two WMX representatives were selected as
members of the National Environmental Justice Advisory Council
convened by EPA to help EPA and other federal agencies respond to
President Clinton's Environmental Justice Executive Order, develop
strategic plans for each agency and work closely with community
activists to find practical solutions to specific incidents of
environmental inequity.


	<P><LI>In March of 1994, the Supreme Court ruled that ash
residue from the combustion of municipal waste in trash-to-energy
plants may be subject to regulation as a hazardous waste.  WMX has
long held that ash can safely be managed in well-operated municipal
waste landfills or monofills.  WMX worked with environmental advocacy
groups, local governments and U.S. EPA to fashion an acceptable
legislative proposal, many elements of which were incorporated by EPA
in its regulatory decision on ash management announced in January
1995.
</UL>

<A NAME="5">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Support for Environmental Organizations
</H3></B></CENTER>

WMX worked with environmental groups on many efforts in 1994, ranging
from cooperation on national policy development to hands-on work in
the field.

<P>
WMX also provides financial support to environmental organizations
through several programs.  WMX and its operating groups made grants
and charitable contributions to environmental organizations totalling
$1,736,650 in 1994 (see Table 4).

<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/table4.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[TABLE 4: Corporate Contributions ($)]">
</CENTER>

<P>
The Company matches employee cash gifts on a two-to-one basis
for environmental groups (one-to-one for other charities).  The
Company also contributes a cash match for employees who volunteer
their time to non-profit organizations (the Servicematch program).

<P>
The WMX corporate campus participates in Earth Share, a combined
giving campaign that provides employees a convenient way to donate
to environmental groups.

<P><HR>
<CENTER><B><I>Putting it to Work:</B>
<A HREF="leadership-work.html">Students Tackle Environmental Issues</A></I></CENTER>
<HR>

