<HEAD>

<TITLE>WMX - Accountability</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Web Builder, 24-May-1995 -->

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.00">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H2>Accountability</H2>

<HR SIZE=5><I>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
This section covers four programs implementing principles eight, 13
and 14 of the WMX Environmental Policy through which WMX is
accountable to its shareholders and the public: 

<A HREF="#1">remediation at WMX facilities</A>, 
<A HREF="#2">management accountability and employee involvement</A>,
<A HREF="#3">environmental certifications</A>, and 
<A HREF="#4">public disclosure through the Annual Environmental Report</A>.
</FONT>

<DL>
	<DT><B>Principles Addressed in this Section</B>
		<DD><P><B>8. Damage Compensation</B><BR>
The Company will take responsibility for any harm we cause to the
environment and will make every reasonable effort to remedy the damage
caused to people or ecosystems.

		<DD><P><B>13. Environmental Policy Assessment</B><BR>
The Board of Directors of the Company will evaluate and will address
the environmental implications of its decisions.  The Executive
Environmental Committee of the Company will report directly to the
Chief Executive Officer of the Company and will monitor and report
upon implementation of this policy and other environmental matters.
The Company will commit the resources needed to implement these
principles.

		<DD><P><B>14. Annual Environmental Report</B><BR>
The Company will prepare and make public an annual report on its
environmental activities.  The report will include a self-evaluation
of the Company's implementation of these principles, including an
assessment of the Company's performance in complying with all
applicable environmental laws and regulations throughout its worldwide
operations.
</DL></I>

<HR WIDTH=75% SIZE=5><P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../art/report/account.gif" ALT="[TABLE: Progress Report: Accountability]">
<H5><I>
1. Including programs to assess and respond to potential Superfund
responsibilities; does not necessarily mean that business units have
been named PRPs.
</I></H5>
</CENTER>

<A NAME="1">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Remediation at WMX Facilities
</H3></B></CENTER>

Most non-permitted releases for which WMX subsidiaries have some
responsibility have occurred at land disposal facilities in the United
States. Virtually all of these have occurred at older facilities
acquired from other companies, or at facilities not owned by WMX but
to which WMX or its predecessors lawfully transported waste.  In
general, environmental considerations in landfill location and design
were much less stringent when these facilities were developed than
they are today.

<P>
At sites acquired by WMX, the Company has assumed responsibility
for investigating contamination and implementing appropriate remedial
measures. At sites not owned by WMX, the Company works with other
responsible parties to investigate and remediate contamination.

<P>
<A HREF="../art/report/pie16.gif">
<IMG SRC="../art/report/pie16i.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 16: Superfund Sites Where WMX is a Potentially Responsible Party]">
</A>

<P>
Some of these sites are on the EPA Superfund National Priority
List (NPL). Claims have been made against WMX subsidiaries at
104 sites on the NPL where these subsidiaries are alleged to be
potentially responsible parties (PRPs). None of the 104 NPL facilities
was originally developed by WMX. Nineteen were acquired by WMX
subsidiaries from other owners. The remaining 85 have never been
owned by WMX, but received some waste transported by a firm currently
owned by the Company, typically as one of many waste haulers serving
an area (see Figure 16).
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
At each of the 19 WMX-owned facilities on the NPL, the Company
lends its technical expertise and works with the government to
characterize or remediate problems. In addition, the Company has
either agreed, or is seeking agreement, with other liable parties
to share the costs of remediation. Sites subject to state &quot;Superfund&quot;
laws are treated by the Company in the same way as NPL sites.
Internationally, WMX has upgraded and cleaned up a number of acquired
facilities.

<P>
<A HREF="../art/report/barfig17.gif">
<IMG SRC="../art/report/barfig17i.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 ALT="[FIGURE 17: Expenditures for Remediation of Closed Sites]">
</A>

<P>
WMX net expenditures for remediation of closed sites (after recovery
of costs from other parties) are shown in Figure 17. In 1991, the
Company recorded a charge of $296 million before tax and minority
interest, to reflect its then-current estimate of Superfund
environmental remediation liabilities. The Company continues to
evaluate and provide for the costs of remediating other sites that may
pose a potential threat to public health, welfare or the environment.
It also provides for costs expected to be incurred after a facility
ceases to accept waste. At the end of 1994, WMX had accrued $813
million to provide for environmental responsibilities, including
remediation and closure and post-closure monitoring costs.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
No significant judgments or settlements were entered in 1994 with
respect to private civil actions against WMX concerning pollutants
released from disposal facilities. WMX carries environmental impairment
liability insurance in amounts that meet or exceed legal requirements.

<A NAME="2">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Management Accountability and Employee Involvement
</H3></B></CENTER>

From division presidents to the Chief Executive Officer, all managers
with environmental responsibilities have incentives for environmental
performance through compensation systems.

<P>
The WMX Executive Environmental Committee is the principal management
committee for oversight of operating group environmental performance
and for strategic reporting to the Chief Executive Officer of
WMX. Its members include executives from each of the operating
groups and major corporate functions. During 1994, the Committee
adopted quantitative measures to track progress under the WMX
Environmental Policy and Principles. Within most of the operating
groups, committees or other mechanisms have been established to
coordinate environmental policies and programs across business
units. For example, WMI plc's country environmental managers meet
quarterly.

<P>
Environmental considerations are inherent in decisions made by
the WMX Board of Directors. In addition, the WMX Law and Compliance
group reports to the Audit Committee of the Board on a quarterly
basis, and for the past five years Arthur D. Little, Inc. has
presented the results of its annual environmental assessment to
the Audit Committee. None of the Audit Committee members is a
WMX employee. The Board of Directors has reviewed and approved
each annual environmental report, including this one, since reporting
began in 1990.

<P>
Environmental performance depends upon the efforts of all employees.
WMX has instituted recognition programs to encourage and reward
employee involvement in environmental issues. In 1994, the first
Chairman's Award for Environmental Excellence was given to MANLIBA
in Buenos Aires for converting a fleet of trucks to natural gas.
Many operating groups also have recognition programs for individuals
or business units.

<A NAME="3">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Environmental Management Certification
</H3></B></CENTER>

WMX companies have pursued certification of their environmental
management systems under various country programs. Two of the three
hazardous waste management companies in the Netherlands, for example,
are certified under the Dutch Environmental Care system and the solid
waste companies are preparing for certification.  Operations in the
United Kingdom are preparing for certification under BS 7750. All of
these programs require independent audits of environmental management
systems.

<A NAME="4">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Annual Environmental Report
</H3></B></CENTER>

This is the fifth WMX Annual Environmental Report.  It was prepared by
the Executive Environmental Committee and approved by the WMX Board of
Directors. A more detailed report is available on request. We welcome
your comments and have provided a
<A HREF="comments.html">response form</A>
for your use. We will make a donation of five dollars for each reply
received to Earth Share, a coalition of 43 national environmental
organizations.

<P><HR>
<CENTER><B><I>Putting it to Work:</B>
<A HREF="account-work.html">Process Improvement Brings Environmental Benefits</A></I></CENTER>
<HR>

