<HEAD>

<TITLE>WMX - Students Tackle Environmental Issues</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Web Builder, 16-May-1995 -->

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.00">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H2>Students Tackle Environmental Issues</H2>
<HR SIZE=5>

<IMG SRC="../art/report/students.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 ALT="[IMAGE: Students of the Annual Symposium for Environment]">

Wheelabrator and the Christa McAuliffe Planetarium and Foundation in
Concord, New Hampshire co-sponsor the Annual Symposium for Environment
and Education, an innovative nationwide student learning project that
was born out of the belief that businesses and communities should
support educators' efforts to introduce real life experiences to young
adults.

<P>
Participating groups of seventh and eighth grade students from
across the country are asked to identify a current environmental
problem facing their community or region and to evaluate and develop
long-term plans and solutions for that problem.  As part of their
research, students are encouraged to meet with business professionals,
government officials, regulators, scientists and members of environmental
groups.  Students have a full school year to identify a problem,
conduct research and come up with a solution.  At the end of the
year, Wheelabrator sponsors a visit by teachers and student representatives
from participating schools to Concord, New Hampshire, where each
team presents its problem, research and solutions to a panel of
independent judges.

<P>
One of three winners of the first Symposium in 1994 was a team
from the West Cottonwood School, Cottonwood, California, who depicted
through computer simulation the development of the City of Cottonwood
in the year 2019. 

<P><HR>
