<HEAD>

<TITLE>WMX - Corporate Profile</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Web Builder, 17-May-1995 -->

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.00">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Don Grage">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H2>Corporate Profile</H2>

<HR SIZE=5><I>
WMX is the leading global environmental services company, employing
more than 74,000 people in 32 countries.  WMX revenues in 1994
exceeded $10 billion.  The company operates five principal subsidiaries
whose major 1994 developments are described below.
</I>

<CENTER><P>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/corppie2.gif" ALT="[PIE CHART: WMX Revenue by Subsidiary]">
</CENTER>

<A NAME="1">
<P><HR><CENTER>
<H3><B>
Waste Management, Inc. (WMI)
</H3></B></CENTER>

The largest solid waste company in North America, WMI provides
collection and processing of recyclables from residential and
commercial customers; transfer and disposal of solid and special
wastes; medical waste collection and disposal; and special events
resources, including portable sanitation, electric power poles,
temporary fencing and street sweeping.  WMI operates 430 collection
divisions, 129 transfer stations, 134 landfills and 116 material
recovery facilities.

<P>
1994 was an exciting year for recycling.  Revenues climbed nearly
30 percent and approached $400 million.  WMI provided recycling
services to 119,000 businesses and 6.4 million households in 860
communities.

<CENTER><P>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/pie1.gif" ALT="[PIE CHART: WMI Revenue By Service]">
</CENTER>

<A NAME="2">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Chemical Waste Management, Inc. (CWM)
</H3></B></CENTER>

CWM is a leading provider of hazardous waste recycling and recovery,
collection, transportation, treatment, thermal destruction and
disposal. It also provides low-level radioactive waste services,
including processing, site assessment, licensing, radiological
controls, decommissioning and disposal.

<P>
In 1994, waste minimization and recycling by industry, decline
in off-site waste volumes from environmental clean-up projects,
a lack of new regulatory initiatives and direction from Washington,
and incineration overcapacity continued to result in lower volumes
of waste handled.

<A NAME="3">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Wheelabrator Technologies Inc. (WTI)
</H3></B></CENTER>

WTI is one of North America's premier builders and operators of
trash-to-energy and independent power facilities.  It is also
one of the largest global suppliers of process engineered systems
and services to municipal and industrial water, wastewater and
biosolids markets. It offers air quality control systems for industrial
and utility applications.

<P>
WTI acquired companies in Singapore, the Netherlands and Spain
that strengthened its ability to provide high-tech industrial
water and wastewater treatment systems.  It opened the world's
most technically advanced trash-to-energy plant in Falls Township,
Pennsylvania.  WTI also joined with Babcock and Wilcox Liaoning
Energy Corp. in an agreement to provide cogeneration projects
to serve district heating systems in Liaoning Province, The People's
Republic of China.

<A NAME="4">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Rust International Inc. (Rust)
</H3></B></CENTER>

Rust is a leading worldwide provider of technology-focused environmental
and infrastructure services for clients in industry and the public
sector.  Services include environmental and infrastructure consulting,
engineering and construction, environmental remediation and a
variety of on-site industrial services.  Overseas, Rust employs
more than 2,500 professionals operating in 31 offices throughout
Europe, the Middle East and the Pacific Rim.

<CENTER><P>
<IMG SRC="../art/report/rust.gif" HSPACE=10 ALT="[PIE CHART: Rust Revenue By Service]">
</CENTER>

<A NAME="5">
<P><HR>
<H3><B><CENTER>
Waste Management International plc (WMI plc)
</H3></B></CENTER>

WMI plc is the leading international provider of solid and hazardous
waste management services.  Related services include waste reduction
and minimization; collection, transportation, storage, treatment,
recycling, trash-to-energy and land disposal of solid wastes;
hazardous waste treatment, stabilization, thermal destruction
and disposal; and international city cleaning and water/wastewater
treatment.  Waste Management International operates 320 collection
divisions, 70 transfer stations, 57 landfills and 50 material
recovery facilities.  

<P>
WMI plc completed 50 acquisitions in 1994.  Recycling operations
were expanded in Italy, Sweden, Germany, the United Kingdom and
Finland.  New landfills opened in Italy, Spain and the United
Kingdom.  In Spain, the Company won a 20-year contract to operate
a new hazardous waste treatment center.

<P><HR>
<H5><CENTER>
<A HREF="http://www.wmx.com/">WMX Main Level</A> ||
<A HREF="report-intro.html#toc">Table of Contents</A> ||
<A HREF="comments.html">Comment &amp; Reponse Form</A>
</H5></CENTER>
</BODY>

<P><HR>
