<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>1995 Annual Environmental Report</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="3c,99,4d">
 
<CENTER><STRONG>WMX TECHNOLOGIES, INC.<BR>
DESCRIPTION OF PENALTIES PAID FOR ENVIRONMENTAL MATTERS 1995<BR>
(More than $10,000)</STRONG></CENTER>

<P>
<STRONG>Chemical Waste Management, Inc.</STRONG><BR>
(Sauget, Illinois)  In 1993, the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency commenced an action to enforce alleged violations of a 1991 consent order involving Chemical Waste Managements Inc. Trade Waste Incinerator facility in Sauget, Illinois.  The State alleged numerous violations generally relating to operating conditions required by the Order.  The Illinois Attorney General acknowledged that the alleged violations had no impact on the environment.  To resolve the matter, CWM agreed to pay $200,000 to aid in the cleanup of East St. Louis, $175,000 for the disposal of hazardous wastes from these Illinois counties, and $250,000 in penalties.

<P>
<STRONG>Rust International Inc.</STRONG><BR>
(Idaho)  Rust paid a penalty of $353,800 for alleged violations of U.S. EPA regulations promulgated pursuant to the Clean Air Act.  The alleged violations of EPAs asbestos rules related to work carried out at a pulp and paper mill in Idaho in 1989 and 1990 by a company acquired by Rust in 1991.  EPA notified Rust of the matters in November of 1992.

<P>
<STRONG>Waste Management, Inc.</STRONG><BR>
(Massachusetts)  On February 7, 1995, the Massachusetts Water Resources Agency cited Waste Management of Massachusetts, Inc. for discharging 90 gallons of septage from portable sanitation units into a waste water treatment facility in June of 1994.  The septage in question could have entered the facility lawfully had it originated from within the prescribed service area.  The driver responsible for the discharge of the septage into the public owned treatment works is no longer with the company.  Waste Management of Massachusetts, Inc. paid a penalty in the amount of $15,000 to resolve the matter,
<P>
(Pennsylvania)  GROWS Landfill and Tullytown Resource Recovery facility paid a $42,000 penalty for alleged violations of regulations pertaining to odor control.  The facilities had filed applications for expansions of gas control systems to avoid off-site odors.  Because of the restrictions imposed upon the agency by the Clean Air Act, the Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection did not issue these permits.  The Consent Order allowed the landfills to install temporary flares to control landfill gas, and to allow construction of power plant facilities that use landfill gas.

<P>
<STRONG>Wheelabrator Technologies, Inc.</STRONG><BR>
(Arizona)  In August of 1993, the U.S. EPA issued a notice of violation and penalty assessment to Wheelabrators Westates Carbon facility alleging several violations of interim status hazardous waste management requirements.  Wheelabrator contested these allegations and, in August of 1995, entered into an administrative settlement under which Westates Carbon agreed to pay an administrative penalty of $57,515 without admitting any of the allegations made by EPA.  The Westates Carbon facility has received EPA compliance inspections every six months since the initial allegations were made and no substantive concerns have been raised.

<P>
<CENTER><BR>Please click on the &quot;Back Button&quot; of your browser to
return to the previous page.<BR><BR><A HREF="contents.htm"><IMG
