<html>
<head>
<title>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</title>

<!pn=arpt2s2e.htm/page edited on 12/17/97blh->
<!page called by arpt2s2m.htm->
</head>

<body>
<center><b>PORT ISSUES</b></center>
<p>
<center><b>WATER RESOURCES DEVELOPMENT AND FEDERAL USER CHARGES</b></center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Water Resources Development Legislation</b>
<p>
For the first time since the enactment of the landmark Water 
Resources Development Act of
1986 (P.L. 99-662), Congressional efforts during 1994 to pass 
biennial legislation authorizing
water resource projects failed.  Previously, Congress was 
successful in reaching agreement in
1988, 1990 and 1992.  During the 103rd session, the House passed a 
bill (H.R. 4460) on
October 3, 1994.  However, the Senate was unable to reach a 
consensus on its version of the
bill (S.2233).  Similar efforts to enact legislation in 1995 were 
unsuccessful.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>Status of Water Resource Trust Funds</b>
<p>
The following series of tables provides the financial status of the 
two water resource trust
funds.  Table 31 presents a summary of the Harbor Maintenance Fee 
collections by source for
fiscal years 1990 through 1995.  Imports represent the largest 
source of revenue for the Harbor
Maintenance Trust Fund (HMTF).  For the period shown, import fees 
averaged about 64
percent of annual collections with exports averaging 28 percent and 
domestic trade 5 percent.  
It should be noted that FY 1991 was the first year in which the 
increased tax rate (0.125
percent) for the Harbor Maintenance Fee was in effect.

<p>
Table 32 provides a summary of the Harbor Maintenance Trust Fund 
revenue and transfer
activity over the last 6 fiscal years.  For FY 1995, the trust fund 
received $670.5 million from
the Harbor Maintenance Fee (HMF), up 7.7 percent over FY 1994.  The 
expenditures for
dredging purposes totaled $529.3 million--up 8.6 percent--leaving 
a balance in the trust fund of
$621.1 million, an increase of $168.8 million.  Two factors have 
contributed to the 
surplus.  The lack of authorizing legislation to allow the National 
Oceanic and Atmospheric 
Administration (NOAA) to withdraw approximately $45.5 million 
annually from the fund.  
Revenue has been accumulating for NOAA since January 1, 1991.  A 
second factor is that the
actual O&M expenditures for the Corps of Engineers (Corps) has been 
less than was originally projected in 1989 when the HMF rate of 
0.125 percent was established.
<p>
Table 33 shows the projected revenues and expenditures from the 
Harbor Maintenance Trust
Fund for fiscal years 1995 to 1999.  Net revenues are projected to 
increase by 30 percent 
during this period while net expenditures are anticipated to grow 
by 11 percent.  The project
surplus is estimated to increase from $645 million in FY 1995 to 
$1.6 billion by the end of FY 1999.
<p>
Table 34 represents the FY 1995 income statement for the Inland 
Waterway Trust Fund.  The
trust fund is funded by the proceeds from a tax on fuel used in 
commercial transportation on the
inland waterways.  The fuel tax was increased to 20 cents per 
gallon in 1995, which is the
maximum tax rate called for when the tax schedule was amended by 
WDRA 86.  During     
FY 1995, the trust fund received over $103 million from the fuel 
tax and transferred nearly $95
million to the Corps for project improvements.  The balance in the 
trust fund at the end of FY 1995 was $242.1 million.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>Harbor Maintenance Fee on Exports Ruled Unconstitutional</b>
<p>
On October 25, 1995, the U.S. Court of International Trade agreed 
with shippers (United States Shoe Corp. v. U. S., 907 F. Supp. 408 
(Ct. Int'l Trade 1995)) that the harbor
maintenance fee (HMF) as applied to exports is unconstitutional. 
The trade court concluded
that the fee violated the Constitution's "Export Clause," which 
bans taxes or duties on any U.S.
exports.  The court rejected the government's argument that the HMF 
was a user charge and not a tax.  In its ruling, the court indicated 
that, to be constitutional, the main purpose of the
underlying law should be regulation and the revenue raised should
be to only to recover the 
cost of services provided.  Specifically, the ad valorem basis of 
the HMF is not a "fair
approximation" of the benefits received.  For example, large 
deep-draft bulk carriers could
benefit more but pay less than smaller vessels carrying high valued 
cargo.  Further, the fact
that the trust fund has been running a surplus was an indication 
that the HMF was imposed to
raise revenue.  On February 1, 1996, the Justice Department filed 
a notice of appeal to the
U.S. Court of International Trade.  Until the appeal process is 
completed, the HMF will continue to be collected.
<p>
If the trade court's decision is upheld on appeal, the ruling could 
result in refunds to exporters
totaling several hundred million dollars since the court decided it 
had jurisdiction to order the
reimbursement of two years of tax payments.  Another consequence of 
this decision could lead
to a challenge of the fee on imports under the General Agreement on 
Tariffs and Trade
(GATT).  A tax or fee, which is applied to only exports or imports, 
can be considered as
discriminatory with respect to GATT.  Based on past experience, if 
the application of the HMF
were limited to just the domestic traffic, the annual HMTF revenues 
would decrease by 90 percent.
<p>
The U.S. port industry is concerned over the trade court's decision 
because of the impact it will
have on the funding mechanism for operations and maintenance 
dredging of federal navigation
channels at public ports.  The industry supported the passage of 
the Water Resources
Development Act of 1986, which created the HMF.  They opposed the 
tripling of the fee in
1990 and called for a rollback of the fee to .085 percent.  They 
also have requested expanding
the scope of Trust Fund uses to include cost shared construction of 
dredged material disposal
facilities, environmental remediation and disposal of contaminated 
sediments.  The
reauthorization of WRDA 96 as passed by both Houses, but not yet 
enacted, expands the
eligible uses from the HMTF to include cost-sharing for dredged 
material disposal facilities. 
This legislation is supported by the Administration.
<p>
<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<h5><a href="arpt2s2m.htm">Return to Port Issues Index</a></h5>
<p>
</body>
