<html>
<head>
<title>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</title>

<!pn=arpt2s2f.htm/page edited on 12/18/96blh->
<!page called by arpt2s2m.htm->
</head>

<body>
<center><b>PORT ISSUES</b></center>
<p>
<center><b>INTERMODAL TRANSPORTATION ACCESS</b></center>
<p>

Intermodal transportation is critical to the United States ports 
and closely linked to our Nation's
economy, global competitiveness and national security.  Waterborne 
transportation in the
United States is inherently intermodal for the movement of freight 
and passengers from origin
to final destination.  Water transport is an important segment of 
the transportation system
whose full benefits can only be realized by linking it cost 
effectively with land-based modes of
rail, road, air, and pipeline transportation to form an integrated 
intermodal transportation
system.  A key element in this linkage continues to be efficientl 
and and waterside access to
ports and terminals which support freight movement as part of 
increasingly integrated supply
chains and distribution networks, domestically and internationally. 
The U.S. port system
handles 95 percent of the Nation's foreign trade, by volume, which 
is expected to double by the
year 2010.  MARAD continues to work with other Department of 
Transportation's (DOT)
operating administrations to ensure that intermodal port and 
terminal access issues are
appropriately addressed under the reauthorization of Intermodal 
Surface Transportation
Efficiency Act of 1991 (ISTEA) and the proposed National 
Transportation System (NTS) initiatives.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>National Highway System Designation Act of 1995 (NHS)</b>
<p>
The importance of major intermodal marine linkages or connections 
to surface transportation
was recognized in the National Highway System Designation Act of 
1995 (Public Law 104-59),
signed by President Clinton on November 28, 1995.  The Act directed 
the Secretary, not later
than 180 days after the date of enactment, to submit for approval 
to the Committee on
Environment and Public Works of the Senate and the Committee on 
Transportation and
Infrastructure of the House of Representatives modifications to the 
NHS consisting of connections to major ports, airports, international
border crossings, public transportation and 
transit facilities, interstate bus terminals, and rail and other 
intermodal transportation facilities. 
The Act also established interim eligibility for improvements to 
proposed connections with
NHS funds if they are consistent with the criteria being used for 
identifying connections for
submission to Congress.  These interim guidelines will remain in 
effect until Congress approves
the connection modifications and additions.  
<p>
On May 24, 1996, the Secretary of Transportation forwarded to 
Congress for approval the
Department's recommendations on the NHS connections to major 
intermodal terminals.   They 
were developed in consultation with the DOT operating 
administrations, State transportation
agencies, national organizations, and public interest groups.  The 
identification process was
based on criteria with two major components, i.e., volumes or 
activity levels by terminal type
and a more subjective approach relative to the importance of the 
terminal to the State.  The
package submitted to Congress identified nearly 1,400 major 
intermodal passenger and freight
terminal connections, which included links to 240 major port 
facilities that handle 99 percent of total waterborne cargo.
<p>     
<hr>
<p>

<b>ISTEA Reauthorization Initiatives</b>
<p>
According to the National Commission on Intermodal Transportation, 
the Nation's
transportation system accounts for 16.8 percent of the Nation's 
Gross National Product (GNP)
with freight transportation accounting for 37 percent of these 
expenditures.  On average, one-sixth of an American household's 
expenditures cover transportation goods and services. 
ISTEA increased our awareness of transportation's economic 
importance and how improved
intermodal connections can increase the effectiveness of the 
transportation system.  
<p>
Growth in both the volume of freight and the size of vessels has 
been matched by increased
investment and more productive marine terminal facilities. 
However, access to many port
terminals in terms of navigation channels and road and rail links 
has not kept pace with this
growth thereby resulting in delays and increased costs.  Moreover, 
like a pipeline, our Nation's
transportation system is only as efficient as its narrowest, most 
congested point; that is often  
the landside access from the port to the closest interstate highway 
or rail yard.  No matter how
productive ports make their terminal facilities, the Nation's 
intermodal transportation system
cannot operate to maximum efficiency unless ports have adequate 
access at both water and landside.
<p>
The DOT has embarked upon a major initiative, including twelve 
forums throughout the United
States, to reauthorize ISTEA.  MARAD is participating in the 
Departmental initiative as well as
in various Departmental operating administrations' initiatives that 
focus on intermodal freight mobility issues.
<p>
MARAD recognizes the need to increase public awareness of freight 
mobility and to involve
private sector freight interests in initiatives that shape 
policies, planning, and funding at DOT
and to find innovative ways to leverage limited dollars needed to 
address critical transportation
infrastructure requirements.  In an effort to address this 
objective, MARAD organized an 
outreach program during the months of July through September 1996. 
The objective of
MARAD's outreach program was to increase communication and dialogue 
with private sector
marine freight interests and to enhance their involvement in 
Departmental legislative initiatives
including ISTEA II and the National Transportation System.  These 
meetings were designed to supplement the ongoing Departmental and 
other operating administrations' outreach efforts.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>National Transportation System</b>
<p>
The Intermodal Surface Transportation Act of 1991 (ISTEA) created 
a new requirement for
States to undertake a continuous statewide transportation planning 
process, modeled on the
metropolitan transportation planning process, by developing a 
long-range plan integrating all
modes of transportation.  At the Federal level, however, the need 
has been recognized to
develop a comparable analytical approach to national transportation 
issues, policies, and
performance looking at the national transportation network in its 
entirety as a single integrated, multimodal system.  
<p>
The DOT has embarked upon the development of a National Transportation
System (NTS) that 
will enable the Department to identify and develop policies and 
programs based on
international, national, regional and multimodal transportation 
requirements.  The NTS will
also enable DOT to anticipate future national transportation system 
requirements and identify
appropriate Federal responses thorough a new and improved ability 
to measure, forecast and
analyze how the Nation's transportation network functions and how 
it responds to external
(e.g., economic and demographic changes) and internal 
(e.g.,regulatory and program actions) pressures.
<p>
<hr>
<hr>
<p>
