<HEAD>
<TITLE>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</TITLE>
<!pn=shocp.htm/page last edited/updated on 12/6/96blh->

</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="BILL3.JPG"></CENTER><P>
<UL>
<LI>SHIP SAFETY</LI>     
<LI>QUALITY OF OPERATIONS</LI>
<LI>EQUIPMENT RELIABILITY</LI>
<LI>EFFICIENCY</LI>
<LI>PRODUCTIVITY</LI>
<LI>WORLD-WIDE COMPETITIVENESS</LI><p>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>
<a><center><b>SHIP OPERATIONS COOPERATIVE PROGRAM</b></center></a>
<p>
<b>Introduction</b>
<p>
     The Ship Operations Cooperative Program was established in
April 1993 with the signing of a Cooperative Agreement between
three U.S. shipping companies (ARCO Marine, Energy Transportation
Corporation, and Sea-Land Service) and two government agencies
(Maritime Administration and National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration).  Since then several new members, with full
membership and associate membership status have signed on.  
<p>     
     The purpose of the SOCP is to address and promote commercially
beneficial innovations in ship operations through the
identification, development, and application of new methods,
procedures, and technologies.
<p>
     Its overall objective is to improve the competitiveness,
productivity, efficiency, safety, and environmental responsiveness
of U.S. vessel operations.  All U.S. vessel operators are eligible
to participate in the program.  With the support of MARAD, industry
and government work together to address common challenges and to
cooperative program allows members to participate in research which
would not be economically feasible on an individual basis.  The
specific objectives of SOCP are to:
<p>     
     1.   Bring together on a continuing basis
          representatives from U.S. shipping
          organizations who are responsible for ship
          operations.
<p>     
     2.   Determine common problems and interests among
          the cooperative's members.
<p>
     3.   Make recommendations concerning cooperative
          actions which might be taken to resolve
          problems by implementing applicable technology
          or training initiatives.
<p>
     4.   Develop implementation plans for the
          performance of individual projects which are
          approved by the membership.
<p>
     5.   Make recommendations to regulatory or
          legislative agencies in the interest of
          maritime safety and the maritime industry,
          based on its collective knowledge and/or the
          results of SOCP projects.
<p>
Several projects have been completed or are currently underway that
lend themselves to these objectives.  They are:
<p>
Current Projects:
<p>
     .    <b>Reliability, Availability and Maintainability (RAM)
          Database</b> - This program to improve the Reliability,
          Availability, and Maintainability of ship's equipment
          will develop and implement a system to collect ship's
          equipment failure/corrective maintenance data and store
          it in a central repository.  Member companies will have
          access to this data for making decisions on improving the
          reliability of their vessel's equipment to reduce vessel
          life-cycle costs.  The participation of marine equipment
          manufacturers and U.S. shipyards is currently being
          solicited to close the feedback loop.
<p>
     .    <b>Multimedia Training - USCG/ABS Shipboard Inspection
          Primer</b> - Two U.S. Coast Guard partnership programs,
          Alternate Compliance Program (ACP) and Streamlined
          Inspection Process (SIP) currently exist in an effort to
          improve the overall vessel inspection process.  The SOCP
          is developing a Multimedia Training Program to instruct
          shipboard officers on how to gain a better understanding
          of the inspection processes and criteria, prepare more
          efficiently for inspections, and conduct vessel self
<p>
     .    <b>Regulatory Research and Analysis</b> - The objective of this
          project is to identify U.S. regulations classified as
          high cost for the ship/vessel operator.  The research
          would include not only existing regulations, but also
          proposed regulations and would define specific
          applications of technology that could reduce the expense
          of compliance.  The analysis would also make
          recommendations for other actions which could be taken to
          reduce costs.
<p>
Completed Projects:
<p>
     .    Crew Member Cross Training
<p>
     .    Fitness for Duty/Evaluation
<p>
     .    Hand Held Computer Applications
<p>
     .    Optimum Staffing and Standard Arrangements for Pilothouse
          Operations
<p>
     .    Survey of Shipboard Management Training
<p>
     .    Ship Management Training Syllabus
<p>     
     .    Vision Enhancement
<p>
<b>SOCP Points of Contact for additional information are:</b>
<p>
                                    
                             
Peter Schaedel<br>
Chairman, SOCP<br>             
(212) 642-9885<br>      
email: pgschaedel@aol.com
<p>
John Dumbleton<br>
Maritime Administration<br>    
(202) 366-1928<br>   
email: john.dumbleton@marad.dot.gov
<p>
Fred Bankert<br> 
Program Administrator<br>      
(703) 620-8148<br>      
email: bankert_fred@prc.com
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>WHY JOIN ?</b>
<p>
Membership in the Ship 
Operations Cooperative 
Program . . .
<p>
Provides the opportunity to conduct high 
priority ship operations projects at a fraction 
of the cost of doing them independently.
<p>
Provides a vehicle by which U.S. shipping 
common problems relating to vessel 
operations.
<p>
Provides membership with a cost sharing, 
industry-wide research and development 
program not economically feasible on an 
individual basis.
<p>
Allows new technologies to be explored using 
the combined resources of private industry and 
government working together.
<p>
Provides the strength of a united consortium 
when making recommendations to state, 
federal, and international regulatory 
organizations.
<p>
Allows members to share in the results of 
onboard evaluations of new products. 
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>WHO CAN JOIN?</b>
<p>
Membership is open to:
<p>
Any U.S. owned vessel operating organization 
(commercial or government). U.S. maritime industry 
organizations such as shipyards, designers, and 
ship managers may also be considered for 
membership. Two classes of membership have been 
established in order to encourage the widest 
possible participation, they are: Member 
(voting/cash contribution) and Associate Member 
(non-voting/in-kind contribution).
<p>
Current Membership Includes:
<p>
American Bureau of Shipping<br>
Arco Marine, Inc.<br>
BP Oil Transportation Corporation<br>
Bay Ship Management, Inc.<br>
Energy Transportation Group, Inc.<br>
Gulf Coast Region Maritime Technology<br>
Center - University of New Orleans<br>
Interocean Ugland Management<br>
Kirby Corporation<br>
Marine Transport Lines<br>
Maritime Administration<br>
Military Sealift Command<br>
National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration<br>
Sea-Land Service, Inc.<br>
United States Coast Guard<br>
<p>                             
<hr>
<p>

<b>CURRENT SOCP PROJECTS</b>
<p>
<b>RAM Database</b>
<p>
This program to improve the Reliability, 
Availability and Maintainability (RAM) of 
ship's equipment will develop and implement a 
system to collect ship's equipment 
failuret/corrective maintenance data and store 
it in a central repository. Member companies 
will have access to this data for making 
decisions on improving the reliability of their 
vessel's equipment to reduce vessel life-cycle 
costs. The participation of marine equipment 
manufacturers and U.S. shipyards is currently 
being solicited to close the feedback loop.
<p>

<b>Multimedia Training - USCG/ABS 
Shipboard Inspection Primer</b>
<p>
Two U.S. Coast Guard partnership programs, 
Alternate Compliance Program (ACP) and 
Streamlined Inspection Process (SIP) currently 
exist in an effort to improve the overall vessel 
inspection process. In this vein, the SOCP is 
developing a Multimedia Training Program to 
instruct shipboard officers in how to gain a 
better understanding of the inspection 
processes and criteria, prepare more 
efficiently for inspections, and conduct vessel 
self inspections to USCG/ABS 
specifications. 
<p>
<hr>
<p>
                    

<b>OTHER CURRENT PROJECTS</b> 
<p>
<b>USCG Regulatory Reform</b>
<p>
The SOCP and its members are participating in 
the development of the Coast Guard's programs 
that help ease the burden of regulatory 
compliance and improve industry 
competitiveness. The main programs are 
Alternate Compliance Program (ACP), the 
Streamlined Inspection Process (SIP), 4C's 
QIT, and the Industry Task Force on Pacific 
Rim Consistency. The SOCP will present the 
lessons learned and successes of these pilot 
programs to the USCG to help formulate a more cost effective
Continuous Inspection Process (CIP).
<p>
<b>Regulatory Research and Analysis</b>
<p>
The objective of this project is to identify U.S. 
regulations classified as high cost for the 
ship/vessel operator. The research would include 
not only existing regulations, but also proposed 
regulations and would define specific 
applications of technology that could reduce the 
expense of compliance. The analysis would also 
make recommendations for other actions which 
could be taken to reduce costs. 
<p>                     
<hr>
<p>

<B> COMPLETED SOCP PROJECTS</B>
<P> 
 o  Crew Member Cross Training
<p> 
 o  Fitness for Duty/Evaluation
<p> 
 o  Hand Held Computer Applications
<p> 
 o  Optimum Staffing & Standard
    Arrangements for Pilothouse Operations
<p>
 o  Professional Skills & Knowledge
    Upgrade
<p>  
 o  Survey of Shipboard Management 
    Training
<p>   
 o  Ship Management Training Syllabus
<p>
<hr>
