<html>
<head>
<title>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</title>
<!pn=arpt2s2b.htm/page edited on 12/11/96blh->
</head>

<body>
<center><b>PORT ISSUES</b></center>
<p>
<center><b>CONTAINERSHIP OPERATORS INTRODUCE<br> 
NEW VESSELS AND CARRIER ALLIANCES</b></center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Impact of the Next Generation Containership</b>
<p>
During the next few years, U.S. ports again will be faced with the 
challenge of handling the
next generation of containerships.  Worldwide, containership 
operators will be taking delivery
of 67 vessels in the 4,500 to 6,000 TEU range in 1996 through 1998. 
The first of the large
6,000 TEU containerships, REGINA MAERSK, was delivered in January 1996.  
Specifically,
the order book shows 26 vessels in the 4,500 to 4,999 TEU range, 26 
vessels between 5,000
and 5,999 TEUs and 15 vessels at 6,000+ TEUs.  These new vessels 
will serve high volume,
long distance trades, with many operating as part of vessel sharing 
agreements or alliances. 
They will require sophisticated and efficient terminal facilities 
with excellent landside intermodal connections.
<p>
The first hurdle for some ports will be dredging.  Ports will need 
to provide channels and
berthing areas with minimum depths of 45 feet.  Currently, only 
half of the top 10 U.S.
container ports, which handle nearly 80 percent of the container 
traffic, have existing channel
depths that can accommodate these vessels.  Many of the leading 
ports, which lack adequate
depths, have projects underway or in the planning stage to increase 
their channel depths.  The
crucial question is whether they can complete these projects in 
time given the problems
experienced by many ports in seeking solutions to siltation, 
dredged material disposal and
contaminated sediments.  While not all ports need the capability to 
handle these vessels, the
failure to provide an adequate number of these channels in a timely 
manner will seriously
impact the efficiency and competitiveness of our intermodal 
transportation system.
<p>
The economics of these new vessels will mean fewer port calls for 
many ports and in some
cases the elimination of port calls all together.  The situation is 
similar to the 1980s when
carriers first introduced the 3,000 and 4,000 TEU vessels.  
For some ports, the pressure to 
ensure that the required infrastructure is in place will increase. 
For those ports which stand to
lose business, they will need to pursue other market opportunities, 
such as non-container
cargoes or niche markets, as was done by other ports during the 1980s.
<p>
Another issue ports must address is the impact of these vessels on 
terminal facilities.  The
volume of cargo carried by new vessels will require new or improved 
terminals.  This includes
larger cranes, berths and storage yards.  Landside access will have 
to be improved to handle
the higher peak volumes of rail and truck traffic.  Today, 
congestion is a major problem at
many container terminals where trucking delays at terminal gates is 
increasing.  Major
improvements will be required in this area before the new vessels 
enter into service.  Ports
have begun a number of major expansion projects.  Virtually, every 
major west coast port is
building or expanding container facilities, including many with 
on-dock rail facilities.  The cost
of a new facility can reach several hundred million dollars.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Impact of Global Shipping Alliances</b>
<p>
A new approach to world trade logistics has become a reality 
through the mechanism of "global
shipping alliances."  An alliance is a consortium or a sharing 
agreement among a group of
steamship lines serving similar trade areas for their mutual 
economic benefit.  The development
of shipping alliances will have a significant impact on how 
shipping and commercial operations
are conducted.  Global alliance shipping lines are rationalizing 
their services and costs by
coordinating their fleet and terminal operations across their trade routes.
<p>
For example, a containership operated by an alliance will share or 
charter space among its
members.  This will increase vessel load factors and reduce the 
number of vessels needed on a
trade route which will lower operating costs for the alliance 
shipping partners.  Other
considerations being discussed by shipping alliances include the 
coordination of container and
chassis pools and procurement.  Additionally, the  integration of 
feeder networks between
consortium partners allows for the shipping line partners to enter 
new markets without making large capital investments.
<p>
What does this mean in terms of impacts to U.S. ports?   Since the 
alliances will be
consolidating port operations, there will be winners and losers, 
especially among neighboring
ports.  For some, it may mean the total loss of alliance business 
because another port was
selected to serve a particular coastal range or, at a minimum, a 
reduction in cargo and vessel calls.
<p>
There will be significant adjustments for ports selected as 
alliance load centers.  Initially,
carriers will be consolidating terminal operations within the port 
area, which may stretch the
capabilities of some facilities.  In time, there will be a need to 
expand existing facilities and/or
construct new ones.  The added business may lead to increases in 
landside congestion--highway
and rail.  While there are many factors, which will determine port 
selection, those ports with
modern facilities, good landside transportation access and large 
local markets will be in a
stronger position to negotiate with the carrier alliances.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
</body>
</html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT11-B16-68</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA064-000372-B044-224</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
