<html>
<head>
<title>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</title>

<!pn=arpt2s2c.htm/page edited on 12/10/96blh->
</head>

<center><b>PORT ISSUES</b></center>
<p>
<center><b>ENVIRONMENTAL</b></center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Environmental Issues</b>
<p>
For any nation to thrive in today's global economy, it must develop 
and maintain an integrated transportation system, which is 
competitive, efficient, safe, and environmentally sound.  One of
the critical challenges facing the U.S. port industry is meeting 
the growing demands and diverse needs of waterborne transportation 
while protecting the environmentally sensitive harbor areas in 
which ports operate.  Vice President Gore's announcement (July 1996) 
of the Administration's plan to help resolve the dredging 
problems at the Port of New York and New Jersey is an example how 
a partnership of public and private interests can resolve difficult
issues.  The plan is designed to address regional environmental 
concerns while promoting economic growth.  The Department of 
Transportation and other Federal agencies, through their
programs and activities are encouraging the incorporation of 
environmental considerations into the transportation planning 
process.   Protecting the environment while providing an efficient
and cost effective transportation system is critical to this 
Nation's economic future. 
<p>
Environmental concerns are an integral part of a port's daily 
operations and development planning process.  Ports are seeing 
larger portions of their budgets and staffing allocated to
meeting environmental needs.  Environmental protection has been a 
particular concern for dredging and new terminal development, where 
controversies over dredged material disposal, environmental 
impacts, and mitigation have resulted in delays.
<p>
Among the key environmental concerns affecting the port industry 
are: (1) dredging navigation channels and disposing of dredged 
material in a timely, cost-effective, and environmentally
sound manner; (2) managing the wastes generated by facilities and
 ships in a safe and environmentally sound manner; (3) providing 
prompt and adequate response to spills of oil and hazardous 
substances; (4) controlling air polluting emissions from vessels 
and port operations; (5) preventing water pollution; (6) providing 
for the safe handling of hazardous cargo; (7) developing old 
industrial properties that may be contaminated; (8) complying with 
wetland and endangered species regulations; and (9) dealing with 
the various legal, liability, and financial obligations associated 
with environmental regulations.
<p>
Ports must comply with environmental laws and regulations from all 
levels of government--Federal, state, and local.  Recent Federal 
rulemakings of particular interest to port and related shipping
and shipyard activities include:
<p>
o    On December 22, 1993, the Coast Guard (USCG), U.S. Department 
of Transportation,
     issued interim final regulations that require vessels carrying 
     oil in bulk as cargo to carry
     discharge removal equipment, install spill prevention 
     coamings, and install emergency
     towing arrangements.
<p>
o    On July l, 1994, the USCG promulgated interim regulations to 
implement the provisions
     concerning financial responsibility for vessels under the Oil 
     Pollution Act of 1990 (OPA 90)
     and the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, 
     and Liability Act
     (CERCLA).
<p>
o    On July 15, 1994, the USCG issued a final rule amending its 
vessel traffic services (VTS)
     regulations in order to make participation in all VTS mandatory.
<p>
o    On October 7, 1994, under the authority of the Act to Prevent 
Pollution from Ships
     (APPS), the USCG issued a final rule requiring the carriage of 
     approved shipboard oil
     pollution emergency plans.  These regulations implement the 
     requirements of regulation 26
     of Annex I of the 1973 International Convention for the 
     Prevention of Pollution from Ships,
     as modified by the Protocol of 1978, as amended, (MARPOL73/78).
<p>
o    On November 9, 1994, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency 
(EPA) proposed
     emission standards under the Clean Air Act (CAA) for new 
     gasoline spark-ignition and
     diesel compression-ignition marine engines.
<p>
o    On December 6, 1994, the EPA proposed amendments to its rules 
under the Toxic
     Substances Control Act (TSCA) for polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs).  
     Changes proposed
     include: marking, storage, and disposal; decontamination 
     levels and procedures; and reporting and record keeping.
<p>
o    On April 7, 1995, the EPA promulgated changes to its National 
Pollutant Discharge
     Elimination System (NPDES) storm water permit application 
     regulations under the Clean
     Water Act (CWA).  These changes will examine additional 
     sources of pollutants.
<p>
o    On August 3, 1995, the USCG amended its regulations for
waterfront facilities capable of
     transferring liquefied hazardous gas (LHG) in bulk to or from 
     vessels in order to strengthen
     the requirements for LHG transfer.
<p>
o    On September 19, 1995, the EPA issued a final rule under the 
CAA concerning air
     pollution standards for marine tank vessel loading operations. 
     These standards require
     technology to limit air emissions of volatile organic 
     compounds (VOCs) and hazardous air
     pollutants (HAPs) from new and existing marine tank vessel 
     loading operations.
<p>
o    On December 15, 1995, the EPA issued a final rule that 
promulgates national emission
     standards for hazardous air pollutants (NESHAP) under the CAA 
     for shipbuilding and ship
     repair (surface coating) operations.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Environmental Laws</b>
<p>
The following describes the key environmental laws affecting the 
port industry.
<p>
<i>Act to Prevent Pollution from Ships, as amended, (APPS)</i>.  
This law implements the provisions
of MARPOL 73/78.  It provides for the prevention of pollution from 
ships by the discharge of
harmful substances or effluents.  MARPOL technical annexes address 
pollution by oil, noxious
liquid substances in bulk, harmful substances in packaged form or 
containers, sewage, and
garbage.  A new comprehensive annex for the control of air 
pollution from ships is under
development.  Annexes I, II, IV, and V have reception facility 
requirements for shipboard
wastes.  Annexes I, II, III, and V are in force in the United States.
<p>
<i>Marine Protection Research and Sanctuaries Act, as amended,(MPRSA)</i>.  
Title I of this act
regulates the disposal of materials at sea, preventing or strictly 
limiting the dumping of
materials that may adversely affect the human health, welfare, 
amenities, or the marine
environment, ecological systems, or economic potentialities.  For 
example, under section 103
of the MPRSA, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers must evaluate 
proposed projects that require
the transportation of dredged material for the purpose of disposal 
in the open ocean.  Activities under this act are also governed by the
Convention on the Prevention of Marine Pollution by 
Dumping of Wastes and Other Matter (London Convention).
<p>
<i>Clean Water Act, as amended, (CWA)</i>.  This law is designed to 
improve and protect surface
water quality.  The primary regulatory tool is the National 
Pollutant Discharge Elimination
System (NPDES) permit program.  It also includes separate permit 
programs for dredged
material disposal.  Under section 404 of the CWA, the U.S. Army 
Corps of Engineers
authorizes discharges of dredged or fill material in waters of the 
United States including
wetlands; and, under section 401 of the CWA, these disposal 
operations must be certified by
the affected state as complying with applicable state water quality 
standards.  The CWA also
addresses spills of oil and hazardous substances into surface water.
<p>
<i>Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability 
Act, as amended, (CERCLA)</i>.  
CERCLA provides for liability, compensation, clean-up, 
and emergency response
for hazardous substances released into the environment and for the 
cleanup of inactive hazardous waste disposal sites.
<p>
<i>Resource Conservation and Recovery Act, as amended, (RCRA)</i>.  
RCRA establishes a Federal-state permit system for hazardous waste 
management, promotes state non-hazardous waste
management efforts, and directs some effort to resource 
conservation and recovery.  It provides
for cradle to grave management of hazardous waste by imposing 
management requirements on
generators and transporters of materials and upon owners and 
operators of treatment, storage,
and disposal facilities.  It prohibits land disposal of hazardous 
wastes unless the wastes meet specified treatment standards.
<p>
<i>Clean Air Act, as amended, (CAA)</i>.  The CAA regulates emissions 
from stationary and mobile
sources and establishes the basic Federal-state regulatory 
framework, i.e., state implementation
plans (SIPS).  Other major programs include the prevention of 
significant deterioration (PSD)
 and attainment/nonattainment area programs.
<p>
<i>Ports and Waterways Safety Act, as amended, (PWSA)</i>.  
The PWSA seeks to enhance
navigation and vessel safety, protect the marine environment, and 
protect life, property, and structures in, on, or immediately adjacent
 to the navigable waters of the United States.  It 
implements many International Maritime Organization (IMO) standards 
concerning maritime safety.
<p>
<i>Coastal Zone Management Act, as amended, (CZMA)</i>.  Under the CZMA, 
coastal states can
formulate a management program for the land and water resources of 
their coastal zones and
submit them for approval to the Secretary of Commerce.  For an 
approved program, any
applicant for a Federal permit must certify that the proposed 
action (e.g., dredged material
disposal) is consistent with the State's approved program and the 
State must concur or disagree.
<p>
<i>Oil Pollution Act of 1990, as amended, (OPA 90)</i>.  OPA 90 has a 
number of provisions that
profoundly change the way oil is transported in U.S. waters, 
including requirements for spill
response plans, certificates of financial responsibility and 
increased liability for companies that
handle, store, and transport oil.  The Act caps liability limits 
and establishes the use of a
Federal trust fund for financing clean-up operations through a five 
cents-per-barrel fee on both
imported and domestic oil.  These liability limits may be exceeded, 
however, in cases of gross
negligence, willful misconduct, or violation of an applicable 
Federal safety, construction, or
operating regulation, thus potentially subjecting owners and 
operators of vessels and facilities to
unlimited liability.  Moreover, OPA 90 does not preempt the 
authority of individual states to
impose unlimited liability on parties responsible for discharging 
oil.  The Act also prescribes
response planning and execution responsibilities for government 
entities, as well as owners and
operators of vessels and facilities.  Further, OPA 90 mandates new 
prevention measures
involving vessel construction and operation.
<p>
Ports recognize the need to deal with environmental issues in a 
more timely fashion and are
developing strategies to address potential delays and costs 
associated with environmental
regulations.  They understand the need to develop long-term plans 
to meet environmental
concerns.  They are becoming more proactive and involved with the 
environmental and
regulatory communities so that port issues can be resolved early in 
the regulatory process. 
Recognizing the need to identify environmental implications from 
the onset, the industry is 
working with regulators and interest groups to improve the permit 
processes, to clarify rules
and to develop consistent standards.  Ports understand the need to 
demonstrate their economic
importance to the communities they serve.  Ports, environmental 
groups, and regulatory
agencies are working in a more cooperative framework in the search 
for solutions to complex
problems that affect the environment, economic growth, and 
transportation services.
<p>
<hr>
<hr>
</body>
</html>

