<html>
<head>
<title>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</title>
<!pn= arpt2s2d.txt/page edited on 12/11/96blh->

</head>
<body>
<center><b>PORT ISSUES</b></center>
<p>

<center><b>DREDGING AND DREDGED MATERIAL DISPOSAL</b></center>
<p>
One of the primary goals of the U.S. transportation system is to 
facilitate the efficient and
secure movement of people and cargo in domestic and international 
waterborne commerce in
order to promote America's economic growth and international 
competitiveness in a safe and
healthy environment.  To accomplish this, the Nation's ports and 
harbors need to be maintained
and improved.  However, the continued development and maintenance 
of U.S. ports has
become an increasing challenge, particularly in the area of 
dredging and dredged material
management.  The past two decades have witnessed increasing 
environmental awareness and
mounting environmental problems affecting coastal areas and ocean 
waters.  During the same
time, increasing world trade and rapid evolution of shipping 
practices and technology,
including containerization and intermodalism, have increased the 
need for port and harbor development.
<p>
Ports play an essential and growing role in the United States' 
economy.  Foreign trade accounts
for over 20 percent of our Gross Domestic Product and this 
percentage is growing.
Approximately 95 percent of all U.S. exports and imports pass 
through ports.  The critical role
of the U.S. ports in world trade makes it essential that harbors 
and channels be maintained and
improved.  However, most of the Nation's harbors and channels are 
not naturally deep to
accommodate modern vessels, and dredging becomes essential to the 
maintenance of our ports. 
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Dredging and Disposal of Dredged Materials</b>
<p>
There are over 400 ports and 25,000 miles of navigation channels 
throughout the United States,
that must be maintained to keep waterborne traffic moving 
efficiently and safely.  Annually, the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers (Corps) dredges approximately 400 
million cubic yards (mcy) --
300 mcy from Federally maintained channels and harbors.  Permit 
applicants (e.g., port authorities, terminal operators and other 
private industry) apply to the Corps for an additional 
100 million cubic yards of dredging annually from navigation 
projects (berths, access channels,
etc).  About 60 million cubic yards are placed in ocean waters at 
more than 100 Environmental
Protection Agency (EPA) approved sites.  The remaining 340 million 
cubic yards are dredged
in coastal and inland waters and placed in a variety of locations, 
including uplands, beach sites,
wetlands and construction sites.
<p>
The Corps reviews projects and issues permits for dredging and 
dredged material disposal in
accordance with Section 10 of Rivers and Harbors Act (RHA), Section 
404 of the Clean Water
Act (CWA--when the discharge is proposed in waters of the U.S.) and 
Section 103 of the
Marine Protection, Research and Sanctuaries Act (MPRSA--when the 
discharge is proposed in
the territorial sea or the oceans).  Under the CWA and the MPRSA, 
the EPA is responsible for
developing the environmental criteria used by the Corps to evaluate 
the disposal of dredged
materials for environmental oversight.  The Corps has the authority 
to issue or deny permits under these statutes.
<p>
Ideally, dredging permit applicants submit complete and technically 
adequate project
applications to the Corps and other review agencies for prompt 
review and decision and to
evaluate the risks and uncertainties associated with the proposed 
project.  Dredged material
testing results provide enough information to assess the 
environmental impacts of dredged
material disposal at the proposed disposal site.  Information is 
then shared among all relevant
stakeholders, from Federal and state agencies to the general 
public; and Congress expeditiously
reviews, authorizes, and funds essential new Federal navigation 
projects.  However, for a
broad range of reasons, dredging projects can become stalled in the 
review process.  
<p>
In some coastal ports, the main concern is the presence of 
contaminated sediments and the lack
or shortage of disposal capacity for contaminated dredged 
materials.  Dredging and disposal of
dredged materials contribute to resuspension of sediments.  The 
redistribution of contaminants
into the ambient environment can cause environmental problems 
including risks to human
health.  Scientific concerns about these issues have led to changes
in the national testing 
protocols for dredged materials rendering them more stringent.  As 
a result of the new testing
requirements, the volume of contaminated sediments has increased.  
Historically, contaminated
sediments accounted for five percent of the annual volume of 
dredged material.  While it is too
early to examine the impact of the new testing nationally, at least 
one port reported that
contaminated sediments represented 75 percent of the dredged 
material.  Further, uncertainties
related to implementation of these revised protocols coupled with 
the shortage or lack of
disposal options have contributed to delays in dredging.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>New Initiatives</b>
<p>
Recognizing the important role ports play in the U. S. economy, 
defense and environment, the
President, on August 13, 1993, acknowledged that the process for 
dredging and maintaining the
Nation's ports sometimes does not work as well as it could.  As a 
result, the Secretary of
Transportation convened the Interagency Working Group on the 
Dredging Process in October
1993, led by the Maritime Administration, to investigate and 
recommend actions to improve the
dredging project review process.
<p>
The Working Group had two major objectives:
<p>
o    Promote greater certainty and predictability in the dredging 
project review process and
     dredged material management, and
<p>
o    Facilitate effective long-term management strategies for 
addressing dredging and disposal
     needs at both the national and local levels.
<p>
The Group delivered a report to the Secretary of Transportation, 
"The Dredging Process in the
United States: An Action Plan for Improvement," in December 1994, 
which was adopted by six
Federal Agencies. The Action Plan contains 18 recommendations and 
a statement of  National
Dredging Policy.  The President endorsed the National Dredging 
Policy (see Figure 4), on June
22, 1995, and directed the Federal agencies to implement the Action Plan.
<p>
The Working Group categorized the problems that slow down the 
dredging process and
provided recommendations in the following four major areas: strengthening 
planning mechanisms, enhancing coordination and communication in the 
dredging project approval
process, addressing scientific uncertainties about dredged material 
and funding dredging
projects consistently and efficiently.
<p>
On July 20, 1995, Administration officials established a National 
Dredging Team--an
outgrowth of the Working Group.  The purpose of the Team is to 
assure that dredging of U.S.
harbors and channels is conducted in a timely and cost-effective 
manner, while ensuring
environmental protection.  The Team also monitors implementation of 
the Action Plan and
develops national guidance on issues affecting the dredging process.  
The Team is co-chaired
by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and U.S. Environmental 
Protection Agency and includes
the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, the U.S. Maritime 
Administration, and the U.S. National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Marine Fisheries 
Service and Office of
Ocean and Coastal Resource Management.  The agencies have sent 
guidance to their field
offices to establish regional dredging teams to address specific 
regional concerns characteristic
of local and regional dredging issues.  The Regional Dredging Teams 
are being established and
include the same Federal agencies that participate in the National 
Team, as well as state resource agencies.
<p>
National and Regional Teams provide a reliable basis for 
interagency coordination and
increased predictability in the dredging process.  In addition, the 
agencies will be engaged in
long-term planning with the ports and affected stakeholders to 
prevent problems from arising in
the future.  The National Dredging Team will provide guidance to 
assist in the development of
long-term dredged material management plans for major ports and 
harbors in the United States. 
As the Department considers reauthorization of the Intermodal 
Surface Transportation
Efficiency Act of 1991, promoting improved connections among modes 
will continue to be
important.  Key considerations toward that end are how to ensure 
efficient access to ports and
better coordinate port access requirements in the transportation 
planning processes.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>National Dredging Policy (Figure 4)</b>
<p>
o  A network of ports and harbors is essential to the United 
States's economy, affecting its competitiveness in world trade and 
national security.  Port facilities serve as a key link in the
intermodal transportation chain and can realize their full potential
as magnets for shipping and commenrce only if dredging occurs
in a timely and cost-effective manners.
<p>
o  The nation's coastal, ocean, and freshwater resources are critcal 
assets which must be protected, conserved, and restored.  These 
resources are equally important to the United States by providing 
numerous economic and environmental benefits.
<p>
o  Consistent and integrated application of existing environmental 
statutes can protect the environment and can allow for sustainable 
economic growth.
<p>
o  Close coordination and planning at all governmental levels, and 
with all aspects of the private sector, are essential to developing 
and maintaining the nation's ports and harbors in a manner that will 
increase economic growth and protect, conserve, and restore coastal 
resources.
<p>
o  Planning for the development and maintenance of the nation's 
ports and harbors should occur in the context of broad transportation 
and environmental planning efforts such as the National Transportation 
System and the ecosystem/watershed management approach.
<p>
o  The regulatory process must be timely, efficient, and predictable, 
to the maximum extent possible.
<p>
o  Advanced dredged material management planning must be conducted on 
a port or regional scale by a partnership that includes the Federal 
government, the port authorities, state and local governments, natural 
resource agencies, public interest groups, the maritime industry, and 
private citizens.  To be effective, this planning must be doe prior 
to individual Federal or non-Federal dredging project proponents seeking  
individual project approval.
<p>
o  Dredged material managers must become more involved in watershed 
planning to emphasize the importance of point and non-point source 
pollution controls to reduce harbor sediment contamination.
<p>
o  Dredged material is a resource, and environmentally-sound 
beneficial use of dredged material for such projects as wetlands 
creation, beach nourishment, and development projects must be 
encouraged.
<p>
<hr>
<hr>
<p>
</body>
</html>


