<body text="#000000">
<A><center><h4>U.S. PUBLIC PORTS ANNUAL REPORT<BR>
PORT ISSUES<BR> 
Introduction and Index</h4></center></a>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Introduction</b>
<p>
The public port industry is faced with an ever increasing number 
of complex issues.  Today's port organizations must address issues 
ranging from financing current operations and future terminal development
to complying with environmental laws and regulations, which impact
most port activities.  For example, reliable and secure funding sources
are necessary to finance the development programs required to meet 
future trade growth.  Ports need a predictable, timely, and efficient 
dredging process to allow them to maintain and improve channels 
and to dispose of contaminated dredged material.  Our Nation's  
growing dependence on intermodal transportation means that the port 
industry must improve landside access to marine terminals and become
more involved in local community planning.  The port industry's 
ability to resolve these issues is critical not only to the industry
but to the Nation, because of the key role ports play in our intermodal
transportation system.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<center><b>Index</b></center>
<p>
