</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</title>
<!pn=arpt2s2a.htm/page edited on 11/29/96blh->
<!page called by arpt2s2m.htm->
<head>
<body>

<h4><center>PORT ISSUES</center></h4> 
<p>
<b>PORT DEVELOPMENT FINANCING AND REVENUES</b>
<p>
Financing capital development programs and generating sufficient 
revenue streams remain two key issues for public ports.  In 1994, 
the American Association of Port Authorities
identified facility development and capital financing as the number 
one issue facing the port
industry.   With tonnage expected to double by the year 2010, ports 
need to expand existing
infrastructure and terminal facilities to accommodate this 
projected growth.  The present
political and economic situation is creating doubts as to how ports 
will finance these
development programs. The fiscal sentiment of many local 
communities makes raising
revenues through increased taxes unrealistic.  State and local 
governments, with their own
budget and revenue problems, continue to demand that ports become 
more financially self-sufficient.  Potentially affecting both 
issues is the relatively recent development of global
alliances among a number of U.S. and foreign carriers.  These new 
alliances allow traditional
competitors to improve their operating efficiencies and reduce 
costs by pooling their
resources, which includes consolidation of their port operations. 
Although it is too early to
see the fall-out from this, among the possible outcomes resulting 
from these carrier alliances
are fewer port tenants and a downward pressure on port tariffs and 
fees.  Carrier alliances are
likely to have greater leverage with ports than a single carrier in 
negotiating favorable tariffs, fees, financing, and services. 
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>Financing Capital Expenditures</b>
<p>
With budgetary shortfalls and the growing demand for public 
services, ports continue to face
stiff competition for scarce public funds.  Given this fiscal 
climate, ports are confronted with
a serious problem of convincing local communities of their need for 
public support in
financing capital programs.  Complicating the situation is the fact 
that many economic
benefits resulting from port investments extend beyond the local 
community or region to
distant communities where exports are produced and imports consumed.

<p>
The port industry's funding pattern for capital programs changed in 
1994.  The primary funding sources through 1993 were port revenues 
and revenue bonds with a combined usage
of 73 percent in 1993.  In 1994, the funding pattern changed to 
port revenues and "other"
(includes state transportation trust funds, state and local 
appropriations, property/sales taxes,
and lease revenues), which accounted for 56 percent of the 
industry's funding.  As a percentage of the total funding sources, 
the use of revenue bonds fell off sharply, from a high
of 40 percent in 1990, to 23 percent in 1993 and 15 percent in 1994.  
"Other" (at 21 percent) and loans (at 16 percent) supplanted revenue 
bonds in 1994 as preferred financing methods,
with port revenues leading at 35 percent.  While the cause of this 
shift is unclear, it may be
an indication that ports are seeking or using non-traditional 
funding sources, i.e. "other,"
when they are available.  The results of future surveys will 
determine whether this shift is an
anomaly or a new trend.
<p>
The funding pattern shifts again when we look at projected future 
funding sources for 1995-1999.  For this period, revenue bonds lead 
with 49 percent while port revenues are a distant
second at 22.5 percent.  The "other" category represents 14 percent 
while loans are 2
percent.  If 1995-1999 projections are correct and port revenues 
and revenue bonds continue
as the primary funding sources, the crucial question is whether 
ports can generate sufficient
income to support this type of financing.
<p>
In terms of capital expenditures, the importance of funding can be 
seen by examining the
1994 capital program for the top 10 ports.  The results show that 
one port exceeded $430
million with the remaining nine ports ranging from $77.5 million 
down to $15 million.  When
considering 5-year projections (1995-1999), estimated total capital 
expenditures exceed $1
billion at one port with the other nine ports ranging from $895 
million down to $153 million. 
Given the magnitude of these capital programs, the issue of funding 
is critical to the public port industry's future. 
<p>
In terms of capital financing, a worst-case scenario for the port 
industry is found in
California, where state legislation permitted local municipalities
to require payments from their local port:
<p>
     o    California enacted legislation in 1991 
          allowing five cities to require payments
          from their local port's reserves to offset 
          the loss of funds formerly provided
          by the state;
<p>
     o    During fiscal years 1991-92 and 1992-93, 
          the ports of Los Angeles and Long Beach 
          gave their cities $69 million and $21 million, 
          respectively;
<p>
     o    In June 1995, the City of Los Angeles released 
          a city-commissioned study, which found that the 
          city could charge its port for municipal services, 
          such as police and fire protection, and not 
          violate state laws;
<p>
     o    In August 1995, as partial payment of its 
          $90 million bill (for municipal services 
          rendered over 18 years), the Port of Los Angeles 
          transferred $20 million to the city.  That 
          transfer is now being challenged by the California
          State Lands Commission which is threatening to sue 
          both the city and the port unless the city returns 
          the $20 million.  The city and state have agreed
          that no additional fund transfers will take place 
          in the mean time.  (Note: In May 1996, an additional 
          transfer of $20 million was made.)

<p>
The impact of this legislation has disrupted development plans, 
caused uncertainty in credit
markets, and upset port users.  This situation exists to a lesser 
degree in other states where port
funds have been utilized to finance nonmaritime projects.
<p>
In another development, six California ports created a joint 
financing authority in November
1995 to issue bonds on behalf of individual ports.  The California 
Maritime Infrastructure
Authority will provide ports with an alternative vehicle for 
issuing bonds when municipal
restrictions prevent or delay port plans to float bond issues on 
their own.  The authority will
work with a maritime infrastructure bank created in 1993-94 
(see next paragraph) as a conduit
for Federal and state funds to be loaned for port projects.  The 
authority will have no debt
rating of its own, and member ports are not responsible for the
debts of other ports.
<p>
The maritime infrastructure bank mentioned above was created in 
1993 and is called the
California Maritime Infrastructure Bank.  Its purpose is to promote 
the growth of international
trade flowing through California's port system and state economic 
growth.  Envisioned as a
type of credit union for ports, the bank was to finance both public 
and private port projects.  To
date, one airport project was funded and one port project is 
pending.  State legislation is being
proposed to establish a permanent source of funding for the bank.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Revenue Generation</b>
<p>
Two factors which commonly hinder a port's ability to generate 
revenue are strong national and
international competition and excess capacity.  Acting together, 
the two tend to exert downward
pressures on both rates charged for port services and, ultimately, 
port revenue.  In addition,
port revenues are tied closely to and dependent upon regional and 
national economies.
<p>
The data exhibited in Tables 28 and 29 summarize the port 
industry's 1994 net income.  These
figures show that 78 percent (43 ports) of those surveyed reported 
net profits, and 22 percent
(12 ports) had losses.  Although both the percentage and number of 
profitable ports increased
from 67 percent (38 ports) in 1992, most profits continued to fall 
under $5 million.  The
figures continue to reflect the industry's low profitability in 
relation to the potential revenues
required to finance day-to-day operations and capital development 
programs.
A knowledge of typical pricing practices used by public ports for 
services, facilities, and
equipment is useful in understanding the industry's low profit 
margins.  There are two main
philosophies on the role of public ports.  The more prevalent one 
in the industry is that ports
are to promote regional economic development and to create jobs. 
The second belief holds that
public ports are to be profit-making enterprises.  Emphasizing 
economic development, most
ports attempt to combine these two philosophies, with mixed results.  
Thus, while many ports
advocate a pricing policy that both covers their costs and provides 
an adequate return on investment, very few achieve it.  
<p>
Focusing on economic development tends to depress price levels for 
the whole industry.  Public
ports rely on price and service competition to attract and hold 
business.  Price competition
tends to lower revenues while service competition may require 
additional investments in
facilities and equipment.  One consequence of price/service 
competition is that many ports rely
on state and local subsidies to cover financial shortfalls. 
<p>
The economic costs of following price/service competition 
ultimately may force the port
industry to reexamine these practices.  By exploring the potential 
benefits of regional
cooperation within the context of the antitrust immunity which they 
are allowed by statute,
public ports may realize both substantial savings and improved 
profitability, while improving
their competitive standing nationally and internationally.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h5><a href="arpt2s2m.htm">Return to Port Issues Index</a></h5>
<p>
</body>
</html>

</DOC>
