<html>                   
<head>
<title>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</TITLE>

<!pn=speech.htm/html edit date 10/18/96blh->
<!page called by whatsnew.htm 10/18/96blh->
</head>
<body>
<b>
<center>Remarks as Prepared for Delivery</center>
<p>
<center>VADM Albert J. Herberger, USN ((Ret)</center>
<p>
<center>70th American Merchant Marine and Maritime Industry</center>
<p>
<center>Propeller Club Conference</center>
<p>
<center>Theme: "National Maritime Policy - On or Off Course?"</center>
<p>
<center>Keynote Address</center>
<p>
<center>Tuesday, 15 October 1996, 1230</center>
</b>
<p>
<p>

      Let me begin by thanking Dan Smith for the invitation to speak to this distinguished
maritime industry forum.  It's always a pleasure for me to be with you.  I also want to
congratulate the Propeller Club on the occasion of their 70th convention here in historic
Baltimore harbor.  Coming right on the heels of the President's signing the Maritime Security
Act last Tuesday, the timing of this convention could not have been better.  
<br>
<p>
      Last year at the Buffalo convention I spoke with you about one of the most critical
issues on the national maritime agenda -- the Maritime Security Program.  This is the
program that would safeguard America's future as a maritime nation.  It would ensure that
American ships, crewed by skilled and loyal American civilian seafarers, would support our
economic and sealift defense requirements.   
<br>
<p>
      Many of you in this audience have worked non-stop together with us as well as
individually to get the message out on this program.   Like Churchill 55 years ago, all we
asked from Congress was to "give us the tools" to make sure that our nation's imports and
exports would be transported during peace and war.  
<br>
<p>
      Today I'm here to tell you that after a long, hard, and uphill struggle we finally have
those "tools" with the enactment of this new bill.  A bill that clearly demonstrates the strong
bipartisan support of Congress.  A bill that passed the Senate by a landslide vote of 88 to 10.  
A bill that the House approved last December and twice voted for overwhelmingly in 1993
and 1994.  
<br><p>
      Last Tuesday an historic moment occurred for the industry when the President signed
the Maritime Security Act.  The last time Congress had enacted any major maritime
legislation was the Merchant Marine Act of 1970.
<br>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<center>-2-</center>
<br><p>
      Now, nearly a quarter of a century later, the President, with just a stroke of a pen, was
putting a foundation in place for a strong U.S.-flag merchant marine.  He was also providing
proof of his determination to support the industry and preserve jobs for American citizens.  
<br><p>
      I want to express my deepest thanks and appreciation to all here, the Propeller Club
and, in particular, the Women's Propeller Club, as well as those in the industry who worked
so hard to help us make this program a reality.  It has taken the entire maritime community,
pulling together, to raise our nation's consciousness about the value of the American merchant
marine and the industry.   
<br><p>
      And as the groundswell of support keeps growing, let there be no doubt.  We intend to
keep our message right in front of the American people so that every citizen will understand
how important the maritime industry is to this country.  
<br><p>
      Let me emphasize some of the highlights of the Maritime Security Program.  
<br>      
<pre><b>
        It's a 10-year program providing funding 
         of up to $100 million annually for up to
         47 vessels.  That's half the cost of the 
         old Operating Differential Subsidy (ODS) 
         program.

        The Program will support an active, privately 
         owned, U.S.-flag and U.S.-crewed merchant 
         shipping fleet to provide sealift sustainment 
         in a contingency.  Let me take a moment to 
         address sealift.  
</b></pre>
<br><p>
      Six years ago, before the Berlin Wall crumbled in November of 1989, we had a
National Security Sealift Policy in place.  That mandate required the U.S. commercial ocean
carrier industry unilaterly -- to the extent it's  capable -- provide sealift in peace, crisis and
war.  
<br><p>
      Moreover, that mandate further required -- through law and regulation -- that we
promote the U.S. merchant marine and its supporting industries so that critical national
security requirements could be met.   
<br><p>
      We have hammered away at those critics who would have utter disregard for the
policy put in place to maintain this country's national security interests.  And we intend to
keep hammering away at them.  
<br><p>
      One of the follow-on requirements of the new legislation is that participating
shipowners must enroll in an Emergency Preparedness Program -- the mechanism in which
carriers will provide origin to destination transportation during military contingencies.   
<br><p>
<hr>
<p>
<center>-3-</center>
<br><p>
      The Program will give the Department of Defense access to the shipping companies'
worldwide intermodal networks: the vessels, the trains, the trucks, the cargo handling
equipment, the tracking and control systems, and even the traffic and logistics management
services.   By packaging all these elements, we capitalize on the assets of a multibillion dollar
capital base while maximizing the industry's modern door-to-door transportation capabilities.   
<br><p>

      Moreover, the carriers maintain their flexibility by pooling their resources and
rationalizing their services.
<br><p>
      So we get even more bang for the buck by expanding total sealift capability.  Here we
have a total package in which the carriers can transport the cargo from the factory or fort to
the frontline.  There isn't a more cost-effective and efficient game plan around to supplement
sealift capability than this.  
<br><p>
      Right now, we're ready to roll and get the gears going on this legislation.  We now
have a policy and a program that guarantees modern commercial vessels will continue to 
<br><p>
<pre><b>
        fly our flag; 
        promote our commerce; 
        employ skilled American seafarers, and 
        answer the call to serve our country 
         whenever needed.    
</b></pre>
<br><p>
      And on that same tack, let's not forget that the critics are still out there blasting away
at the Jones Act.  We are continuing our efforts to counteract their distortions and untruths.  
<br><p>
      Let me again point out the Jones Act facts to you.
<br><p>
<pre><b>
        The Jones Act generates 125,000 jobs 
         for American citizens and touches every
         region of the nation including 20,000 workers 
         here in the North Atlantic region of the
         country.

        More than 80 million passengers and 1 billion 
         tons of cargo worth about $222 billion get 
         transported under the Jones Act trade.  That's 
         30% of the cargo in America for just 2% of the 
         entire domestic freight bill.

        The Jones Act supports an economic infrastructure 
         of $26 billion.  That's a capital investment with 
         sunk costs made by thousands of American companies.  

</b></pre>
<hr><p>
<center>-4-</center>
<br><p>
      Here are the national security reasons:  
<br><p>
<pre><b>
        The Jones Act guarantees our nation's control 
         of essential transportation assets and their 
         related infrastructure in both peace and war.  

        The Jones Act makes certain that U.S.-owned, 
         U.S.-crewed, and U.S.-built ships will be 
         there to transport domestic cargo during a 
         national emergency.
</b></pre>  
<br><p>
      It's America keeping American assets and American interests under American control. 
It's the principle of sovereignty.  Every nation in the world, new and not so new, exercises
sovereignty over their domain.  As the greatest trading nation on the face of this earth, should
we do any less?
<br><p>
      We are a maritime nation whose American carriers and maritime unions have
pioneered the most innovative transportation technologies copied the world over.  
<br><p>
      We are a seafaring nation whose shipbuilders continue to build the most sophisticated,
high quality naval vessels known to the world.  And they are transitioning those highly
specialized skills to the commercial sector.   
<br><p>
      Commercial shipbuilding in America is making a comeback.  America's shipbuilders
are coming back into commercial shipbuilding -- made possible by their initiatives and two
National Shipbuilding Initiative programs, Title XI and MARITECH.
<br><p>
      As many of you know, the National Shipbuilding Initiative authorized Title XI
financing expanded authority to grant loan guarantees in two new directions: shipyard
modernizations and export projects such as the vessels built in U.S. shipyards but owned
under foreign registries.
<br><p>
      Thus far, we've approved over $2 billion in projects for 4 shipyard modernizations and
251 vessels.  This includes 13 double hull tankers and 2 double-hull chemical tankers meeting
OPA and IMO requirements as well as 196 liquid, dry cargo and power barges.
<br><p>
      Let me give you a few examples.  Over two years ago the National Steel and
Shipbuilding Company, known as NASSCO, received the first shipyard modernization loan
guarantee for $23 million to support its $26 million modernization project.  NASSCO made
capital improvements in their ship design and technology processes as well as investing in its
facilities, building a 175 ton gantry crane.  

<br><p>
<hr><p>
<center>-5-</center>
<br><p>
      Since the loan guarantee, not only are NASSCO's facilities more competitive but
they've performed contracts more efficiently and effectively.  The Title XI investment in
NASSCO has saved the government millions of dollars on Navy contracts.   
<br><p>
      In the export market arena we approved a $134 million loan guarantee for Fleves
Shipping Corporation, an affiliate of Eletson Holding Corporation in Greece.  Newport News
Shipbuilding & Drydock Company is now constructing four double-hull product tankers at a
cost of $153 million for Fleves.  The first tanker will be launched next January.  
<br><p>
      Another export project is the $47 million loan guarantee for Dannebrog Rederi of
Denmark.  The guarantee covers the construction of two double-hull tankers to be built at
Alabama Shipyard in Mobile.  The first tanker will be launched next June.  
<br><p>
      The other National Shipbuilding Initiative that is an outstanding success is
MARITECH.  This is a five-year research and development program that develops advanced
technology to improve shipyard competitiveness.
<br><p>
      MARITECH focuses on manufacturing and information technologies for ship design
and production.  It matches industry investment with federal funds on a competitive basis. 
Now in its third year, it has $150 million in ongoing projects and has generated 36 new
commercial ship designs thus far.  
<br><p>
       All of these elements are part and parcel of the new course we're charting in maritime
strategy.  And in charting that course we realize that we must develop a better blueprint for
our ports.  There's a lot of major challenges for them on the horizon.  
<br><p>
      One issue is dredging and the disposal of dredged material.  While we have National
and Regional Dredging Teams in place and we're making some progress, it's still going too
slow.
<br><p>
      In his address to the American Association of Port Authorities last month Secretary
Pea spoke about the dynamic change transforming the global economy and in particular our
ports.  The Department has developed a multi-agency strategy to address the dredging issue
and the Secretary is preparing to fully implement that strategy.  So we're hopeful that we'll
see some speedy progress shortly. 
<br><p>
      Another problem is land and waterside access.  One-half of all our ports and nearly
2/3 of our container ports will see congestion increase on major truck routes serving the
terminals.  The reauthorization of ISTEA, the Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency
Act, presents an opportunity to address and potentially fund some of these access problems.  
<br><p>
<hr><p>
<center>-6-</center>
<br><p>
      The Department of Transportation has just concluded a series of 13 outreach meetings
in September throughout the country on a range of issues from planning to global economy
and safety.   We're working hard with industry in this area to develop action plans.  But we
need to turn the burner up on these issues as well.  
<br><p>
      Let me conclude by saying that the policies we now have in place will bring the
outright hemorraghing of our industry to a stop.  
<br><p>
      We have a three-pronged strategy that's simple, sound and straight-forward -- the
National Shipbuilding Initiative, the Jones Act and now the Maritime Security Act.  
<br><p>
      These initiatives will propel us forward.  They will be our markers as we chart the
new maritime agenda for the 21st century.  
<br><p>
      Your conference theme, "National Maritime Policy -- On or Off Course?"  We're
getting back on course.  It's up to us to keep the momentum going.  We need to keep pulling
together.  We need to keep putting our message out there.  We need to keep our merchant
marine and our maritime industry on "all ahead."  All of us, together, on "all ahead."  
<br><p>
<center>* * * * *</center>

</body>
