<body>
<h1>Jones Act -- Essential Element of
Maritime Program</h1>
<u><b>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</b></u><p>

Wednesday, June 12, 1996					<p>

<b>JONES ACT, DOMESTIC SHIPPING INDUSTRY <p>

SUPPORT NATIONAL AND ECONOMIC SECURITY,<p>

MARITIME ADMINISTRATOR TELLS CONGRESS</b><p>

<p>

	Echoing President Clinton's commitment to American shipping, Maritime Administrator <a href="VAAJHERB.TXT">Albert
J. Herberger</a> told a Congressional subcommittee today that the domestic shipping industry is an
essential part of the nationwide intermodal transportation system and serves America's national
and economic security needs dependably and efficiently. <p>

	Admiral Herberger spoke as part of a forum on domestic shipping held by the House
subcommittee on Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation.<p>

	"We have a robust domestic shipping industry providing efficient, environmentally sound
transportation and supporting thousands of jobs for American citizens," the admiral said.<p>

	The forum focused on America's coastwise trade laws, often called the Jones Act, which
generally require that U.S.-built, crewed, owned and registered vessels be used in the nation's
domestic waterborne commerce.<p>

	The purpose of the Jones Act, Herberger said, "is to maintain reliable domestic shipping
services and to ensure the existence of a domestic maritime industry available and subject to
national control in time of need."<p>

	"The Administration supports the Jones Act as an essential element of U.S. maritime policy,"
he emphasized.  "It will continue to serve the nation's interests well into the 21st century."<p>

	As an example of the importance to defense of the Jones Act, Herberger told the
Subcommittee that dry cargo ships and tankers were chartered by the Pentagon during the
Persian Gulf conflict.  In addition, many seafarers who normally crew Jones Act vessels
volunteered to crew government-owned ships to support U.S. forces.<p>

<p>

	Addressing economic and environmental contributions, Herberger said Jones Act vessels
employ about 80,000 American citizens, generate another 44,000 jobs in the shipbuilding, ship
repair and related industries and support $26 billion in capital investment.<p>

	"Domestic vessel owners must comply with U.S. labor, environmental, safety, and tax laws
and regulations, and by doing so, they protect our waterways and workers," he said.<p>

	In addition, Jones Act workers "pay federal, state and local taxes and their salaries contribute
to the well-being of local economies throughout the nation," he added.<p>

	As for efficiency, domestic shipping moves over 30 percent of the cargo in America annually
at less than 2 percent of the entire domestic freight bill, he said. <p>

<center>###<p>

<p>

<i>An electronic version of this document can be obtained via the World Wide Web at:<p>

http://www.dot.gov/affairs/index.htm</i>
</center>
</body>
