<title>MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</title>

<!CreatedBy Vontell Tucker 5/21/96, content=WP Internet Publisher 6.1->

</head>
<body>
<h1>Merchant Marine Memorial Service</h1>
<p>

<p>

<img src="vontel.jpg" alt="Memorial Service Program" width="750" height="750"><p>

<p>

<hr>
<p>

 <p>

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE,                                                         MAR 05-96<p>

Tuesday, May 21, 1996                                                                       Contact:  John Swank<p>

													     Tel.:  (202) 366-5807<p>

<p>

<b>NATION TO OBSERVE NATIONAL MARITIME DAY;<p>

MAY 22 EVENTS SCHEDULED IN WASHINGTON, D.C.</b><p>

<p>

	In New York, a wreath will be laid at the Merchant Marine Memorial in Battery Park.  In
Norfolk, one will be placed in the water from a riverboat.  A training ship will host a ceremony
in New Orleans; there will be a luncheon in Houston; war veterans will sponsor a San Francisco
celebration; and in Washington, D.C., government officials, labor leaders, industry
representatives and mariners will mark the day in the Hubert Humphrey Building's Great Hall.<p>

	 Since 1933, each year the President of the United States has called on the people of the United
States to observe May 22 as National Maritime Day, and 1996 is no different.  President Clinton,
too, proclaimed the day a special time to honor the heroism of seafarers.<p>

<p>

	"The men and women who serve aboard U.S. vessels, and in supporting industries, remain
prepared to support the Nation in times of crisis.  Their outstanding professionalism and heroic
performance have been evident throughout our Nation's history -- most recently in Vietnam, the
Persian Gulf, Haiti and Somalia.  Now these men and women continue to bring great honor, not
only to themselves, but also to the entire maritime community through their support of our troops
in Bosnia," President Clinton stated.<p>

<center>-more-</center>
<p>

<center>-2-</center>
<p>

"Seafarers from the United States have braved peacekeeping and humanitarian missions
throughout history.  Their contribution has been unstinting and professional.  I salute them for
their performance in peace and war," Secretary of Transportation Federico Pe&ntilde;a said.<p>

<p>

	During World War II, 733 American cargo ships were lost and more than 6,000 civilian
American seafarers were killed as a result of enemy action.  After World War II, many inland
states joined in saluting the merchant marine for its heroic contributions.<p>

<p>

	Today, most National Maritime Day observances are held in the nation's port cities.  But the
many civilian merchant mariners who lost their lives in wartime service are still remembered in
the Nation's Capital.<p>

<p>

	At 11:00 a.m. Wednesday, government officials, members of Congress, merchant marine war
veterans, active civilian seafarers, maritime industry and labor leaders, and others will gather in
the Great Hall of the Hubert Humphrey Building, 200 Independence Avenue, S.W. for the annual
Merchant Marine Memorial Service. The public is welcome at the ceremony. <p>

<p>

	Speakers will include Deputy Secretary of Transportation Mortimer Downey; Michael Sacco,
president, Maritime Trades Department, AFL-CIO; and Maritime Administrator Albert J.
Herberger.  Tributes from members of Congress and industry leaders also are expected.<p>

<p>

	Music will be provided by the Department of Transportation's choir along with Ms. Erin Gantt, a
1983 graduate of the U.S. Merchant Marine Academy.  The academy's color guard and chaplain
also will participate.<p>

<p>

	Related May 22 Washington area events include:<p>

<p>

	11:45 a.m. - National Maritime Day Luncheon sponsored by the Propeller Club of the United
States.  Speakers: Vice Adm. Albert J. Herberger, Maritime administrator; Rear Adm. Thomas J.
Matteson, superintendent, U.S. Merchant Marine Academy; and Michael Sacco, president,
Maritime Trades Department, AFL-CIO.  Location: U.S. Senate Hart Office Building. 
Reservations are required, and the contact is Tina Hammonds, (301) 423-3335.<p>

<p>

<p>

	4:00 p.m. - Military Sealift Command's National Maritime Day Wreath Laying Ceremony,
United States Navy Memorial, 701 Pennsylvania Ave., N.W.  The public is welcome.  Call (202)
685-5055 for additional information.<p>

<p>

	Bowie Baysox National Maritime Day celebration, before its 7:05 p.m. game with Canton
Indians.  Prince George's Stadium.  <p>

<p>

	The Maritime Administration's exhibit on the role of the U.S. Merchant Marine during World
War II is on display at the U.S. Navy Memorial throughout May.  It also will be in the lobby of
the U.S. Department of Transportation building, 400 Seventh St. S.W., during the week of May
20, as well as at the May 22 Bowie Baysox game.<p>

<p>

<center>###<p>

</center>
<p>

An electronic version of this document can be obtained via the World Wide Web at:<p>

http://www.dot.gov/affairs/index.htm
</body>
</html>
