<body bgcolor="#e6e6fa">

<center><h4>BROCHURE</h4></center>
<p>
<center><H4>NATIONAL MARITIME RESOURCE AND EDUCATION CENTER</H4></center>         
<p>
        <I>The Maritime Administration as the U. S. Government's 
commercial shipbuilding advocate has established the National 
Maritime Resource and Education Center to assist the U.S. shipbuilding 
and allied industries in improving their competitiveness in the 
international commercial market. The center will be a major 
information source and facilitator within the government for 
the maritime industry by providing expertise, information and 
reference material on commercial shipbuilding. <P>
        
        The Center's near term focus is presented, but this 
is just the beginning of a continuous process to acquire and 
maintain marine standards, develop and conduct seminars and 
workshops, and provide other information to assist the industry.
The Center's program will adapt to meet those industry needs as 
they are identified. We will promote positive interaction between 
the industry and MARAD. We encourage input and recommendations from 
industry on ways to improve the Center's programs.<P> 

        MARAD will serve as the focal point within government, 
working closely within other government agencies and departments, 
standards developers and regulatory bodies and the marine industry, 
to move America forward in the international commercial maritime market.</I><P>

                                        <B><I>Albert J. Herberger,<br> 
                                        Maritime Administrator</B></I>
<P>
<HR>
<p>
National Maritime Resource and Education Center near term focus:<P>
<UL>
<LI>Marine Industry Standards Library
<LI>ISO 9000 Information/Assistance
<LI>USCG Interface for Implementing consensus Standards in lieu of Regulations
<LI>Support to ISO Technical Advisory Group(U.S. TAG to ISO/TC-8)
<LI>Collaboration with ARPA for Funding Shipyards to Establish Commercial Ship Designs
<LI>MARAD Guideline Specifications Update
<LI>Three-Dimensional CAD Library
<LI>Metrication
<LI>Marine Environmental Protection Information
</UL><P>

        The Marine Industry Standards Library is staffed and operational.
International, foreign and domestic standards are available. Searches 
may be performed by subject matter or standard number. Regulatory 
documents are being acquired from the International Maritime 
Organization(IMO) and the U.S. Coast Guard(USCG). Rules, 
standards and guides are being acquired from International Association 
of Classification Societies(IACS) and American Bureau of Shipping(ABS). 
Technical assistance is available to the marine industry for questions 
on standards and applications. There is a nominal charge for obtaining 
requested standards.<P>

        ISO 9000 series has become the recognized quality standard in 
over 50 nations; it is acceptable in lieu of MIL-Q-9858A by DOD; and 
many countries are requiring registered suppliers. Some U.S. shipyards 
are registered. MARAD will facilitate ISO 9000 registration for the 
marine industry by identifying registrars and through seminars and 
workshops on the program.<P>

        Seminars, symposia and workshops will be developed and 
conducted on a variety of topics such as standards, regulations and 
environmental concerns. Materials and programs will be developed for 
skilled labor training in new technologies. They will be based on 
industry desires and inputs and conducted with participation of 
industry plus appropriate government agencies and departments.<P>

        MARAD will be working closely with standards developing 
bodies and the USCG to facilitate adoption of voluntary consensus 
standards, both international and domestic, in lieu of regulations.<P>

        Support will be provided to the U.S. Technical Advisory Group 
(TAG) to the International Standards Organization's Committee on Ships 
and Marine Technology(ISO/TC-8). This is the official representative 
group to ISO and chartered by American National Standards Institute
(ANSI) who is the U.S. member body to both ISO and International 
electrotechnical Commision(IEC). MARAD will take the lead, with the 
assistance of other departments and agencies to provide administrative 
support to the tag to insure our continued active participation and 
the dissemination of the information which is key to promoting U.S. 
interests in the development of international standards. The U.S. 
has assumed an increased leadership role in ISO and holds several
key leadership positions, including representing ISO in the 
International Association of Ports and Harbors.<P>

        MARAD is updating its "standard specifications" with today's
requirements. The last issue dated 1979 was aimed at ships built under
the construction differential subsidy(CDS) program. <I><B>The new version 
is a guideline metric specification for merchant ship construction 
to help U.S. shipyards in the export business</B></I>. This guideline concept 
references international, foreign and domestic commercial standards. 
These new guidelines will not prevent owner modification or tailoring 
for his particular needs; however, they will be compatible with 
current technology and satisfy current regulations. This guide, 
together with standard pro forma contracts being developed by MARAD 
based on industry inputs, should be valuable to both U.S. shipyards 
and potential foreign owners (buyers).<P>

        There is probably no more critical area to the marine industry
than environmentally responsible standards and regulations. We will be 
working with the USCG and the TAG to ISO/TC-8 in this critical area and 
will be an information source for marine environmental protection 
information.<P>

<HR>
<b>
For Information and assistance, contact the director,
National Maritime Resource and Education Center:<P>
<pre>        
        Mr. Joseph Byrne, Director 
        Office of Shipyard Revitalization

        U.S. Department of Transportation
        Maritime Administration
        400 Seventh Street, S.W.
        Washington, DC 20590
        Tel: (202) 366-7197
        Fax: (202) 366-7197
</pre>
</b>
<p>
<HR>
