<TITLE>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</TITLE>

<!pn=pam2.htm/page posted on 10/29/96->
<!page called by hpms3.htm->
</HEAD> 

<!-- Body Tag --><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFBA" TEXT="#000000">             <H1 ALIGN=CENTER>MARITIME FACTS </H1>                                                                                       <P>The U.S.-flag merchant fleet is one ofthe safest in the world.  American standards of crew training andcertification are the highest in the world.</P><!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR><P ALIGN=CENTER><I>The prime innovators in this drmatic change             in the efficiency and productivity inocean transportation have been our Americancarriers.  Specialized ships ... containerization... double stack rail cars... specialized containers... electronicequipment identification... all areAmerican innovations.</I></P>  <P ALIGN=CENTER><B>Maritime Administrator A.J. Herberger</B>           (VADM, USN, ret.)</P><!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>                        <H3 ALIGN=CENTER>LINER VESSELS</H3><P>Liner vessels sail between specified ports ona regular basis, carrying high value cargoes,often in containers.</P><!-- List Tag --><UL><LI>Of approximately 300 ships in the  privately owned U.S.-flag merchant fleet,  about 80 are liner vessels operating in  international trade.<BR><LI>The U.S.-flag commercial fleet is a  worldwide leader in innovative  technologies in ocean shipping.   Innovations include double-stack trains,  seamless cargo tracking and identification  technologies.<BR><LI>The U.S.-flag liner fleet includes world-  class vessels that meet the higher U.S.  mandates for safety and environmental  protection.</UL></UL><!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>               <H3 ALIGN=CENTER>HIGH AMERICAN                 STANDARDS</H3> <P>The U.S.-flag commercial fleet is one of  the safest in the world, meeting U.S. Coast  Guard standards for vessel structure and  maintenance, and operational condition.   U.S. standards exceed international  requirements.</P><P>American standards for crew training and  certification, also enforced by the Coast  Guard, are the highest in the world.</P><!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>               <H3 ALIGN=CENTER>AMERICAN JOBS FOR THE                 AMERICAN ECONOMY</H3><P>The oceangoing U.S.-flag fleet employs about  18,000 U.S. citizen civilian merchant  mariners and nearly 70,000 more persons in  shoreside indirect and induced jobs.</P><P>These 87,000 workers contribute an estimated  $4.7 billion to the U.S. economy in household  earnings.  These American workers and their  employers pay about $760 million in Federal  personal and business taxes.</P><P>U.S.-flag oceangoing shipping companies  contributed over $5 billion to the Nation's  freight bill in 1993.</P><P>The American economy accounts for about 15  percent of all international waterborne trade --  far ahead of other major maritime nations --  yet U.S.-flag ships only carry 4 percent of our  total international waterborne trade.   However, U.S.-flag ships carry over 16  percent of our high-value international liner  trade.</P><P>America remains one of the most open  maritime countries in the world, allowing  foreign vessels, companies, and crews into the  U.S. to operate freely in U.S. waters and ports  when carrying international trade cargo.</P><!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>            <H3 ALIGN=CENTER> EMERGENCY SERVICE</H3><P>During times of national emergency, there is noreliable alternative to a U.S.-flag fleet ofcommercial ships and trained American crews.</P><!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR><P>For additional information call          1-800-99MARADor visit the Maritime Administration'sWeb Page at <I>http://www.marad.dot.gov</I></P><!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR><P>September 1996 </P>
