<body>
<a><center><h4>AN OVERVIEW OF U.S. PUBLIC PORT INDUSTRY</h4></center></a>
<p>
<b>ECONOMIC IMPACT OF U.S. PORTS</b>
<p>
The ports of the United States play an important role in meeting the 
demands for water transportation service, which is driven by the producers 
and consumers of waterborne cargo--both in foreign and domestic commerce.  
This demand for waterborne cargo initiates a chain of economic activity 
which contributes to the overall national economy.  U.S. ports are a vital 
link in this economic chain.
<p>
This section analyzes the economic impact of the port industry, public 
port capital expenditures, and port users.  The measurement of the direct, 
indirect, and induced effects are shown in terms of employment, personal 
income, business sales, Gross Domestic Product (GDP), and taxes.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Port Industry Impacts</b>
<p>
The port industry is defined as any economic activity that is directly 
needed for the movement of waterborne cargo.  The main categories include 
vessel services for pilotage and dockage; trade services for freight 
forwarders, customs brokers, and insurance; cargo handling and storage 
activities; and inland transportation.
<p>
The port industry's impact on the national economy is summarized in Table 1.  
The economic impacts were based on the total domestic and foreign waterborne 
tonnage handled in 1994 by the Nation's deep and shallow draft ports.  The 
benefits shown include direct, indirect, and induced impacts.  The latter 
two impacts result from themultiplier effect of the direct spending 
associated with port activity.  The port industry is responsible for 
generating over 1.6 million jobs.  This equates to the creation of one 
job, nationally, for the movement of every 1,858 metric tons of 
waterborne commerce.  The handling of the Nation's waterborne
commerce was directly and indirectly responsible for $151.3 billion of 
sales revenues. 
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Capital Expenditure Impacts</b>
<p>
Table 2 highlights the national economic impact derived from the public 
port industry's capital expenditure program for the construction and 
modernization of the terminal facilities and
channel dredging.  For 1994, the public port industry's capital 
expenditures total $686.6 million.  The impacts reflect the short, 
but not the long-term benefits.  For example, it includes the 
benefits derived from the construction of a new terminal facility, 
but not the economic gains that result from future terminal use.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Port User Impacts</b>
<p>
Port users are businesses that make significant use of the port 
system for shipping or receiving goods.  The economic impacts shown 
in Table 3 illustrate the importance of waterborne trade
to the national economy.  As an example, about 95 percent by weight  
of all U.S. foreign trade moves through U.S. ports.  The total number 
of jobs generated by port users is 14.3 million, with business 
revenues in excess of $1.4 trillion.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Total Economic Impacts</b>
<p>
Table 4 presents a summary of the overall national economic impact 
of the port industry, capital expenditures, and port users.  
This includes 15.9 million jobs, income of $515.1 billion, and sales in 
excess of $1.6 trillion.  This impact also contributes $783.3 billion 
to the Nation's GDP and $154.3 billion in federal taxes and $55.8 billion 
in state and local taxes.

<p>
Table 5 shows how the total impacts in Table 4 are distributed 
within the economy. Specifically, it depicts which industrial sectors 
of the economy benefit from the U.S. ports total economic activity 
in terms of employment, income, sales, and contribution to Gross Domestic 
Product.  The manufacturing sector continues to be the largest beneficiary 
of port activity across all four impact measures.  The services and retail 
trade sectors are beneficiaries of port activity in terms of employment, 
while services and transportation are among the principal sectors for income.  
The finance and transportation sectors are leaders in sales and
contributors to GNP.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
