<body>
<a><h4>WATERBORNE COMMERCE AT U.S. PORTS<br> 
(Foreign and Domestic Trades)</h4></a>
<p>
For 1994, the waterborne commerce of the United States reached a record 
level of 2 billion metric tons.  The 1994 tonnage increase represents a 
4.1 percent gain over 1993.  Foreign
trade shows growth for the fourth consecutive year with volume exceeding 
the one billion mark with domestic tonnages rising over the 
four-year period despite some slippage in 1993.
Table 7 provides a 40-year summary of the U.S. waterborne trade 
from 1955 to 1994.  This table includes a breakdown of the foreign 
and domestic trade figures by trade segment.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>Domestic Waterborne Trade</b>
<p>
The 1994 domestic waterborne tonnage increased by 2.9 percent to 
996.8 million metric tons. 
Within the domestic trade segment, traffic figures for all elements 
rose over the previous
year's level.  Coastwise trade shows an increase of 1.9 percent to 
251.2 million metric tons
with lakewise traffic increasing by 4.4 percent to 104.1 million metric 
tons.  Internal or inland waterway tonnage, which accounts for 56.2 
percent of the domestic trade, grew by 1.8 percent 
to 560.9 million metric tons rebounding from the flood induced 
decline in 1993.  Table 6 compares the 1995 through 1993 tonnages for 
selected inland waterways.  As shown, the
Mississippi and Ohio rivers and the Gulf Intracoastal Waterway 
continue to carry the majority
of the inland waterway traffic.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>Foreign Waterborne Trade</b>
<p>
The Bureau of Census trade data in Table 8 shows that U.S. foreign
trade continued to grow steadily since the decline in 1991.  For 1995, 
traffic totaled 980.1 million metric tons valued at $619.7 billion.  
This represents a 4.5 percent increase in tonnage and a 9.5 percent gain in
dollar value over the previous year.  For the year, imports declined 
by 4.6 percent to 570.6 million metric tons with a value of $391.5 
billion (up 4 percent), while exports rose by 20.5 percent to 409.5 
million metric tons valued at $228.2 billion.
Table 9 provides a comparison of foreign trade by coastal region for 
1995 and 1994.  On a tonnage basis, all coastal regions showed increases 
over 1994 with the North Pacific region
showing the largest gain--18.2 percent.  All regions except the Great 
Lakes had increases in trade value.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>U.S. Waterborne Trade - Commodities and Trading Partners</b>
<p>
Figure 1 depicts the principal 1994 U.S. waterborne trade commodities on 
a tonnage basis. For total trade, petroleum products remains as the 
dominant commodity with over 43 percent
of the market.  Other key commodities include crude materials, such 
as nonmetallic minerals, ore, and forest products (16.7 percent), 
coal (14.2 percent), andfood and farm products (11.6 percent).  Within 
the foreign and domestic trade segments, petroleum remains the leading
commodity with 48.5 percent and 38.4 percent of the respective trades.  
Other significant foreign trade commodities are food and farm 
products (14.6 percent) and crude materials (13.3 percent).  On the 
domestic side, coal and crude materials each account for approximately
20 percent of the domestic sector.  Table 10 provides additional
 commodity information for
total trade and each of the foreign and domestic trade components. 
<p>
Table 11 highlights the leading trading partners by tonnage and value and 
by direction of trade flow for 1995.  The U.S. foreign trade is highly 
concentrated both in terms of tonnage and value.  The top 5 trading 
partners account for approximately 39 percent of the tonnage and 45
percent of the value.  For the top 25 trading partners, the percentages 
grow to 80 percent in both cases.  Venezuela is the leading trading 
partner by tonnage. Japan is the clear leader in all trade areas based 
on value.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Foreign Trade Forecast</b>
<p>
The following table (Table 12) provides a 5-year forecast of U.S. foreign
 trade for the period 1996 to
2000.  The forecast projects a steady growth rate for this trade 
annualized at 3.8 percent.  A
similar growth pattern is expected for both imports and exports.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>U.S. Port Tonnages</b>
<p>
The movement of waterborne commerce through the U.S. port system 
remains highly concentrated.  Table 13 shows that 50 coastal and 
inland ports handled 89.2 percent of the
total waterborne trade in 1994.  The top five ports total 28.3 percent 
and the top 20 account for 63 percent.  The percentage distribution 
(based on tonnage) among the top 50 ports remains consistent with the 
results shown in previous reports.  In 1994, there were 3 ports that
handled over 100 million metric tons.  Even with this high degree of 
concentration, there were 142 ports that handle over 1 million 
metric tons of cargo.  This indicates the broad base on
which the U.S. port system is built.
<p>

Table 14 shows the tonnage distribution for the top 150 ports for 1994.  
The port distribution is categorized for each of the three principal 
trade segments--total, domestic, and foreign. The concentration of 
activity among the leading U.S. containerports is reflected in Table 15. 
The top 25 ports handled 97.3 percent of U.S. foreign container cargo 
based on twenty-foot equivalent units (TEU) in 1995.  The first 10 ports 
accounted for 77 percent of the total with 4 west coast ports among 
the top 5.  For 1995, container traffic increased by 7.8 percent--nearly
one million TEUs--over 1994.  The top three ports captured approximately 
42 percent of the 1995 traffic increase.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h5><a href="arpt2s1m.htm">Return to Public Port Industry Index</a></h5>
<p>
</body>
</html>

