<html>
<head>
<title>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</title>
<!pn=arpt2s1c.htm/page edited&implemented on 11/19/96->
<!page called by arpt2s1m.htm->
</head>
<body>

<h4>MARINE TERMINAL FACILITIES</h4>
<p>
<b>Deep-Draft Seaport and Great Lakes Port Facilities</b>
<p>
Table 16 provides a comparison of the major U.S. seaport facilities 
by coastal region.  As shown, there are a total of 1,940 terminals 
comprising 3,179 berths.  These figures include
both privately and publicly owned facilities.  Overall, privately 
owned facilities account for 75 percent of the deep-draft terminals.  
The distribution of terminals among the four seacoasts is
fairly even with the east coast having the largest share at 31.1 percent. 
The gulf coast follows
at 25.4 percent with the west coast at 24.8 percent, and the Great 
Lakes at 18.7 percent.  The
coastal distribution pattern of berths is similar to that for the 
terminals with the east coast
region accounting for 34.6 percent of the total.

<p>
Table 17 examines distribution of deep-draft facilities at the 
berth level by type of berth and
coastal region.  Berth types are grouped into five general classes. 
Within each class, there are
a number of related single-purpose and multipurpose berth types.
<p>
The general cargo class represents the largest berth segment with 
37.7 percent of the total. 
Within this class, the predominate single use type is general cargo 
with 48.2 percent followed
by container with 12.2 percent.
<p>
The bulk segments are approximately equal in size with dry bulk 
accounting for 22.3 percent
and liquid bulk for 19.8 percent.  The distribution of dry bulk berth 
types shows a fairly wide
distribution pattern among the commodity specific berth types.  On 
the other hand, liquid bulk
is highly concentrated with 83.1 percent of the berths associated 
with the handling of various
types of petroleum products.
<p>
Figure 2 depicts the berth distribution by coastal region for 
general cargo, dry bulk, and liquid
bulk facilities.  For general cargo berths, there is a fairly even
regions with the gulf region leading at 22.6 percent followed by 
the North Atlantic region at
22.1 percent.  In the dry bulk category, the Great Lakes region 
accounts for 38.9 percent of
this berth segment with the gulf coast second at 23.8 percent. 
Liquid bulk facilities are
equally concentrated in the North Atlantic and gulf regions with
29.3 percent, each.  Over half
of the passenger berths nationwide are located in the South and 
North Atlantic regions.
<p>
Figure 3 depicts the mix of berth classes within each coastal region.  
For all regions except the
Great Lakes, the general cargo class is the predominate type.  Dry 
bulk facilities account for
the majority of the Great Lakes facilities.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Inland River and Intracoastal Waterways Port Facilities</b>
<p>
The U.S. inland waterway ports and terminals possess unique 
characteristics that distinguish
them from the coastal seaports.  Aside from shallow water depths of 
14 feet or less, the inland
system is less concentrated geographically and provides almost 
limitless access points to the waterways.  Overall, there are more 
inland facilities locatedoutside traditional port boundaries
than within.  Terminal siting on the waterways is less constrained 
than coastal ports providing greater flexibility to the users 
in determining the location of plants requiring water access.
<p>
Table 18 provides a profile of the terminal facilities located on 
the U.S. inland waterway system, which consists of over 25,000 miles 
of navigable inland rivers and intracoastal waterways.  The information 
is categorized by state and terminal type.  As shown, there are
approximately 1,800 river terminals located in 21 states.  Dry bulk 
facilities account for the majority with 57.9 percent of the terminals.  
Within dry bulk, grain and coal terminals are the
leading types at 26 percent and 22.9 percent, respectively.  Liquid 
bulk terminals are the second largest category comprising 27.1 percent.  
Within this category, petroleum facilities account for 57.1 percent.  
Multipurpose and general cargo terminals account for the balance of
the terminals with 10.9 percent and 4.1 percent, respectively. 
Private ownership of inland waterway facilities is more pronounced 
than the ownership of coastal facilities with 89 percent 
compared to 75 percent.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h5><a href="arpt2s1m.htm">Return to Public Port Industry Index</a></h5>
