<html>
<head>
<title>U.S. MARITIME ADMINISTRATION</title>
<!pn=arpt2s1d.htm/page edited/implemented on 11/19/96blh->
<!page called by arpt2s1m.htm->
</head>
<body>

<h4>CAPITAL CONSTRUCTION, DEVELOPMENT AND FUNDING <br>BY U.S. PUBLIC PORTS</h4>
<p>
<b>Capital Expenditures</b>
<p>
For the period from 1946 through 1994, the U.S. public port industry 
invested $14.1 billion in capital improvements to its port facilities.  
This investment covers expenditures for the construction of new 
facilities and the modernization and rehabilitation of existing ones.   
Table 19 summarizes the historical expenditures by coastal region.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Capital Expenditures for 1994</b>
<p>
Table 20 compares the annual expenditures for 1991 through 1994 
broken down by coastal region.  For 1994, total capital expenditures 
amounted to $929.6 million--up 42.2 percent over 1993.  The sharp 
increase resulted from the purchase of a large tract of land for current
and future port development by a South Pacific region port.  The 
South Pacific region led the
nation with $533.9 million (57.4 percent) in capital expenditures 
followed by the South Atlantic region at $124.8 million (13.4 percent) 
and the gulf region at $109.2 million (11.8 percent).
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Capital Expenditures by Facility Type</b>
<p>
Table 21 analyzes the public port industry's capital expenditures 
by type of facility.  The industry's emphasis continues to focus on 
specialized and conventional general cargo facilities.
As shown in the table, specialized general cargo facilities account 
for 34.8 percent of the 1994 expenditures.  The South Pacific region 
totals 63.5 percent of these expenditures with the
South Atlantic region following with 24.5 percent.
<p>
General cargo investment represents 22.8 percent of the total 
expenditures with the gulf region accounting for 34.4 percent followed 
closely by the South Pacific region with 33.4 percent. 
South Pacific region is the focus of the dry bulk expenditures at 
75.6 percent with the South Atlantic region accounting for 54.3 percent 
of the liquid bulk expenditures.  The passenger segment captured 
4.7 percent with the South Atlantic and gulf regions totaling 60.5 percent
and 36 percent of these investments, respectively.  "Other" 
expenditures amount to 7.3
percent with activity centered in Gulf and North Pacific regions.
<p>
Port infrastructure improvements represent 21.1 percent of the 1994 
expenditures.  The off-terminal segment totaled 71.6 percent of the 
infrastructure investments.  The North Atlantic region accounts for 
47.1 percent of the off-terminal expenditures followed by the South Pacific
at 24.9 percent.  The west coast regions' investments account for 
88.1 percent of total on-terminal improvements followed by the gulf 
(8.1 percent) and the east coast (3.8 percent).
Dredging expenditures amounted to 3.4 percent of the total with the 
majority occurring on the east and gulf coasts--South Atlantic 
(32.3 percent), gulf (27.9percent), and North Atlantic (25
percent) regions.
<p>
Expenditures for new construction represent 75 percent of the 1994 
capital expenditures. Specialized general cargo facilities account for 
40.3 percent of the new construction expenditures with conventional 
general cargo at 26.6 percent and infrastructure at 12.3 percent.  
For modernization and rehabilitation (M&R) expenditures, infrastructure 
is the leading category with 43.6 percent.  Other significant M&R 
categories include specialized general cargo (19.9 percent) and 
conventional general cargo (12.1 percent).
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Projected Capital Expenditures for 1995 to 1999</b>
<p>
The public port industry's projected capital expenditures for 1995
through 1999 are summarized in Table 22 by coastal region.  These 
expenditures are forecasted to total $4.6
billion during this 5-year period.
<p>
The South Pacific region remains the center of investment activity 
with proposed expenditures of $2.2 billion (47.2 percent).  Two other 
regions have significant projected investments--the South Atlantic 
at $910.9 million (19.4 percent) and the gulf at $788.1 million 
(16.8 percent).
From a coastwise perspective, the west coast is projecting to invest
over $2.4 billion (51.9 percent) with east coast expenditures 
at $1.2 billion (26.7 percent) and 
the gulf at $788.1 million (16.8 percent).
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>Capital Expenditures by Facility Type</b>
<p>
Table 23 shows the proposed expenditures by type of facility. 
Specialized general cargo
continues as the leading sector with $1.8 billion (38.4 percent) of 
the expenditures.  The South Pacific and South Atlantic regions account 
for 83.1 percent of the proposed expenditures in
this category of facility expenditure--South Pacific with 59.1 percent 
and the South Atlantic with 24 percent.  The North Pacific region is 
projecting expenditures of $139 million (7.7 percent).
<p>
General cargo expenditures account for $775.4 million (16.5percent) of 
the proposed investments with the focus of this activity in the South 
Pacific (33 percent) and gulf (32.5 percent) regions.  Dry and liquid bulk 
facility expenditures represented 6.3 percent of
future investments with dry bulk representing over 97 percent of 
the bulk category.  The gulf
and South Pacific regions account for 88.1 percent of the total 
projected bulk expenditures--gulf with 51 percent and the South 
Pacific with 37.1 percent.  Passenger facility investment is
3.2 percent of the total with the majority of the investment in the 
South Atlantic (60.6 percent) and gulf (32.1 percent) regions.
<p>
Projections for infrastructure investments approach $1 billion 
(20.8 percent) with on-terminal
expenditures accounting for 58 percent of the total.  The South 
Pacific region is projected to
capture 55.7 percent of these investments with the North Atlantic 
region at 15.7 percent and
the South Atlantic at 11.8 percent.  Dredging expenditures 
represent 8.4 percent of the total
with projected expenditures concentrated in the South Pacific 
(49.6 percent) and South Atlantic (23.7 percent) regions.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Funding Sources</b>
<p>
This section describes the financing methods used to fund the 1994 
expenditures and the
proposed methods for the projected 1995-1999 expenditures.  Table 24 
provides a basis for comparing the changes in the primary financing 
methods used by the public port industry. 
The table (Table 24) highlights the shift in financing methods from 
general obligation (GO) bonds to port
revenues that occurred between the 1973-1978 and 1979-1989.  The 
funding pattern in the 1990s remains consistent with this shift.  
During the 1990s, the relative use of "all other" 
methods has increased steadily.  This suggests that ports are 
seeking alternatives or supplements to port revenues through increased 
usage of loans, grants, special trust funds, and
appropriations.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>Funding Sources for 1994</b>
<p>
A comparative summary of financing methods used during the 
1994-1990 period is shown in Table 25.  The combination of port revenues 
and revenue bonds continues to account for half
of all forms of funding.  For the first time in recent years, the 
use of "other" and loan financing methods were among the top three 
sources of funding. There has been a steady
decline in the combined use of port revenues and revenue bonds from 
a high of 88.3 percent in 1988 (not shown in table) to a low of 
50.2 percent in 1994.
<p>
For 1994, port revenues was the principal funding source accounting 
for $309.7 million or 35.3 percent of the public port financing.  
This represents a significant decrease from 1993 when port revenues 
financed 50.6 percent of the expenditures, although the dollar volume
increased by about 4 percent.  "Other" and loans showed sharp 
percentage and dollar volume increases in 1994.  "Other" grew from 10.2 
percent to 20.7 percent, while loans increased
from 0.8 percent to 16 percent.  Revenue bonds declined from 22.8 
percent in 1993 to 14.9 percent in 1994.  The relative usage of GO bonds 
and grants remains largely unchanged from their 1993 levels. 
<p>
Table 26 examines the distribution of 1994 funding sources within 
the coastal regions.  Port revenues are the primary financing method 
in three coastal regions with GO bonds leading in
two regions and revenue bonds, loans, and grants leading in one of 
the remaining regions. 
<p>
The South Pacific region was the principal user of port revenues
with $197.5 million (63.8 percent) followed by the South Atlantic 
region at $40.7million (13.2 percent).  The
South Atlantic region was the primary user of GO bonds with $60.9 
million (67.7 percent).  
<p>
Revenue bonds were the most evenly distributed funding source.  The 
South Pacific region accounted for 58 million (44.4 percent) with 
the non-contiguous at $33.6 million (25.7 percent) and the gulf 
at $28.9 million (22.2 percent).
<p>
The South Pacific region accounted for most of the  loan funding 
with $125.8 million (89.6 percent).  The gulf region was the principal 
grant beneficiary with $10.3 million (42.8 percent).  
The South Pacific region was the primary user of "other"sources with $147.5
million (81.5 percent).
<p>
<hr>
<p>

<b>Projected Funding Sources for 1995 to 1999</b>
<p>
Table 27 shows the anticipated funding sources for the U.S. public 
port industry's projected 1995-1999 capital expenditure program.  
Revenue bonds and port revenues are the chief 
sources accounting for 71.6 percent of the overall funding. 
Revenue bonds are the primary 
source of funding with 49.1 percent followed by port revenues with 
22.5 percent.  Revenue
bonds are projected to be the leading funding source in three 
coastal regions with port revenues in two regions and GO bonds, loans, 
and grants each leading in one of the remaining regions.
<p>
The South Pacific region is projected to be the primary user of 
port revenues with $308.4
million (30.5%) followed closely by the gulf region with $279.6 
million (27.7 percent).  The South Pacific is also a principal user 
of revenue bonds with $1,624.3 million (73.8 percent). 
The South Atlantic region is the leading user of GO bonds with 
$257.3 million (76.6 percent).
<p>
The South Atlantic region accounts for $48.4 million (48.1 percent) 
of the loan category.  The
gulf region is the projected leader in the use of grants with $82.8 
million (36.8 percent) with
the South Atlantic at $75.5 million (33.6 percent).  The "other" 
funding category is concentrated in the South Pacific with $260.3 million 
(42.5 percent) and the gulf with $244.5 million (36.7 percent).
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h5><a href="arpt2s1m.htm">Return to Public Port Industry</a></h5>
<p>
</body>
