<body>
             
<a><center><b>**************************************</b></center></a><p>
<a><center><b>ISO 14000 - List of Related Activities</b></center></a><p>
<a><center><b>**************************************</b></center></a>
<a><center><b>MARAD  10/28/96</b></center></a>
<p>
<hr>
<p>  
<a><center><b>Department of Energy</b></center></a> 
<a><center><b>May Mandate ISO 14001 for its Contractors</b></center></a> 
<p>
A new law signed by President Clinton in March 1996 could set the
way for the DOE to require ISO 14001 certification of its
suppliers and contractors.   The law could also pave the way for
similar edicts from Department of Defense, The Environmental
Protection Agency and other government agencies.  The National
Technology Transfer and Advancement Act of 1995 could require
federal agencies and their respective contractors to implement
and seek third party certification to ISO 14001 in lieu of
agency-specific or departmental standards.
<p>
The Department of Energy has not determined exactly how it will
address the law, but just resently it postponded plans to release
a high-level policy statement signed by Secrearty Hazel O'Leary
that would advise contractors to implement an energy management
system (EMS) such as  ISO 14001 as part of the procurement
process.    DOE is now considering using stronger wording to the
document.
<p>
While the act does not specifically mention ISO 14001, the ISO
9000 quality system standard, or any other voluntary standard, it
does make it clear that federal agenies will use consensus
standards during procurement or whenever possible.   The National
Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) within the
Departmrnt of Commerce will spearhead implementing the law amonge
federal agencies. 
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<a><center><b>The Environmental Protection Agency</b></center></a> 
<p>
The US Environmental Protection Agency has announced plans to
implement a new environmental reporting system called Key
Identifier.  The project will be modeled after the income tax
filing procedure.   The reporting facility would fill out a one
or two page form requiring basic information.  Each individual
compliance report would then become an attachment much like a tax
schedule.
<p>
Each facility included in the database would be assigned an ID
number, contact name, facility name and address, and industry
code.  Eventually the EPA wants to implement a "one-stop" process
by puttingf all of the information about each company on-line. 
This system would give the Environmental Health Safety managers
the ability to access each other's information.  The goal of the
Key Identifiers is to make the information more useful.  The EPA
is calling for comments dealing with how the information should
be gathered in the Key Identifiers project. 
<p>
<hr>
<p>
 If you need additional information or you have additional     
    information, please contact Michael Pursley any of the       
    following ways:
