<HTML><BODY BGCOLOR="#000063" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FFFF00"
VLINK="#E60000" ALINK="#FF4FFF"><P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
<title>Maritime Security Act of 1995</title>
<CENTER><h1>Maritime Security Act of 1995</h></CENTER>
<font size=4><p>

The U.S. House of Representatives on December 6, 1995, approved
the
Administration's proposed Maritime Security Act of 1995, 
H.R. 1350.   Following are statements released by Secretary of
Transportation Federico Pena and Maritime Administrator Albert J.
Herberger.</p>

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR>
<center>
<h2>STATEMENT BY SECRETARY OF TRANSPORTATION FEDERICO PENA</h2>
<h2>                  MARITIME SECURITY ACT OF 1995</h2></center>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->

<p>     I welcome the bipartisan action in the U.S. House of 

Representatives today to help ensure America's future as a 

maritime nation.</p>

<P>     The Maritime Security Act of 1995 will phase out an
existing
subsidy program, deregulate the foreign commercial activities of
U.S.-flag merchant ships and encourage the use of modern vessels
by U.S.-flag ship operators.  </P>
<P>
     The program makes good sense for America strategically and
economically.  It ensures that the world's greatest trading
nation will continue to participate in the ocean transportation
of its international commerce.  It also ensures that U.S.-flag
merchant ships and skilled American civilian seafarers will
continue to be available to support our armed forces, whether in
times of conflict or in support of humanitarian and peacekeeping
efforts.</>

<p>     On behalf of the President, I thank Members of the House
from both sides of the aisle for their cooperation and for their
support for this measure, which truly is in the best interests of
our nation.   In the very near future, we look forward to similar
action in the Senate, and stand ready to work with members of
both parties toward that end.</P>

<center><P>                            # # # # #</P></center>

 <!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR>
<HR>
<center>
<h2>STATEMENT BY MARITIME ADMINISTRATOR ALBERT J. HERBERGER
</h2>
<h2>                  MARITIME SECURITY ACT OF 1995</h2></center>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->


<p>     I am pleased to join Secretary Pena in applauding the 

bipartisan vote in the U.S. House of Representatives approving 

the Maritime Security Act of 1995.  I hope the Senate will act 

shortly to send the legislation to the President for his 

signature.</p>

<p>     The United States depends upon oceangoing ships to carry
the
vast majority of our exports and imports.  The House has wisely
acted to maintain a U.S.-flag presence in the transportation of
those cargoes.  U.S.-flag carriers have been the innovators in
developing modern intermodal transportation systems, and our
nation will benefit from their continued leadership.  In
addition, U.S.-flag ships crewed by American merchant mariners
continue to be a cost-effective source of sealift for our armed
forces.</P>

<p>     We in the Maritime Administration and the U.S. Department
of
Transportation look forward to the opportunity to implement this
significant new approach to maritime policy.</P>

<CENTER><P>                           # # # # # </p></center>
<p>
