<body>
<A><center><h4>U.S. PUBLIC PORT ANNUAL REPORT<BR> 
RELATED DEVELOPMENTS</h4></center></a>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
NORTH AMERICAN INTERMODAL TRANSPORTATION SYSTEM
<p>
Trade within the Americas is the fastest growing of all U.S.commerce.  The water mode
complements rail and truck, as well as providing an alternative to 
handle the increased traffic. 
Water transportation is low-cost, safe, and energy efficient and is 
ideally suited to carry
products among Canada, Mexico, and the United States.  Maritime 
ports are also alternatives to relieve the congested land border crossings.  
<p>
The Maritime Administration's (MARAD) research program, the 
Maritime System of the Americas (MSA), provides a comprehensive analysis 
of potential market and technological
opportunities for water transportation in the United States, 
Canada, and Mexico trades.  This
program focuses on the commercial waterbridge linking Canada, the 
mid-United States, and Mexico via the St. Lawrence Seaway, the Great Lakes, 
the Mississippi River System, the
Tennessee-Tombigbee Waterway, the Gulf Intracoastal Waterway and 
the Gulf of Mexico. 
Through the Caribbean Sea, this waterbridge extends to eastern 
Central America, the northern
rim of South America, and the Caribbean Islands.
<p>
Phase I of the MSA study addresses the potential for small river/ocean vessels on the
waterways and rivers linking the central portions of the U.S. andCanada to Mexico.  The study
determines that such vessels are viable in niche markets carrying general cargoes, containers,
and some bulk commodities between the South Central United States and Eastern Mexico.
<p>
Phases II and III of MSA research examines the potential for conventional and short sea
shipping, as well as intermodal operations in the MSA region.  The analyses suggest that the
intermodal movement of domestic trailers using a roll-on/roll-off (ro/ro) ferry type vessel has
cost and logistical advantages over other transport options in serving the eastern/central regions
of both the U.S. and Mexico.
<p>
Phase IV of MSA consists of two components.  First, outreach meetings to discuss research
groups, shippers, and other maritime interests.  The meetings were held in Houston, TX;
Tampa, FL; Memphis, TN; Baton Rouge, LA; Jackson, MS; Birmingham, AL; and Merida,
Mexico.  
<p>
The second component includes research and analysis of cargo movements with
origins/destinations in the northern portion of the MSA waterway system.  This includes
investigation and use of existing or new vessels capable of navigating the Great Lakes, St.
Lawrence River, Gulf of St. Lawrence, Upper Mississippi River and its tributaries, and the
New York State Barge Canal.  Release of this study is expected in Fall 1996.
<p>
The Maritime System of the Americas is truly a North American intermodal transportation
system, linking cargo origins and destinations to the waterways by rail and/or truck.  It is a
north/south transportation corridor that provides shippers with an opportunity to move their
international cargoes via water as a complement to current service.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

GREAT LAKES  - NEW SHIPPING VENTURES
<p>     
<b>Expanded Use of River Barges in Lake Michigan</b>
<p>
The expanded use of river barges with U.S. Coast Guard (USCG) Great Lakes Limited
Load-Line designation created new trades in commodities, such as decorative landscape stone,
cotton seed, lumber, scrap iron, road salt and grain.  Since the success of the Milwaukee barge
movement, other ports on Lake Michigan have requested similar USCG barge approval. 
During the last three years, the use of river barges between Chicago and Milwaukee, WI,
generated over 400,000 tons of traffic.  The USCG recently (Spring 96) approved barge
operations between Chicago and Benton Harbor/St. Joseph, MI. Applications for the Michigan
Ports of Muskegon, Holland, and Grand Haven were approved in August 1996.  The barge
approvals have provided new opportunities for small shallow-draft port operators who can now
take advantage of the barge industry's low cost transportation and environmental benefits.  The
Secretary of Transportation has given Michigan ports his support in this effort with safety of
<p>

<b>Lakes Vessel to Barge Transfer Operation</b>
<p>
During the 1995-1996 Great Lakes shipping season, several shipments were made using
existing Lakes vessels in a new cargo transfer operation.  Lakes vessels with self-unloader
booms transferred dry bulk cargoes directly to river barges off-shore near the Port of Chicago. 
Both U.S. and Canadian self-unloaders participated in the new transfer operation. 
Commodities, such as grain, fertilizer and salt were moved from various Great Lakes ports and
loaded into barges at Chicago for shipment to destinations throughout the U.S. inland waterway
system.  The Calumet Safety Committee and the USCG Marine Safety Office in Chicago
cooperated in developing safe procedures for transferring cargo in the busy waterway.  This
new approach reduced transportation costs that in the past included unloading to shore and
reloading the barge from the shore-side facility.
<p>

<b>New U.S.-Flag Service in the Great Lakes</b>
<p>
During the 1995 Great Lakes shipping season, the U.S.-flag ITB (integrated tug barge) DIXIE
COMMANDER tank vessel made three trips into Toledo, OH, with 
liquid urea fertilizer from
Mexico.  Outbound voyages with liquid calcium chloride and other liquids from Ludington,
MI, and Canadian ports to the U.S. gulf coast provided a well balanced new trade for the
vessel.  This was the first incident of recent record for a U.S.-flag vessel combining an import
foreign trade movement with a U.S. domestic trade movement in the same voyage.  The Saint
Lawrence Seaway Authority/St. Lawrence Development Corporation gave the vessel reduced
incentive tolls since this was a new trade opportunity into the region.  Plans call for the ITB
DIXIE COMMANDER to return for the 1996 shipping season.  Dixie Carriers may introduce a
second ITB capable of handing dry bulk, container and general cargo for the 1996 season.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
CARGO THEFT
<p>
Cargo theft has become a serious problem in the port cities and hinterland areas throughout the
works cooperatively with government, has estimated that losses due to cargo theft in the United
States exceed $10 billion annually.  Cargo theft is being committed by highly organized and
sophisticated criminal groups with the ability to export stolen merchandise out of the U.S. to
countries where the demand for Western consumer goods is high.

The average value of a single cargo theft loss now stands at about $500,000.  The insurance
industry has begun to require more accountability for cargo security from firms shipping and
transporting cargo.  The insurance industry has forecast increases in premiums and difficulty in
obtaining insurance for those firms that do not reduce losses by deterring the opportunities for
criminal exploitation.

The absence of consistent cargo theft reporting and record keeping procedures has been an
obstacle over the years to marshaling effective strategies against this crime.  However, the
transportation, shipping, and insurance industries are beginning to work cooperatively with
Federal, state, and local government agencies to document the scope of the cargo theft problem
and implement strategies to reduce losses.  Efforts are focused on the full range of expected
outcomes, including prevention, deterrence, cargo recovery, criminal apprehension, and
successful prosecution.  As an example of this cooperation, the Federal Bureau of Investigation
and the NCSC cosponsored the Interstate Theft and Strategic Initiatives Cargo Theft
Conference in Miami (April 1996).  The Maritime Administration is working cooperatively
with industry and other Federal agencies to counter the problem of cargo theft occurring during
intermodal phases of transport. 
<p>
<hr>
<p>
NATIONAL DEFENSE - NATIONAL PORT READINESS NETWORK
<p>
The National Port Readiness Network was formed in 1984 and wascomposed of six Federal
agencies involved in port activities during a military deployment. The number of agencies in
the Network has grown over time and it is now composed of nine agencies.  In addition to the
Maritime Administration, the current members are HQ, Forces Command (FORSCOM), U.S.
Transportation Command (USTRANSCOM), U.S. Army Military Traffic 
Command (MTMC), U.S. Navy Military Sealift Command (MSC), U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers (USACE), U.S. Coast Guard (USCG),  U.S. Naval Control of Shipping
Organization (NCSORG), and U.S. Maritime Defense Zone (MDZ).
<p>
The chairmanship of the National Port Readiness Network Steering Group and the National
Port Readiness Network Working Group rotates on an annual basis among the member
agencies.  MARAD is the current chair of these groups.  As the Chair, MARAD has the lead in
the creation of new initiatives to ensure port readiness.  Improved communication between
Network members, ports and terminal operators is being addressed. Training needs are being
examined in light of the awareness of on-going personnel reassignments and changes.  
<p>
For the past several years, selected ports which the military plans to use during a deployment
have been issued planning orders.  These are non-binding letters of intent which provide the
ports with deployment information for planning purposes.  Planning orders are now issued for
only a one year period in another effort to encourage communication among ports, terminal
operators, and the military. The Network instituted a program of semi-annual visits to ports
with planning orders to improve the deployment process.  Efforts are being made to have ports
participate in FORSCOM's Key Asset Protection Program.
<p>
The Network is encouraging the exchange of deployment data between the military personnel
responsible for the logistics of a unit move and the unit itself. This information can be used to
identify and discuss lift requirements, port capabilities and commercial disruption impacts.  The
identification of industrial property near ports which could be used as cargo staging areas is
being examined as a means to alleviate potential problems associated with surge movements of
military cargo through commercial port facilities.  Other initiatives include increased emphasis
and support of local Port Readiness Committees, enhancements inport readiness exercises, and
the updating of various publications.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

SUPPORT OF DEFENSE INTERMODAL TRANSPORTATION
<p>
MARAD is required by law to act as the intermediary between the 
military on container issues in connection with deployment of U.S.Armed Forces, or other
national defense requirements.  Under 46 CFR 340, the Maritime Administrator is to identify
container and/or chassis suppliers that can furnish DOD with the required number of containers
and/or chassis needed for a contingency and to minimize the disruption of the commercial
sector.
<p>
The commercial transportation sector invests in new equipment and technology to enhance its
systems to become more competitive and reduce overall costs. These transportation advantages
can be put to use in the defense sector.  With recent changes in the national defense strategy
and the downsizing of the U.S. military establishment, an increased emphasis is placed on the
need for a more effective deployment of forces in times of national emergency using the
commercial intermodal transportation system.  The benefits that the military can derive from
containerization and intermodal transportation are the same as in the commercial sector: lower 
costs, decreased transit times and lower rates of damage.  The common thread is the use of the
intermodal freight container.  This package has the same standards worldwide, and it is
apparent that its use will continue and increase in the foreseeable future.
<p>
Various means are being used to explore ways for the military to take advantage of the
commercial intermodal system.  MARAD has increased its coordination with the commercial
and military sectors to explore ways that the existing system can be used for military purposes. 
Programs such the United States Transportation Command's Center for the Commercial
Deployment of Transportation Technology are reviewing existing and emerging technologies
that may be of benefit to military deployments.  MARAD's Voluntary Intermodal Sealift
Agreement has been established to prepare the commercial shipping industry for possible future
deployment contingencies.  The Cargo Handling Cooperative Program assists member
companies to explore ways to increase productivity and enhance competitiveness.
<p>
New directives within the Department of Defense reinforce the concepts of intermodalism and
containerization.  A new Joint Chiefs of Staff publication 
and Procedures for Use of Intermodal Containers in Joint Operations, states "Intermodal
transportation that is flexible and fast is used by the Department of Defense to prepare, deploy,
support, and sustain forces assigned or committed to  a theater of operations or objective area." 
Other directives within DOD require specific minimum containerization requirements for
specific military cargoes.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

PORT FACILITY CONVEYANCE PROGRAM
<p>
The National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 1994 (Public Law 103-160) authorizes
the Secretary of Transportation to convey needed surplus Federal real property to non-Federal
public entities without monetary compensation for use in the development or operation of a port
facility.  This authority was subsequently delegated to the Maritime Administration (MARAD).
<p>
The program requires MARAD to receive, evaluate, and approve applications after consultation
with the Departments of Labor and Commerce and recommend assignment of surplus property
to MARAD for final conveyance to an applicant.  Final assignment decisions are made by a
disposal agency--military service or General Services Administration.  All conveyances are in
perpetuity by a MARAD Quitclaim Deed which contains the terms, conditions, reservations
and restrictions of the conveyance.
<p>
MARAD is responsible for enforcing compliance with the provisions in the deed.  The program
is designed to create jobs, encourage economic development and assure adequate port capacity
to meet future trade and national defense needs.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
