<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA on Supreme Court Decision</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea100.htm">Who We Are</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea200.htm">Opportunities for Educators</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Advice for Parents</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Support for Kids</A></P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><A
HREF="http://dol.state.vt.us/gopher_root3/000000/supct/a-e/brigham_v_state.96-502"><IMG
SRC="exclamat.gif" WIDTH="31" HEIGHT="64"></A>  In a decision that has profound
implications for every community, student, and educator in Vermont,
<A
HREF="http://dol.state.vt.us/gopher_root3/000000/supct/a-e/brigham_v_state.96-502">the
Vermont Supreme Court has ruled</A> that the state's current system of funding
education is unconstitutional.</P>
<P><B><I>This message for Vermont-NEA local Association leaders was delivered
on February 11...</I></B></P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Vermont Supreme Court decision mandates BIG changes
</FONT></H2>
<P>February 5th was a red letter day for local property tax payers whose burden
has been unfair and for kids in towns without the wealth to equal what's
available in other communities for education. The Vermont Supreme Court ruled
last Wednesday that the current system for funding education in Vermont is
unconstitutional. The decision is momentous for two reasons: 
</P>
<UL>
<LI>It establishes a right to &quot;equal educational opportunity&quot; for
every child in Vermont.</LI>
<LI>It ends immediately the decades-long debate over property tax reform.</LI>
</UL>
<P>Vermont-NEA has fought long and hard for both equal educational opportunity
and property tax reform. Now we must catch our collective breath and help shape
the very dramatic changes to come.
</P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Equality AND Quality</FONT>
</H2>
<P>Equal educational opportunity must not be perverted to result in equal but
mediocre education. Rather, Vermonters who care about quality education must
work to ensure that the State of Vermont achieves equity in spending by
(finally!) generating adequate revenues to support the system.  It would be
wrong -- and educationally unsound -- to bring up spending in some districts
while undermining other districts. Instead of robbing Peter to pay Paul, the
legislature must understand that new revenues are necessary. A fair statewide
property tax, a tiered income tax, and other taxes all must be on the table for
consideration. 
</P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Local control and participation
</FONT></H2>
<P>Speaking of pitfalls: A major strength of Vermont school systems which we
must strive to preserve is local community control and participation. Each one
of us who has worked to pass a school budget or save a school program
understands that people care about a school that BELONGS to them. If decisions
about local education and how to spend school funds are made in Montpelier, the
special support that many schools enjoy may well evaporate. </P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Statewide Teachers' Contract?</FONT>
</H2>
<P>The world is different now. The Supreme Court says that it is the state's
responsibility to guarantee substantially equal educational spending among local
communities. A so-called statewide teachers' contract -- like the one we fought
against three years ago -- has been mentioned in the press, but now may be
irrelevant. 
</P>
<P>A new system mandated by the Supreme Court could give the state
responsibility for all education funding, not just for the funds for teachers'
salaries. The state may well decide how much schools can spend in total. 
</P>
<P>How might the state determine how much to allocate to school districts? The
simplest way to do this might be to allocate funds on a per pupil basis. This
could guarantee spending equity while preserving local community decision
making. </P>
<HR>
