<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Editorial 8/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A> | <A HREF="vtnea100.htm">List
of Editorials</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea200.htm">Opportunities for Educators</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Advice for Parents and Support for Kids</A></P>
<H1><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">We have incredibly important work to do</FONT></B></H1>
<P><B>By Angelo J. Dorta, Vermont-NEA President</B></P>
<P>There is something undeniably exciting, invigorating, and even magical about
the start of a new school year. Everyone feels it: students, educators, parents,
citizens. The reminders and symbols are everywhere. Department store aisles
overflow with school supplies and gleaming lunchboxes sporting the most popular
cartoon or movie characters and real-life young celebrities. Shoppers for school
clothes inevitably debate fashionable versus practical, costly versus reasonably
priced, &quot;I'm not gonna' wear it!&quot; versus &quot;You'll wear it or else!&quot;
Yellow school buses again lead parades of slow-moving traffic heading to work. 
</P>
<P>The human spirit of hope, of renewed opportunity, perhaps even a bit of
personal redemption is what powers our eager anticipation of school in late
August. There aren't many experiences in this life that allow individuals to
start afresh, to make a new beginning. Thankfully, the school experience is one
of them! 
</P>
<P>In a very real way, everyone connected with schools can begin the first day
with a clean slate. The shackles of the past can be broken. Former failings,
transgressions, and deficiencies can be forgotten and forgiven. Great
possibilities exist for all if we can adopt this mindset. Every boy and girl in
your class now can be a star student regardless of last year's academic or
behavioral problems. Despite past power struggles and personality conflicts,
every child now can be that special student and young friend long remembered
even after your retirement. The company president, the policeman or fireman, the
professional artist, the plumber or travel agent, the teacher, principal, or
instructional assistant of tomorrow all are seated in your class. What is
required at this moment is only the allowance of a new beginning. 
</P>
<P>Every lesson plan, instructional activity, and unit of study now potentially
abounds with student learning and  motivation, with those precious &quot;teachable
moments&quot; that later in the year can seem as rare as black pearls. Perhaps
the 1996-97 school year will yield improved relations with a troublesome
colleague, or deeper trust and camaraderie within your teacher-team, or even
smoother contract negotiations and beneficial media reportage. 
</P>
<P>Why do I advocate such positive thinking and optimism? Two reasons, the
first a highly personal one: thirty five or forty years ago, I was that
elementary and middle-grade student who desperately wanted a clean slate to
begin the year and a caring relationship with my teacher. My home environment
was economically and emotionally difficult. I needed to know that my teacher
valued me as a person, that I could learn and achieve in the classroom, and that
I had true friends among my peers. Fortunately for me, I had a succession of
educators and other school employees who provided such support. A happy and
productive school life kept me going when troubles were brewing at home. 
</P>
<P>The second reason is a practical one that -- for many of us -- acknowledges
a sad reality about our jobs: there is a part of ourselves that resists and even
dreads our return to the classroom. It is natural and really has nothing to do
with our students, nor with the practice of teaching itself, nor with our
co-workers and contracts. Simply put, working in schools in the 1990's takes a
tremendous toll on our personal lives and well-being. 
</P>
<P>Many of us grow increasingly weary and emotionally drained as planning and
corrections paperwork mount, as the serious student discipline problems
dramatically surface, as the challenges of learning dysfunction and family
instability become more recognizable and severe within our classrooms while the
support services and resources dwindle. We are burdened by those well-known
impossible-to-please citizens in our communities, by the reporters, legislators,
and candidates who want to criticize directly or obliquely our best efforts, by
the constant negativity of some colleagues in our own building, by the strains
of working together within a SYSTEM -- teachers, students, administrators,
support staff, parents, taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>This tangible downside to public school work, this personal toll, must be
recognized and resisted rather than ignored. Acknowledging its existence and its
impact helps to contain it and to compensate for it. That's why every school day
must be a new day and a fresh beginning for every school employee and student.
We always must carry at least a remnant of today's hope and energy and high mood
into our classrooms on each successive day. We need to draw from it when our
minds and bodies and enthusiasm for the work begin to sink, as they will at
times. If each day really is new in our hearts and in our minds, then we also
possess a limitless array of the best opportunities for ourselves,  our
students, and our colleagues. 
</P>
<P>You see, we have two very special elements in our favor: One, we are strong
individuals, and even stronger when working together. We would not still be
working in schools if we weren't strong people. And two, we have incredibly
important work to do. In the words of Marge Piercy's 1973 poem entitled &quot;To
Be of Use&quot;: 
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The people I love the best jump into work head first 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>without dallying in the shadows...
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>who strain in the mud and the muck to move things forward, 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>who do what has to be done, again and again. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>...who are not parlor generals or field deserters 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>but move in a common rhythm
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>...the thing worth doing well done has a shape that satisfies,  clean and
evident. ...
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The pitcher cries for water to carry and the person for work that is real. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>We indeed have real work to do. Let us try our best to do it well. Have a
successful year.  
</P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A> | <A HREF="vtnea100.htm">List
of Editorials</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea200.htm">Opportunities for Educators</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Advice for Parents and Support for Kids</A></P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
