<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Editorial 9/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A> | <A HREF="vtnea100.htm">List
of Editorials</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea200.htm">Opportunities for Educators</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Advice for Parents and Support for Kids</A></P>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">&quot;No one wins alone... We need to devise a
community strategy for school improvement&quot;
</FONT></H1>
<P><B>By Angelo J. Dorta, Vermont-NEA President</B></P>
<P>It's not a pretty sight when citizens begin to turn against their schools. I
know. It's happening right now in my own community, the Mount Mansfield Union
Supervisory School District. A springtime rescind petition and a switch to
Australian balloting helped to defeat the $10 million 1996-97 school budget. A
recent 3-hour information meeting for the public revealed harsh disdain of the
school board's decision to trim only $60,000 (.6%) from the original proposal.
It also produced a cacophony of related school criticisms. 
</P>
<P>My neighbors are hopping mad about high property taxes. They're frustrated
that 80% of  school costs -- such as negotiated teacher contracts, special
education, administration, and out-of-district high school tuition for
technical/vocational education -- are expenses still  beyond their control
despite the budget defeat. They talk of an NEA &quot;stranglehold&quot; on
school boards around the state. 
</P>
<P>They also recite a seemingly endless litany of personal school anecdotes
that decry a lack of student academic prowess and that question the proficiency
of our teachers. Few speak positively and publicly about our two middle schools
and the high school. They ignore comparatively low costs-per-pupil, already high
teacher-student ratios, and levels of student achievement judged better than
merely acceptable by all available measures. Approval of the slightly revised
budget at the September re-vote may or may not occur. A local budget-slashing
group calling itself Enough Is Enough again is spearheading the drive to reject
the budget. I worry about the possibility of larger budget cuts in the future
and their impact on the education of my 15-year-old and 12-year-old sons. 
</P>
<P>I realize that I am not alone in my concern. Educators, parents, and school
supporters of all kinds have had good reason to fret in recent weeks and months.
In communities such as Colchester, Newport, Milton, Benson, St. Albans, and
Shelburne, serious questions are being raised by vocal citizen groups about
fundamental school issues: how Vermonters pay for education; how to accurately
gauge student progress; how to balance real school costs against &quot;opportunities
to learn&quot; for all students; evaluation practices and judgments of teacher
competence; the validity of various instructional methods, goals, and
philosophies identified either as &quot;the basics&quot; or as &quot;education
reform&quot;; the meaning and relevance of vouchers, school &quot;choice,&quot;
and merit pay; and the role of teachers' unions in facilitating or impeding
necessary school improvement. Easy explanations and sound-byte answers do not
exist for these substantive school matters. 
</P>
<P>Certainly, a burdensome and unfair system of local property taxation
inflames the ongoing debate about our schools. It represents a compelling
problem for Vermont-NEA members and their neighbors. However, let us not be
mistaken: if school funding in Vermont suddenly became equitable, adequate, and
progressive overnight, issues of school quality and of teachers unions still
would be on the minds and lips of citizens at school meetings, in supermarkets,
on radio and television, in cyberspace, and at all types of social and business
gatherings in our communities. Our society now realizes full well that the
desired paths to national economic security and to an individually satisfying
quality of life both must pass directly through our schoolhouse doors.
Unfortunately, a national drumbeat of unremitting criticism and denigration of 
public education for a dozen years has shaken community support for our local
schools. 
</P>
<P>What is the proper stance and course of action for our local Associations? I
believe that we must directly engage our severest critics, our marginal
supporters, and the undecideds on their own local turf, on the issues of
greatest concern: property taxes, school quality, and teachers' unions. We must
initiate no-holds-barred discussion forums that are open to everyone in the
community and that acknowledge the issue of confidence in our local public
schools. 
</P>
<P>First, we will have to LISTEN. We must listen without defensiveness, without
justifications and self-satisfactions. Without bruised egos and a sense of
underappreciation. Without meek explanations that can be taken by skeptics as
only rationalizations and excuses. As difficult as it will be, we first must
allow them to express the common complaints, allegations, biases, and
misconceptions -- as well as the honest questions and doubts --  that are
undermining confidence in public education today. Try first to understand, then
to be understood. 
</P>
<P>Next, we must RESPOND. In simple, clear, jargon-free language, we must
communicate the complexities of daily teaching and the fact that we are working
harder than ever before. We need to explain the new education challenges
presented by children, families, and American culture in the '90s. And we must
state -- in no uncertain terms, with unquestionable data -- that public school
teachers have never done a better job of providing educational excellence and
equity for all students than we are doing today. All of the traditional
indicators of student achievement support this assertion, and we must use them.

</P>
<P>Finally, we must SEEK CONSENSUS. In a series of several meetings, we must
join with all willing community members to develop a shared vision for our
students and for our local schools. That guiding vision must focus on our common
future instead of on the differences of the past. We need community goals for
what our students should know and be able to do based on high expectations for
all children. We need to devise a community strategy for school improvement. 
</P>
<P>No one wins alone. All community groups must meet the challenge together.
Vermont-NEA members must help to weave together a broad network of support for
teachers and schools, a community-wide partnership of educators, parents and
non-parents, business people, senior citizens, professionals and blue-collar
workers, labor leaders and clergy. Only these community partnerships will assure
that necessary services and resources are provided to schools to produce the
highest academic achievement possible for all of our students. 
</P>
<P>These are troublesome times for public education and for unionism. We need
faith that we can move beyond the disagreements with our neighbors to work
together cooperatively for the benefit of the children in our communities.
Without such faith, nothing will change. Schools and their communities will go
down grappling with each other until the bitter end, while public education
crumbles before our very eyes. 
</P>
<P>I need that faith now to bridge the gap with school critics in my own home
school district in the shadow of Mount Mansfield. Perhaps you need it, too. We
will make the resources of this Association available to you in your efforts.
Our Vermont communities must become the nurturing fields for our schools and for
our common future.           
</P>
<HR>
