<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Editorial 10/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A> | <A HREF="vtnea100.htm">List
of Editorials</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea200.htm">Opportunities for Educators</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Advice for Parents and Support for Kids</A></P>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Virtually every school must become a school of
choice</FONT>
</H1>
<H2><I>&quot;Educate the best, forget the rest&quot; is unacceptable </I>
</H2>
<P><B>By Angelo J. Dorta, Vermont-NEA President</B></P>
<P>Whether you know it or not, whether you are ready and willing or not, you
now are a front-line soldier in the battle for public education. The struggle is
beginning to rage full-throttle throughout Vermont and the United States. Its
final outcome will determine the parameters of &quot;public&quot; schooling in
the 21st century. The issue is called &quot;school choice.&quot; Republican
candidate for president Bob Dole made it a high-profile topic recently, but it
already had been embraced across-the-board by other GOP candidates in Vermont
and elsewhere: gubernatorial candidate John Gropper, Lieutenant Governor running
mate John Carroll, and U.S. House challenger Susan Sweetser have reserved seats
on the bandwagon.  They seem to be reading from the same national script: public
schools have failed, they are inferior when compared to our international
counterparts, and it's time to &quot;blow the system wide open&quot; (Carroll)
by providing public tax dollars to any and every private religious and
non-sectarian school. An unrestricted marketplace of competing public and
private schools is their vision for better education and for school improvement
in Vermont's cities, towns, and villages of the future. 
</P>
<P>Let's be clear about a crucial point: Vermont-NEA does not oppose all forms
of school choice. Schools must be highly responsive to their local communities
and must accommodate explicit, strong desires for sound instructional options.
But we believe that choices for students and their parents can be expanded and
incorporated immediately into existing local public schools in several ways:
</P>
<P>1) Small schools and single-school districts must use their hiring powers to
secure the services of individual teachers with specific styles and philosophies
that result in a more instructionally diverse teaching staff. Also, voluntary
consolidation of the very smallest schools for greater economy and for greater
classroom variety would be helpful. 
</P>
<P>2) Large schools can develop &quot;school-within-a-school&quot;
organizational plans. This concept allows teams of teachers to more precisely
define and implement distinct teaching and learning methodologies, curriculum
innovations or emphases, systems for delivery of student special services,
alternatives for grouping students and for organizing grade levels, sets of
unique educational experiences, and access to various types of education
technology, resources, and learning materials. Classrooms with teaming teachers
usually are located together within the school building.      
</P>
<P>3) Multi-school single districts and supervisory unions could establish one
or more designated &quot;magnet school(s)&quot; that can attract and enroll
students from anywhere in the district or supervisory union who want education
based on an attribute of instruction described in (2).  
</P>
<P>However, Vermont-NEA will vigorously oppose school choice plans that give
public tax dollars to private non-sectarian and religious schools and that
simply abandon  low-performing schools. Uncontrolled school choice and voucher
programs are likely to intensify educational stratification and inequity when
advantaged schools cream the best students and the most funding, while
struggling schools are further depleted. Public accountability and traditional
community control over school governance and use of funds  would become obsolete
or meaningless, especially for 75% of our taxpaying citizens who do not have
children in schools. Re-segregation of many students according to wealth and
social class, to ethnic or racial or religious group, and to intellectual or
physical ability and disability is probable. The role of our local public
schools as the laboratories of democracy for school-age children in a culturally
heterogenous society will be lost or diminished. School advertising and
marketing to increase enrollments will be elevated above the substance of school
performance and student achievement. Tuition fees will rise for schools in
demand. Time and additional funds will be needed for state and local officials
to administer and monitor choice programs. A practical solution to the
formidable problems of equal access to transportation and of transportation
costs have not yet been suggested. Parents will regularly require information
and counseling about school options. What happens when a student is rejected by
their school of choice, which occurs 66% of the time now among private schools?

</P>
<P>We must acknowledge that there is not yet any significant, consistent,
unambiguous data which supports school choice as the primary means to better
schools and to greater student achievement. Indeed, a comprehensive and
scientifically rigorous study of this issue never has been done. School choice
only can become a meaningful factor when internal school improvement efforts
produce more high performance, 21st century -style schools from which to choose.
To reach that goal, we must establish a prior and a steadfast commitment at the
national, state, and local levels to reasonably equal educational opportunities
for all students and to sufficient funding for our schools. Choice plans must
attack the truly difficult problem: stimulating improvement in schools operating
at lower levels of effectiveness rather than simply reinforce today's adequate
and outstanding schools. Ineffective schools will not improve if currently
touted choice plans deprive them of needed fiscal and human resources. 
</P>
<P>Virtually every school must become a school of choice, perhaps some with
distinctive programs that are developed in complementary and collaborative ways
rather than competitively. Together, we need to pursue positive developments
such as higher academic standards, more technology, finer and more varied school
report data and student assessments, and school-based decision-making. As
independent education researcher Ann Bastian suggests, we must ask ourselves
these questions: Is public education irredeemable? Does equity matter? Who
should govern education? How well does the unrestricted marketplace fulfill
human needs? 
</P>
<P>Education in Vermont and in the United States always has been viewed as
serving the public good, not a purely personal or private interest. Our system
of public education has served this country far too well for over 300 years for
us to jeopardize it now with radical, unproven experimentation. Vermont-NEA
cannot support plans which result in policies that intentionally or
inadvertently promote an &quot;educate the best and forget the rest&quot;
philosophy. We can and will, however, work with all citizens to achieve and
support choice aimed at providing an excellent education for all children.
</P>
<HR>
