<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Editorial 11/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A> | <A HREF="vtnea100.htm">List
of Editorials</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea200.htm">Opportunities for Educators</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Advice for Parents and Support for Kids</A></P>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Vermont-NEA will participate in Rutland area public
school choice study
</FONT></H1>
<P><B><I><FONT SIZE="+1">Vermont-NEA President Angelo Dorta delivered these
remarks at a news conference October 24, 1996 at the Vermont-NEA Convention...
</FONT></I></B></P>
<P>The 145th Annual Vermont-NEA Educators' Convention is an occasion for
celebrating the tremendous professionalism and the tireless dedication of our
teachers and school support staff from Bennington to Richford, from St. Albans
to St. Johnsbury. And there are many achievements to celebrate:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The number of Vermont high school students taking a core curriculum of four
years of English, and three years each of math, science, and social studies has
more than tripled since 1982.</LI>
<LI>Vermont SAT scores have increased each year since 1993 despite the fifth
highest participation rate in the country &#151; 70 percent &#151; compared to a
national average participation of 41 percent.</LI>
<LI>Vermont's high school completion rate has remained steady for the past 10
years at about 85 percent despite profound changes in family structure, work,
and general society. By contrast, in the 50s, nearly half of all high school
students quit before graduating. Most handicapped and disabled Vermont students
were taught at home or in institutions, rather than experiencing the equal
education opportunities that exist today in Vermont's very inclusive public
school classrooms.</LI>
<LI>More than 50 percent of Vermont students continue with post-secondary
education, over 20 percent more than three decades ago.</LI>
<LI>Recent College Board citations for Vermont students included
better-than-national average performance on most Advanced Placement tests and
English and Math achievement tests.</LI></UL>
<P>The data goes on and on, and the message is clear: Most Vermont students who
care about learning receive a high quality education. That does not mean we are
complacent. Vermont-NEA members realize that the new world order of global
markets and international production centers require a high skilled U.S.
workforce that knows how to use technology and teamwork and solid academic
skills to design efficient solutions to every-changing problems. 
</P>
<P>Ironically, at a time when student achievement results and teacher
qualifications have never been higher, the effectiveness of Vermont's public
schools are at the center of a swirling debate.
</P>
<P>1996 has been the year of the school choice issue in Vermont. Speculation on
the value, the costs, and the utter practicality of allowing parents to choose
their children's schools has surfaced strongly in candidate speeches, in
editorial columns, at school board meetings and community forums, and in casual
conversations between average citizens across this state. However, at this very
moment, there is only one certainty about school choice: its long-term impact on
student achievement, on the sustainability of our local schools and local school
governance, and indeed on the very spirit that enlivens our communities is
unknown.
</P>
<P>Some candidates and vocal citizens make much of the fact that parents in 90
Vermont communities already have public school choice options because their
towns lack local elementary or high schools. This unique tradition exists solely
because of the preponderance of small, rural communities in Vermont. It is
vitally important to note that choosing between public schools and
state-approved independent school in other communities does not jeopardize
school enrollment in the towns of residence for these students.
</P>
<P>Vermont-NEA believes that it is time to get some likely answers to some
serious and specific questions about prospective public school choice plans in
our great state:</P>
<UL>
<LI>questions about access that focus on transportation capability, enrollments
limits, and admissions procedures for various classes and education programs;</LI>
<LI>questions about costs and funding that consider town financial resources
and more equalized tax rates and State Aid;</LI>
<LI>questions about school governance that examine existing state statutes,
State Board of Education regulations, and accountability to taxpayers who do not
use the schools or who live in towns away from the school programs;</LI>
<LI>questions about special education services and school commitment to
providing equal education opportunities for all students;</LI>
<LI>questions about costs and procedures to regularly inform and counsel
parents about school options and about the rights, responsibilities, and
limitations that may accompany their decision;</LI>
<LI>questions about the impact of school choice, competition, and marketplace
principles such as supply-and-demand on school tuition fees, advertising,
schools with declining enrollments, and student diversity.</LI></UL>
<P>If parents, students, and taxpayers truly believe that they need more
choices in education, then 350 years of U.S. public education demands that our
public schools provide those choices to ensure academic excellence and equity
for all of our children. Vermont's public schools belong to the citizens of this
state. They have the ultimate authority and responsibility necessary to work
alongside local educators and other school employees to create the 21st Century
schools that are needed. Citizens must help improve their schools, not fall into
the trap of negativism and scapegoating that simply leads to school abandonment.
</P>
<P>Therefore, today Vermont-NEA announces its acceptance of Rutland
Superintendent David Wolk's invitation to participate in the Public School
Choice Collaborative Study Group. The Study Group will examine the essential
issues related to the possible establishment of a countywide, Rutland region
choice plan among public schools. Vermont-NEA's Board of Directors has
authorized me to attend meetings of the Study Group beginning on October 29th at
Rutland's Stafford Technical Center along with fellow local Association
representatives from the six area superintendencies. I thank Superintendent Wolk
for his invitation and salute him for his vision and timing in calling for a
thorough, grassroots-level study of public school choice before any new
legislation is contemplated. Vermont-NEA can and will work with all citizens to
achieve and support education options aimed at proving excellent schooling for
all children, regardless of their family's personal wealth or geographic
location.
</P>
<P>On a closing note, it is important to underscore again the fact that the
Study Group only will be examining public school options. Nearly 70 percent of
Vermont House candidates and 55 percent of Senate candidates stated forthrightly
their opposition to the use of public tax dollars for non-approved private or
parochial schools, when they were interviewed in August by over 400 Vermont-NEA
members who voluntarily staffed our district and county candidate screening
committees.
</P>
<HR>
