<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Editorial 12/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A> | <A HREF="vtnea100.htm">List
of Editorials</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea200.htm">Opportunities for Educators</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Advice for Parents and Support for Kids</A></P>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">President Dorta answers Free Press attack</FONT></H1>
<P><B><I><FONT SIZE="+1">Editorialists at Vermont's largest daily newspaper
unleashed a barrage of mean commentary against Vermont-NEA last month in
response to the Association's decision to accept an invitation to join in a
study of public school choice in the Rutland area. This was President Angelo
Dorta's &quot;It's My Turn&quot; answer to the Free Press attack: 
</FONT></I></B></P>
<P>Your November 2 editorial, &quot;The Last Player,&quot; recycles trashy,
time-worn, anti-Vermont-NEA propaganda. Teachers across this state rarely become
disgusted any longer, or even disappointed, at your criticisms. For the past 10
years, we've come to expect Free Press disrespect and negativity towards us and
our organizations. </P>
<P>The editorial is noteworthy only for its venomous and derogatory undertone. 
Your backhanded compliment to Vermont-NEA for joining the Rutland-area public
school choice study is a veil. Your real purpose is to dredge up and to
perpetuate a meanspirited characterization of Association goals and
perspectives. Like Bob Dole, you assert an artificial division between teachers
and Vermont-NEA by claiming that &quot;Vermonters tend to love individual
teachers...&quot; and then proceeding to castigate their state union. 
</P>
<P>You accuse us of dragging our heels on school choice. Then, displaying an
abysmal lack of awareness, you ironically list the very questions that
Vermont-NEA has publicly and oft-repeatedly stated must be answered by a
grassroots study before any statewide or regional interdistrict choice plan
should be implemented: costs, governance, transportation, special education,
admissions, student resegregation, and parent information. Somehow, you
myopically overlook Vermont-NEA's espousal of current intradistrict school
choice options that appeared on your own September 12 editorial page. 
</P>
<P>Vermont-NEA &quot;is giving the profession a bad name?&quot; We &quot;grind
to dust proposals for improving education?&quot; Most teachers today would give
you a failing grade for research &#151; if indeed any actual research was done &#151;
and for journalistic fairmindedness. Check your facts, please. Have you
forgotten the annual Vermont-NEA Educators' Convention, with nearly 200
education exhibitors, two dozen workshops, and eight Scholars' Bowl academic
competitions for high school teams? What about the 20 different subject
affiliates that are partially subsidized by Vermont-NEA, such as the Vermont
Council of Teachers of Math or the Vermont Foreign Languages Association or the
Vermont Council on Reading? Have you visited our web site at www.vtnea.org and
seen the &quot;Advice for Parents and Support for Kids&quot; pages and our
suggested book list for K-12 readers? Did you decide to ignore the information I
sent you regarding the Vermont-NEA Teaching and Learning Programs and the
Listening to Parents initiative? Do you recall our participatory community
forums that were reported in your newspaper on October 2? Aren't you aware that
our members and elected Association leaders provided straightforward testimony
and endorsement of regular, frequent, and rigorous teacher evaluation at a joint
hearing of the House and Senate Education Committees in Montpelier last March?
Have you spoken with individual and educational organization policymakers
(Governor Howard Dean, Education Commissioner Marc Hull, Vermont PTA, State
Department of Education, etc.) to gauge Vermont-NEA's strong support of higher
academic standards, more comprehensive statewide student assessment, and greater
parental involvement? 
</P>
<P>Similarly, unbiased research also clearly shows that Vermont-NEA has
advocated fairer and less burdensome education financing for over a decade, not
opposed it, as the Free Press contends. In 1994, we worked with the Vermont
Superintendents Association, the Vermont Principals Association, the Vermont
Coalition of Disability Rights, and three other groups to jointly develop six
principles for funding Vermont public education and used them to evaluate
legislative proposals and to lobby for acceptable bills together at the
Statehouse. In the 1990 Legislature, a Vermont-NEA property tax reform bill was
introduced that asked for a $50,000 homestead exemption, full funding of the
Current Use Program, a tax on second homes and some commercial properties, and
decoupling the state income tax from the federal. Go back four years earlier to
1986 and dig out our Fair Tax Initiative that suggested a $25,000 homestead
exemption, statewide property tax classifications with variable tax rates, and a
decoupled state income tax. 
</P>
<P>Individuals may agree or disagree with our specific proposals, but
Vermont-NEA is not obstructionist. We fought alongside the Vermont School Boards
Association and other allies against former Speaker Ralph Wright's statewide
teachers' contract in '93 and '94 because it was detrimental to local school
governance and policy matters, negated 25 years of collective bargaining rights
for our members, and couldn't deliver on its economic promises of state
affordability and equalized teacher salaries. 
</P>
<P>We are ethically obligated to our members, to their students, and to all
Vermonters to express serious concerns and to advocate for a strong, high
quality, equitable public school system. The views of many Vermont citizens are
influenced by your columns. In this instance, you betrayed your public
responsibility to consider positive facts in your possession about the
Association. Unlike the newspaper's reckless diatribe, Vermont-NEA states
explicitly what we support and what we oppose, and we back our stances with
clear rationales. When new data and conditions and member viewpoints evolve,
then we adjust our positions on the issues accordingly. That's hardly a &quot;rigid
organization,&quot; in my view. 
</P>
<P>Your comfortable, second-floor editorial office certainly has great views of
College and Church Streets. I've visited you three times for discussions since
May, 1995. However, I suggest that you come down to the street level more often.
That's where teachers and students reside each day. That's where you can find
Vermont-NEA, too. So far, you've chosen not to see nor hear who we really are. 

</P>
<P><B>Angelo J. Dorta, Vermont-NEA President</B></P>
<HR>
