<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Editorial 1/97</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A> | <A HREF="vtnea100.htm">List
of Editorials</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea200.htm">Opportunities for Educators</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Advice for Parents and Support for Kids</A></P>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">&quot;We must ensure that our common voices are
heard above the surrounding cacophony...&quot;  </FONT></H1>
<P><B>By Angelo J. Dorta, Vermont-NEA President</B></P>
<P>For a decade or more in Vermont, a virtual din of broadcast media reports,
reams of newspaper text, and plentiful public forums around the state have
analyzed and debated the core policy issues of teaching and learning. Vermonters
have had constant exposure and ready access to the education viewpoints of
elected government officials, media pundits, business interests, community
groups, policy and research centers, other advocacy organizations, aspiring
political leaders, consultants, experts, and study teams, and polling firms.
Even loose networks of less-than-serious education dilettantes, entrepreneurs,
and wannabes easily gain a share of the education spotlight for their opinions
and pronouncements. 
</P>
<P>The only collective, organizational voice that has been mostly silent is
Vermont-NEA&#146;s -- at least up until now. Occasionally, we have been vocal in
the past on some non-contractual education quality issues, such as the struggle
to achieve a teacher-majority professional standards board and classroom special
services integration under Act 230. However, Vermont-NEA never before has
attempted to stake out a comprehensive set of principles and recommendations
that define our public positions on a broad array of classroom- and school-level
teaching and learning issues: qualifications for teaching, use of instructional
time, school standards for student decorum, curricular balance between academic
content and methodology, rigorous academic programs for all students and
remediation for any child who needs it, annual academic and career planning
advice to students and their parents beginning in the 7th grade, and others.
These daily professional concerns most directly and most consistently affect our
Association members and our student/parent/community clients. 
</P>
<P>Finally, a major effort has begun to chronicle educator perspectives on such
issues based on  repeated statements to Vermont-NEA leaders and staff, and then
to develop a clear, common, formal Association voice that speaks honestly and
positively from classrooms across Vermont. The results to date are compiled in a
draft report entitled &#147;Schools That Work: Keys to Improving Learning in
Vermont&#146;s Schools.&#148; The draft report&#146;s full text is published in
this edition of Vermont-NEA Today and also is available on Vermont-NEA&#146;s
website (www.vtnea.org). 
</P>
<P>Publication of the report in print and electronic draft form has one vital
purpose: to solicit as many member comments and suggestions for revisions as
possible in the weeks ahead. A statewide open hearing on the contents and
drafting process of &#147;Schools That Work&#148; is scheduled for Saturday,
January 25 in the Montpelier area. 
</P>
<P>The Vermont-NEA Board of Directors could take official action on the draft
report as early as their February 8 meeting. Over 1,000 copies of the draft
report already have been sent out from Vermont-NEA headquarters on request. At
least 200 Association members have participated in some type of focussed
discussion led by Association Board members, local leaders, and UniServ staff
and have provided immediate, face-to-face feedback. Six regional UniServ
District meetings lead by me in November and December included give-and-take
over the substance and process of the report&#146;s initial public draft.
Suggested revisions in notes and letters arrive at the Association&#146;s office
each day and carefully are added to the cumulative catalogue of responses. 
</P>
<P>Sparked by the well-substantiated critiques of frank and assertive members,
15 significant changes -- in total, over 75 improvements -- already have been
incorporated into the original document by the committee writing team and
subsequently approved by the Board of Directors on December 7. Now, all
Association members have the most up-to-date version of &#147;Schools That Work&#148;
in their hands for personal, independent review and for dialogue with their
colleagues. And the latest principles, recommendations, and accompanying
discussion text still are bound to change further.
</P>
<P>&#147;Schools That Work&#148; has spawned exactly the kind of rigorous,
democratic debate on relevant teaching and learning issues that Vermont-NEA has
needed for so long. It has elicited overall praise from the vast majority of
responding members, and some generally harsh but instructive criticism from a
few others. 
</P>
<P>Sanctioning probationary periods for new teachers, establishing a 200-day
school year, requiring teachers to achieve a master&#146;s degree or equivalent
college-level coursework, and examining the balance between concerns for
academic achievement and student self-esteem have been particularly
controversial so far. However, encountering diverse member viewpoints naturally
occurs when venturing into previously uncharted policy areas. I&#146;m confident
that a more participatory and organizationally healthy Association will emerge.
Ultimately, our internal rough-and-tumble will hone a document that will be more
representative of our entire constituency. A stronger Association voice
consequently will be heard on these school matters of daily importance. </P>
<P>Few of us may end up agreeing with every single point in the report, but
does it, we must ask ourselves, on balance accurately reflect our collective
thinking? The absolutely most crucial statement in the report perhaps is an
implicit one: Vermont-NEA now intends to become fully engaged with members, with
citizens, and with officials and leaders of every type on all aspects of
teaching and learning.    
</P>
<P>Each passing day adds even greater urgency to our task. Others clamor for
recognition and approval of their own specific recommendations and agendas for
public school improvement. Many of them have experiences far removed from the
daily realities of Vermont classrooms that we have known for years. Therefore,
they can offer little advice of practical value and much that can inadvertently
undermine and be harmful to our schools and students. Widespread support for
public school education now seems more tenuous than ever due to a rising tide of
clashing political ideologies, perplexing international comparisons of student
achievement levels, and crushing economic disparities. 
</P>
<P>The &#147;Schools That Work&#148; report, however, can become a powerful
catalyst and a platform under constant construction to support future
Association actions which more precisely and more effectively serve the changing
instructional leadership and advocacy needs of the members. The draft report&#146;s
introduction sounds a reasoned call for &#147;a renewed and enhanced commitment
to high intellectual and behavioral standards in Vermont&#146;s public schools.&#148;
We must ensure that our common voices are heard above the surrounding cacophony,
and they must be heard soon, before it is too late. 
</P>
<P>In a letter written by me and published in the June, 1995 Vermont-NEA Today,
 I thanked members for my election and promised to &#147;tell it like it is.&#148;
I thought that my own 22 years in public school classrooms was sufficient
experience. It is not. I need your help because it is our collective experience
and vision that now is essential. </P>
<HR>
