<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Editorial 2/97</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A> | <A HREF="vtnea100.htm">List
of Editorials</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea200.htm">Opportunities for Educators</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Advice for Parents and Support for Kids</A></P>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">&quot;Let&#146;s hope that the bloom of spring at
the Statehouse brings the legislation that we need...&quot; 
</FONT></H1>
<P><B>By Angelo J. Dorta, Vermont-NEA President</B></P>
<P>A time-honored ritual now is underway. Throughout our state, the political
attention of Vermonters has begun to turn towards the golden dome of the
Statehouse in Montpelier. What will be the real achievements of Vermont&#146;s
citizen-legislature this year? That question is posed rhetorically during winter
snow and cold, but the answers will emerge with spring&#146;s warming crocuses
and daffodils. 
</P>
<P>Last year, Vermont-NEA figuratively turned several major corners amid the
hallways and committee rooms of the Statehouse. We sought to challenge
legislator perceptions of the Association and its members and to cultivate a
more accurate view of Vermont-NEA. Offering to give up the right to strike in
exchange for mandatory binding interest arbitration and the removal of school
board imposition powers surprised and intrigued lawmakers.  State Representative
and State Senators also discovered from testifying Association members that we
do not fear or avoid performance evaluation. On the contrary, we told them,
teachers and support staff insist that evaluations be rigorous, fair, and
frequent because that&#146;s how we prove our competence to the community and
how we help to raise the overall quality of the education workforce. In fact, we
consider it downright demeaning to us and to our profession that so many school
district evaluation instruments and procedures are weak and haphazard, when used
at all. 
</P>
<P>Your Association lobbyists &#151;Executive Director Dick Lang, General
Counsel Joel Cook, and myself&#151; were always calm, courteous, and informative
in our frequent individual conversations with legislators and government
officials. Our testimony in committee meetings and at hearings was factual and
well-prepared. We listened carefully and were proactive and positive in
expressing the Association&#146;s viewpoints.  We spoke authoritatively and
persistently for higher student academic standards and for reasonable statewide
student assessment and testing strategies; for structural improvements and
greater equity in the property tax system of school funding; for the
establishment of acceptable indoor air quality measures in schools; for
consistent use of objective data in education decision-making; for early
diagnosis and intervention in reading; for enhanced access to computer
technology to support classroom learning; for use of existing, appropriate
discipline guidelines in special education law to control disruptive and
dangerous student misbehavior; for increasing the State&#146;s share in the cost
of public education; and for ensuring the fiscal integrity of the State Teachers&#146;
Retirement System. 
</P>
<P>We accomplished our objectives or made progress in some of these areas.
Other proposals fell by the wayside when property tax reform efforts failed
again. Many will be revived in the days and weeks ahead as Vermont-NEA and its
allies refuse to simply abandon worthy, unfinished legislative business.   
</P>
<P>We also provided the critical analyses that stoked opposition to Rutland&#146;s
plan to use public tax vouchers to help pay student tuition at non-approved
private and religious schools; to a flawed charter schools provision that also
ultimately would have diverted funding from existing public schools; to the
shifting of responsibility for teacher retirement costs to local school
districts; and to a bevy of GOP notions that were ill-conceived and damaging:
increased class sizes through reductions in teaching staff, wholesale waiving of
the teacher license requirement, de facto elimination of just and sufficient
cause for teacher dismissals, allowance for retroactive and multi-year contract
impositions by school boards, and others. In conjunction with many like-minded
education organizations and private citizens, we helped expose the dangers in
these proposals that resulted in their demise.   
</P>
<P>By adjournment in early May last year, many lawmakers viewed Vermont-NEA
more favorably than at any time since the days preceding the 1993 statewide
teachers&#146; contract proposal. Occasionally, some simply complimented us on
our presentations or respectfully acknowledged a clearer understanding of
Association goals and positions. Others, however, praised us in private for
exhibiting a renewed or heightened sense of education professionalism and
earnestly urged us to continue this brand of vigorous legislative involvement.
They recognized Vermont-NEA&#146;s deep commitment to instructional leadership
and support issues as well as to traditional labor union matters. 
</P>
<P>It is time now to build further on this solid foundation for successful
legislative and political engagement. General Counsel Joel Cook has crafted the
most comprehensive compilation yet of Association public positions on a broad
range of education policy issues that significantly affect our members: Agenda
for Public School Education and Educators. 
</P>
<P>Our most effective potential Association lobbyists, however, are the
400-plus members who served last summer and fall on the House district, county,
and statewide political action committees to assess several hundred candidates
for public office. Once mobilized again on specific House and Senate legislative
proposals, they can have direct and widespread Association impact on legislative
activity. Without doubt, legislators pay closest attention to the comments and
letters of their own constituents and are most likely to be swayed by the
sentiments of their voters. Statehouse accountability to our members, to our
students, and to our schools may depend largely on targeted and timely contacts
with legislators by these willing, grassroots, Association political activists. 
        Together, we will continue to push for the necessary resources, the
promising instructional reforms, and the employment conditions of educators that
can produce real and lasting student achievement and school improvement in
Vermont. We will stand firm against State-imposed limitations on local education
funding, privatization of school services, siphoning financial support  from
existing public schools, Retirement System underfunding, and school district
actions that presume guilt and that punish teachers accused of child abuse
before valid local investigations are concluded. It is an ambitious legislative
agenda in challenging times for public school educators. 
</P>
<P>Several months from now, let&#146;s hope that the bloom of spring at the
Statehouse brings the legislation that we need. Your help and support are
essential.     </P>
<HR>
