<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont Teacher of the Year</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFF80">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A> | <A HREF="vtnea100.htm">Who
We Are</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea200.htm">Opportunities for Educators</A> |
<A HREF="vtnea300.htm">Advice for Parents and Support for Kids</A></P>
<H1><FONT COLOR="#8000FF">Vermont-NEA member Peggy Dorta named Vermont Teacher
of the Year
</FONT></H1>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD>
<P><B><I>&quot;These days it is easy to get caught up in the rhetoric and
negative images that surround public education... But we need to work together
to accentuate the positive...&quot;
</I></B></P></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="peggy.jpg" WIDTH="200" HEIGHT="180"></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>UNDERHILL -- Peggy Dorta, a 27-year veteran teacher and multiage 1-4
classroom teacher at Underhill Central School, has been named Vermont's 1997
Teacher of the Year by the Vermont State Department of Education. She will
represent Vermont in the National Teacher of the Year competition, which is
sponsored by the Council of Chief State School Officers and Scholastic, Inc.
</P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT">Peggy Dorta is well known and respected among Vermont
educators. She is an adjunct professor for Trinity College, the University of
Vermont, and St. Michael's Prevel Graduate School. She works as a consultant in
Vermont and nationally and presents workshops in multiage education and
curricular issues. UVM videotaped her classroom to help preservice teachers with
ideas for setting up a classroom environment. Her presentation was the most
popular at the 1995 Educators' Convention, with the room filled to overflowing.
All this is in addition to a successful, full time career as a multiage
elementary school teacher, including nine years at Williston and going-on nine
in Underhill.  </P>
<P><B>This is a representative award
</B></P>
<P>Dorta says she was &quot;shocked, flattered, honored&quot; to be named
Vermont Teacher of the Year. She is very proud of her professional achievements,
but her pride extends beyond personal success: &quot;This is a representative
award,&quot; she says. &quot;I am not 'the best teacher in the state.' I simply
exemplify some of the wonderful things going on in education in Vermont. This
award tells me I'm on the right track.&quot;
</P>
<P>Dorta says that the reaction of her colleagues has been the best personal
award for being named Teacher of the Year. Teachers at her school threw her a
surprise party and gave her a  rosebush from Nantucket (a place she loves). &quot;They
really surprised me. It's the first time I've ever been speechless.&quot; And,
typically for Peggy Dorta, she learned something from the experience. &quot;It
is really important,&quot; she says, &quot;to turn to someone when you're
thinking it or feeling it and say:  'I appreciate you. I like what you do.'&quot;
</P>
<P>Dorta learns from every aspect of her life, beginning with her years as a
student in elementary school. &quot;The important message I learned way back
then was that each and every person is special. Each and every person has the
right and the need to be educated. That in school, skills and knowledge are
important objectives, but students' feelings and dispositions are equally so. We
need to listen and watch well enough to find ways to reach each student.&quot;
</P>
<P><B>Community and service</B>
</P>
<P>The parents gave Dorta a party, too, with flowers and a Miss America-style
sash decorated with the notes she has sent home to kids. 
</P>
<P>Community is important to Peggy Dorta. &quot;Ten years ago I made a
conscious decision to apply for a teaching job within the community where I
live,&quot; she explains in one of her National Teacher of the Year essays. &quot;It
has been wonderful to live and to work with families I know well. I appreciate
that I have been able to integrate service to my community within and through my
teaching program.&quot;
</P>
<P>Parent and community involvement are basic to Dorta's philosophy of
teaching. &quot;The student, the parent, and the teacher are the triad that make
success happen in school. Communication and involvement are key elements for
parents and the larger community,&quot; she says. &quot;It is my job to draw
them in and to inform them of what is happening. It is my goal to find a way for
each parent to participate in some way with the classroom activities.
Volunteering, spending a day with us, chaperoning field trips, giving a special
presentation, showing us their work or workplace. There are so many ways to
invite participation and it is such an important part of my program.&quot;
</P>
<P><B>Her message</B>
</P>
<P>Asked what advice she would offer to fellow educators, Dorta makes three
suggestions: Don't get overwhelmed. Take the time to reflect. Keep researching.
&quot;It's easy to get lost,&quot; she says, &quot;because we're so busy and
there is so much work to do. But we need to read and discuss and research. We
need to ask: 'What am I doing?' 'How am I doing it?' and most important, 'Why?'&quot;
</P>
<P>Dorta has a message, as well, for educators and the general public: &quot;Let's
work together... Let's make our focus the students... These days it is easy to
get caught up in the rhetoric and negative images that surround public
education... we need to work together to accentuate the positive and focus on
what we can do to continue to improve public education.&quot;</P>
<HR>
