<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Schools That Work DRAFT</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0">
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">DRAFT REPORT</FONT></B></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="sw-3.htm">Contents</A> | <A HREF="sw-4.htm">Learning
Environment</A> |
<A HREF="sw-5.htm">Educators</A> | <A HREF="sw-6.htm">Academics</A></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT COLOR="#800000">Schools That Work  --  Keys to
Improving Learning  in Vermont's Public Schools</FONT></H1>
<H2 ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT COLOR="#000040"><FONT COLOR="#800000">Schools That
Work:  Introduction</FONT>  
</FONT></H2>
<P>The social, political, and economic welfare of our state and nation depends
on the quality of our public schools. All children, irrespective of class,
gender, ethnicity or disability, need access to a high quality public education.
We must not permit our public schools to wither from within or close their doors
for lack of public support.</P>
<P>We know that some of our schools are in trouble, from within and without. 
</P>
<P>Inside education, we speak too often a language alien to the very people who
want most to support our schools. In plain talk, &quot;high standards&quot;
should reflect what the public generally means by that phrase.</P>
<P>Outside our schools, a host of social ills &#151; hunger and poverty, abuse
and family conflicts, alcoholism and drug addiction, depression and suicide &#151;
can cause a crippling effect on our classrooms. They eat up already limited time
and resources teachers have in which to hold together their schools and their
professional lives. Our schools have had to confront an ever-growing number of
young people simply not ready for a rigorous academic experience. </P>
<P>One self-defeating byproduct of all this: the teaching profession itself has
increasing difficulty attracting and retaining many of the most talented and
best educated college graduates.</P>
<P>While our loudest detrators come from the fringes, concern also comes from
our neighbors, our friends, our children's teachers, people who have been public
education's strongest advocates. They are weary of and frustrated by seemingly
declining standards and decorum in too many Vermont schools. They are tired of
being pitted against each other, and of seeing their communities suffer for it.
We cannot ignore heartfelt frustrations:  </P>
<UL>
<LI>&quot;My child never has any homework; he only read one book in English
last quarter.&quot;
</LI>
<LI>&quot;There's no support from administrators and parents.&quot;
</LI>
<LI>&quot;Why is my daughter always being put in groups to teach other kids who
are fooling around?&quot; 
</LI>
<LI>&quot;John's math teacher spends all her time trying to control one or two
disruptive students &#151; there's not much time left to teach Algebra.&quot; 
</LI>
<LI>&quot;I'm tired of watering down my curriculum. Every year I have to do
less or lower my expectations ... and I'm talking about kids headed for college.&quot;</LI></UL>
<P>It is time we all embraced a common sense response to these complaints. All
public schools should be safe, orderly places where each child learns at an
academically challenging level. Students should be respectful towards their
education, and they should be required to conduct themselves respectfully. If we
adhere to these simple rules, we will get good educational results:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Teachers will teach. 
</LI>
<LI>Parents will nurture.
</LI>
<LI>Administrators will support.
</LI>
<LI>Students will work hard and pursue scholastic achievement.
</LI>
<LI>Boards will set clear, high expectations.
</LI>
<LI>Everybody else will help where they can.</LI></UL>
<P>What people want from their public schools is safety, order, and instruction
in basic and advanced skills. They do not want to dismantle or abandon the
public school system &#151; because it can provide good educational results. We
need to address certain problems, starting now.</P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#800000">Where do we go from here?  </FONT></H2>
<P>Our challenge as Vermont-NEA members is to build a ground swell of support
with other concerned citizens and community groups to demand forcefully, without
equivocation, a renewed and enhanced commitment to  high intellectual and
behavioral standards in Vermont's public schools.</P>
<P>As teachers, we cannot afford to have &quot;standards&quot; become &#151; or
remain &#151; meaningless education jargon. We must insist that every classroom
be a place where learning goes on regularly, without interruption or disruption,
and we must ally ourselves with those parents and community members who share
this goal.</P>
<P>The Vermont Standard we advocate is one that imbues our schools with
excellence, order, and academic rigor. To begin, we must acknowledge and
confront practices in our schools that, even when successful, do not win broad
public support and are frequently misunderstood or inconsequential. No amount of
&quot;learning how to learn&quot; justifies diminished emphasis on mathematics,
writing, history, science, literature, or the arts.</P>
<P>Let us begin with honesty and substance. We must accept heartfelt, valid
criticism and respond by turning all our attention toward the substance of
education. We can do that only by focusing on safety, order, and respect for
real learning and the real work it requires.</P>
<P>As a result, Vermont-NEA will advocate for those changes we know will make
our public schools work better. We will continue to support complementary
principles which promote safety, order, and substance &#151; in short, a sound
educational program worthy of public support. In many communities in Vermont,
these principles are in place. In a disturbing number, however, not all are.
Unless they all are present, uniformly excellent education will always be a goal
rather than a reality.  
</P>
<P>In this document are compiled the thoughts and proposals of our members
about improving learning in Vermont's public schools. On their behalf, we now
bring them to the public. We ask you to join us in having every community adopt
them as its own.  
</P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#000040"><FONT COLOR="#800000">Vermont-NEA Keys to Improving
Learning in Our Public Schools  </FONT> </FONT></H2>
<P><B>We believe that a high quality public education system is characterized
by 3 key elements: </B></P>
<P><B><A HREF="sw-4.htm">I - Environment of learning </A></B></P>
<P><B><I>Highly attentive student bodies &#151; attention by parents and
community to sending all students to school every day physically and emotionally
ready to learn, and attention by schools to providing a place to learn that is
free of distractions  --</I></B></P>
<P><B>Keys</B></P>
<OL>
<LI>Strengthen student behavior standards 
</LI>
<LI>Enforce classroom attendance expectations</LI>
<LI>Improve the use of  instructional time
</LI>
<LI>Assure all students enter school each day ready to learn
</LI></OL>
<P><B><A HREF="sw-5.htm">II - Educators</A>   </B></P>
<P><B><I>High caliber teachers and administrative and support personnel &#151;
trained, knowledgeable, and energetic in providing a sound educational
environment for our children &#151;</I></B></P>
<P><B>Keys</B></P>
<OL>
<LI>Raise the professional qualifications required to obtain a teaching license
</LI>
<LI>Establish a two-year probationary period for newly licensed teachers
</LI>
<LI>Conduct frequent performance evaluations of education personnel throughout
their careers
</LI>
<LI>Provide educators career-long professional development emphasizing subject
matter knowledge and student learning</LI></OL>
<P><B><A HREF="sw-6.htm">III -Academic programs and standards</A>   </B></P>
<P><B><I>Dedication to a rich and varied academic curriculum &#151;
challenging and rigorous with sufficient flexibility to account for differing
learning styles and abilities  &#151;
</I></B></P>
<OL>
<LI>Elevate the importance of academic content 
</LI>
<LI>Provide rigorous academic program choices 
</LI>
<LI>Uphold grade advancement and graduation requirements 
</LI>
<LI>Provide regular planning and guidance for all students</LI>
<LI>Promote mastery of content over immediate self-esteem</LI></OL>
<HR>
