<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Hot Links for Kids</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H1><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Websites Recommended for Kids and Young Adults</FONT></H1>
<P><B><I>These websites are recommended by educators for kids and young
adults. Just click the apples to start exploring. And
<A HREF="mailto:links@vtnea.org">let us know</A> if there's a site you think
should be added to this list.</I></B></P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Kids</FONT></H2>
<P><A HREF="http://www.mtlake.com/cyberkids"><IMG
SRC="apple2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <B>CyberKids</B>  This site aims to
create a place for kids throughout the world to communicate and features
booklists, art, writing contests and a CyberKids Connection.</P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.kidlink.org/"><IMG SRC="apple2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A>
<B>KidLink</B>  This site works to build a global dialogue among children, age
10-15. Every child begins participating by answering four thought-provoking
questions.</P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Young Adults</FONT></H2>
<P><A HREF="http://www.mtlake.com/cyberteens"><IMG
SRC="apple2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <B>CyberTeens </B>  This site is an
offshoot of CyberKids and is designed as a place for teenagers to communicate.
Sponsored by software publisher Mountain Lake, the site features <I>Zeen</I>,
an online magazine devoted to teenage issues and creative writing.</P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.cit.state.vt.us:80/vhs/"><IMG
SRC="apple2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <B>Vermont Historical Society</B>  This
site includes information about Vermont history, historical sites, collections,
projects and research.</P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.pitsco.com/p/ask.html"><IMG
SRC="apple2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <B>Ask An Expert</B>  Teachers or
students can send e-mail from this site to an expert and receive a timely
response. Extensive listings cover all curriculum areas.</P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.nea.org/cet/links"><IMG SRC="apple2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A>
 <B>NEA Education Links (EDLinks)</B>  This area on the National Education
Association's website is reserved as a showcase for the best World Wide Web
links about Teaching, Learning and Technology.  Each link in the NEA database is
there because education practitioners, parents and kids who visit NEA's site
have asked that it be included.</P>
