<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA History-6</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H2><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Vermont Teacher Strikes</FONT></H2>
<P>Vermont's only teacher strikes* were by these Vermont-NEA local affiliates: 
</P>
<OL>
<LI>Champlain Valley Union High School Teachers Association (September 5 -_,
1978) - less than 1 week
</LI>
<LI>Burlington Education Association (September 6 - 12, 1978) - 1 week</LI>
<LI>Chester Education Association (April _-18, 1979) - 2 weeks</LI>
<LI>Rutland Education Association (August 30 - September 7, 1979) - ordered
back to work by Superior Court Judge Thomas Hayes</LI>
<LI>The Burke Unit of the Caledonia North Teachers Association (June 1980) -
one day</LI>
<LI>Poultney Teachers Association (May 1984) - less than 1 week</LI>
<LI>Hinesburg Unit of the Chittenden South Education Association (April 1985) -
87 days</LI>
<LI>Colchester Education Association (September 1985) - less than 2 weeks</LI>
<LI>Addison Northwest Teachers Association (February 1987) - about 1 week</LI>
<LI>Barre Education Association (January 1989) - about 1 week</LI>
<LI>Winooski Education Association (February 1989) - 3 days</LI>
<LI>North Country Union Education Association (May 1989) - about 1 week</LI>
<LI>Addison Northwest Teachers Association (December 6, 1989-January 3, 1990)
</LI>
<LI>Fair Haven Graded School Teachers Association (April 25-26, 1990) </LI>
<LI>Georgia Teachers Education Association (June 1-5, 1990)</LI>
<LI>Windham Northeast Education Association (December 1990) - about one week</LI>
<LI>Southwest Vermont Education Association (September 1992) - about one week</LI>
<LI>Oxbow Teachers Association (March 25-April 1, 1993)</LI></OL>
<P>* History does record one other teachers' strike in Vermont. This article
appeared in the Friday, June 9, 1911 edition of <I>The Vermont Journal</I>:</P>
<P><B>TEACHERS ON STRIKE</B></P>
<P>All the grade teachers, six in number, of the Swanton High and Graded School
have tendered their resignation to the superintendent, Mrs. Harriet M. Ide, on
the ground of inadequate salaries and the unwillingness of the Board to allow
them a small increase asked. Those who resigned were Miss Celia Corbett, Miss
Pearl Butterfield, Miss Elsbeth Neibel, Miss Grace Fitzsimmons, Miss Blanche
Blake and Miss Hazel Stone. All are teachers of experience, three having taught
over 10 years, one over six years and two for shorter terms in the grade
departments.</P>
<HR>
