<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Best Lessons</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1>U.S. History Debates -- The Progressive Era and the Proper Role of
Government
</H1>
<H4>Submitted by David Schoales, Morristown</H4>
<P>This unit is designed to enable high school students to achieve the Vermont
Framework standard for communication which requires them to &quot;use verbal and
nonverbal skills to express themselves with power and purpose.&quot; It includes
introductory and enabling activities as well as assessment guides and rubrics.
</P>
<P>This week we will be discussing the Progressives and looking for ways we can
continue their work toward making the United States a better country. For the
next two days we will be working in pairs to select an issue from the
Progressive Era and find background information about that issue. On the third
day, each student pair will prepare and engage in a debate about their issue.
Each student will take a side of the issue and play the role of someone
representing that side by presenting arguments in a debate. </P>
<P>Before you begin the research phase, it will be necessary to understand the
answers to the following questions:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>What did the Progressives believe about society?
<UL>
<LI>Do you agree with them?</LI></UL>
</LI>
<LI>Which of the achievements of the Progressives do you believe was the most
important for the United States?
<UL>
<LI>Why do you believe this was an important achievement? </LI>
<LI>How did it help the country?</LI></UL></LI></UL>
<P>A successful debate performance will include:</P>
<OL>
<LI>Clear evidence of planning and research</LI>
<LI>Background information which clearly communicates the facts of the issue</LI>
<LI>Effective use of pace, volume, enunciation, and gestures (body language)</LI>
<LI>Correct grammar and word choice</LI>
<LI>Expression of the importance of the issue</LI>
<LI>Clear expression of the presenter's opinion, preferences, feelings</LI></OL>
<P>Once we have concluded the Progressive Era debate, each pair will choose a
problem currently facing our country and prepare a debate presentation arguing
for local, state or federal government action (or inaction) to help solve the
problem.
</P>
<P>Call David Schoales for more information: 802-899-1375</P>
<HR>
