<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Best Lessons</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1>International research on food via telecommunications</H1>
<H4>Submitted by Dianne Gross Percy, Milton</H4>
<P>In this seven-week unit, fifth and sixth grade students at School Street
School in Milton learned to communicate via computers. They used
telecommunications to gather data about food from the international community
and to enrich their understanding of the world community through cross-cultural
contacts.
</P>
<P>First, classrooms within the school formed teams and hooked up by e-mail.
They worked out the bugs and learned data gathering skills in school, before
reaching out to the international community. </P>
<P>The teams selected a concept around food -- nutrition, cost, preparation,
eating out, waste disposal, sources of food, etc., and developed questions. 
Then, the students attempted to make contact with schools and kid nets around
the world. </P>
<P>The preparing and the waiting proved to be important lessons. Students and
teachers learned the importance of being flexible and succeeded in linking up
with Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>These Vermont-NEA members worked on the F.O.O.D. (Formulating Options On
Diversity) unit: Dianne Gross Percy, Maggie Stockwell, and Edward Barry. Call
Dianne for more information: 802-878-2744.
</P>
<HR>
