<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Best Lessons</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><I>To Kill a Mockingbird</I>
<B>&quot;There are some men in this world who are born to do our unpleasant
jobs for us.&quot;
</B></P>
<H1>Another framework for understanding Atticus Finch
</H1>
<H4>Submitted by Stephanie Keitel, Union-32</H4>
<P>Quotes were reviewed using the framework of emotional bank accounts from
Steven Covey's book, The Seven Habits of Highly Effective People. As a class, we
mapped emotional bank account deposits on a circle web of characters. Students
became so adept at this discussion framework that they lead several classes
using teacher prepared materials. Students also personalized the principals of
emotional bank accounts, resulting in many discussions of the qualities of true
friends. These discussions resulted in explicit visual proof of Atticus'
emotional deposits into both individuals and the community of Maycomb which
allowed the town's people to respect/tolerate his defense of Tom Robinson.
</P>
<P>This unit is easy to pull together with your own favorite quotes and Covey's
book. This was originally taught in a low skills English class, successfully
helping students see how one character's behavior influences other characters'
reactions. It easily could be adapted to other ability groups.
</P>
<P>Call Stephanie Keitel for more information: 802-229-0321.</P>
