<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Best Lessons</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1>Listening for Emotion</H1>
<H4>Submitted by Tom Walters, Camel's Hump Middle School</H4>
<P>This Music Education lesson is for 5th and/or 6th grade students. 
</P>
<P>The lesson starts out with a general discussion about &#147;active&#148; vs.
 &#147;passive&#148; listening.  I usually use the example &#147;when you&#146;re
doing your homework with the radio on, that&#146;s passive listening. Today, we&#146;ll
practice listening with your whole mind, with no distractions.&#148; I then hand
out the worksheet while explaining the directions.  The students read down the
list of emotions on the right-hand side of the first page.  If there is a word
they don&#146;t understand, I&#146;ll usually ask if anyone else in the class
knows the meaning (there is an element of new vocabulary in this lesson). I try
to add a contextual meaning for the word.  For instance, I&#146;ll say that &#147;mournful&#148;
is usually associated with death or loss.  &#147;Mournful is how you would feel
if you had a pet hamster, and the hamster died.&#148; </P>
<P>We then turn to page two and prepare for listening.  I make a transparency
of the song lyrics, lower the lights and project the lyrics on a screen.  I
insist upon total quiet in the classroom; if anyone talks, I start the music
over again.  The first time I used this lesson, I chose &#147;Tears in Heaven&#148;
as the first listening example.  The song was written by Eric Clapton in
response to the real-life death of his son (most kids know this fact). 
Invariably, when the music starts there is a murmur of recognition.  However,
most children have never truly listened to the song. </P>
<P>As the song plays, the students choose words from the list on side one that
describe how the song makes them feel.  I purposefully placed the words on side
one so that they must hold the word in their mind for a second as they turn the
sheet back and forth.  Also, I chose music with veiled meaning to encourage
critical and abstract thinking.  For example, in &#147;Tears in Heaven&#148; it&#146;s
not clear whether the song is happy or sad.  Mr. Clapton obviously mourns the
death of his son but is also happy as he is sure they&#146;ll meet in heaven. 
These elements of the song always spur lively discussion in the class.  It is in
this discussion phase that students practice using the new vocabulary words and
more importantly, learn language to express their emotions.  Keep in mind that
the lights in the classroom are dimmed at this time creating a rather &#147;safe&#148;
environment.  I saw tears in several students eyes as we listened. </P>
<P>I&#146;ve included lyrics for the second listening selection, &#147;Burlingtown,&#148;
as composed by Todd Thibaud and Jim Wooster of the &#147;Courage Brothers.&#148;
Again, the emotional content of this song can be taken in several ways: the
singer is both happy and sad upon returning to his hometown of Burlington,
Vermont.  The kids in Richmond always get a kick out of hearing &#147;Interstate
89&#148; in a song. 
</P>
<P><B>Resources</B></P>
<P>Photocopied worksheets and pencils, transparencies and overhead projector,
CD player and CD&#146;s. 
</P>
<P><B>Method of assessment </B></P>
<P>The only assessment I give for this lesson is one for behavior; I grade each
class based on their level of involvement and engagement.  Since the goal of the
lesson is to teach children to use emotionally descriptive and appropriate
vocabulary, I feel it would be counter-productive to assign any shade of right
or wrong to a child&#146;s opinion or feelings in this case. 
</P>
<P><B>More information</B></P>
<P>Tom Walters, Camel&#146;s Hump Middle School (802) 434-2188 or home (802)
860-6239. Email: TomWa1@aol.com</P>
<HR>
