<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Professional Exchange</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H1><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Help me articulate my love for teaching</FONT></H1>
<P><B>By Stephanie Keitel, Union-32 High School 
</B></P>
<P>Recently two different conversations collided for me and so I seek a forum
for collegial sharing. Please help me name what we do -- in the manner of
Madeline L'Engel, <I>A Wrinkle in Time,</I> your Namer is the only one who
knows you so well they can truly call you by your real name.   </P>
<P>First, my parents and I were discussing a family friend whose company &quot;rightsized&quot;
him into unemployment. As a middle-aged man, he has had very little luck
regaining paid employment.  He is too &quot;experienced,&quot; too likely to
quit if a more suitable offer comes along. My parents, in all sincerity, said
they thought the solution would be for him to take the few Mickey Mouse
education courses needed for a teacher's license, so that he could fall back on
teaching. After all, there always seem to be vacancies in the schools and he has
nice kids and he'd love all the summer freedom.  </P>
<P>I found myself speechless. People I love, people who love me and who have to
plan their time with me around my summer school obligations, were saying that
the work I have done for over 20 years for countless days, evenings and weekends
is a &quot;fall back&quot; job.
</P>
<P>Yet to be honest, is this perception partially my own doing? How many times
have I replied sheepishly, semi-embarrassed to the question of what I do? While
internally I revel in my school work, externally my reply seems to sound almost
apologetic for not being the CEO of a corporation, or at least president of my
own firm.  </P>
<P>How strange. I put in more hours than anyone I know. I am just as educated.
I balance budgets I can't expand. I have to teach everyone (teachers aren't
allowed to &quot;right size, downsize&quot;), even after there are no more desks
or books left. I am more current in my professional research than anyone besides
my family doctor.  I have turned more family trips into continuing education
experiences than anyone I know. My family has graciously accompanied me to
school games and evening activities, and welcomed many unpredictable  guests
into our home for dinner (15 seventh graders for dinner is not without surprises
and breakage!).  I  am still waiting to meet the &quot;private sector&quot;
employee who spends as great a proportion of income as teachers on continuing
education classes, books, journals and basics such as kleenex and holiday
treats. 
</P>
<P>Then on the second day of school while reading Avi's <I>Nothing But the
Truth</I>, I came upon this: &quot;I suppose after doing anything for twenty-one
years a body does get a little tired... All the same I remain steadfast in my
belief that my life was meant to be the bringing of fine literature to young
minds. Is it wrong to speak of the work as a calling? Well, teaching is almost a
religion to me. I will complain from time to time, but it is my life. The truth
is I like it.  I would be lost without my books, my teaching, my students.&quot;
(page 5)  
</P>
<P>So, fellow teachers, help me articulate my love for teaching. Share some
words that show the fire we feel for our profession, for the depth and sparkle
it brings to our lives. </P>
<HR>
