<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Professional Exchange</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H1><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Burnout &#151; A Prisoner's Story
</FONT></H1>
<P><B>By Janet Van Fleet, on leave from Union Elementary, Montpelier
</B></P>
<P>I'm a really good teacher &#151; for nine years I've been respectful,
engaged, and creative with kids; open and collaborative with parents; and
cheerfully committed to doing more than my share of the work outside my
classroom with colleagues and administrators. But I won't be showing up in the
classroom this year because I'm taking a year's leave of absence. I've got a
major case of burnout.
</P>
<P>By the end of last year I was feeling imprisoned in my classroom. I began to
think, &quot;There's something wrong with this picture: Nobody could imagine
that one mother could take care of 22 children all day every day. Even if you
had 22 children, some of them would be at least 15 years older than the rest and
be helping out. And of course, once they got to be five or six, you'd be sending
them off to school for most of the waking hours of each day! What kind of
parenting could you do under such circumstances? How would you ever get any
quality time with any of your children? The question is, why do we think
teachers should be able to do this?&quot;
</P>
<P>Any manager in the public sector who is responsible for supervising the work
of 22 employees has impressive amenities and support systems: an office where
focused, uninterrupted work can be accomplished, a personnel manager, an
assistant, at least one secretary, a computer with software designed for making
recordkeeping and communication more efficient, and probably lots of other
goodies that I don't even know about. If this supervisor needs to get some
perspective, there's no law against walking around the block and getting a cup
of coffee. An hour's lunch (or an hour for exercise in the middle of the day) is
standard. If you need more, and the day's schedule allows it, you take it; after
all, you'll be working some evenings or Saturdays &#151; it all works out.
</P>
<P>Teachers, by contrast, have no office; they work in the same room as the 22
people they're supervising. They design all the training programs, create or
find the materials, and do the training for all 22 workers. They oversee all of
the daily work, evaluate the employees and let them know where and how their
performance needs to improve (and emphasize all the things that they're doing
well!), and keep daily records on workers' performance all by themselves.
Teachers do all the filing, all the correspondence, and all the quarterly
reports by themselves. AND they break up fights, help the workers keep track of
their personal belongings, consult with employees' families and their own
supervisors about how the training program is going, and try to maintain an
atmosphere of high morale and community in the workplace.
</P>
<P>Well, if mom-at-home and manager/supervisor don't quite work as analogs for
teaching, what does? In my current frame of mind, factory work &#151; in which
you're tied to your place on the assembly line &#151; seems to come closest. If
you need to go the bathroom you can't unless you can get someone to step into
your spot on the line. You get working people's hours (last year all the
teaching staff at my school were required to report daily at 7:30 a.m.; it
didn't matter how many hours you put in on the other end of the day). You can't
leave the plant for lunch (because there isn't time, or because you need to
supervise lunch period). At least factory workers, or people who stock shelves
at Ames, get a coffee break. Alas, not to teachers.
</P>
<P>Our profession is betwixt and between &#151; it doesn't have the personal
freedom, perks, independence and respect the other professions do; nor does it
have the minimal, blanket protections designed for non-salaried workers. Thank
goodness our union is working to address these issues. And thank goodness the
great joys of teaching compensate for the constraints and unrealistic and
demeaning circumstances under which we sometimes work. But until that glorious
day, when, exhausted, frustrated, and desperately needing some time out, I can
walk down the street and buy a cup of coffee, I worry that I'm going to continue
to feel incarcerated in my classroom.
</P>
<HR>
