<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Professional Exchange	</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H1><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Advice from a retired teacher: &quot;Stick to it --
be the best you can be&quot;</FONT></H1>
<P><B>By Alan Blakeman, retired from Montpelier High School</B></P>
<P>I was interested in reading Janet Van Fleet's &quot;Burnout -- A Prisoner's
Story.&quot; I well understand Janet's situation , as I have been there myself.
Also, I have had the opportunity to work with Janet on some local education
issues and know she is a caring professional.</P>
<P>I taught my last class in June 1995, ending a busy and rewarding 37 years in
the profession. I feel that my last year was my most effective as a teacher.
Burnout during that time? Yes! Kudos to Janet for taking the year off to get
refueled. I never did take a year's absence, but did teach at what was
Montpelier's Junior High School for a year.  For a high school teacher, that was
eye-opening and rewarding in its own right. I went back to Montpelier High
School the next year renewed and with a greater understanding of what middle
school people go through.</P>
<P>I am now involved in substitute teller work at the Chittenden Bank, and the
teaching profession has helped me much in my &quot;second career.&quot; I enjoy
banking. One of the neat things is that over this past year, only seven days
have passed where I have NOT met a former student at the bank. I am proud that I
taught and now, I have had a year to reflect. Teaching was worth it, even though
the money and the personal time for family and self can never be made up.</P>
<P>A few things come to mind that I would like to pass on to my fellow
teachers. One of the things that I resented in the profession was the worship of
&quot;reinventing the wheel&quot; and some of the trends that I have seen come
and go. There is a lot to be said for picking up new ideas and trying out new
methods. However, these PhD's from brand-name institutions do not have the
advantage that you and I have: that of working with kids day-in-day-out. Learn
new methods, but do not go against your grain. Through hard experience (I wish I
could redo some of my mistakes!) I have learned that I have to be ME, and that
is not so bad!</P>
<P>I also encourage teachers to do things NOT in the education field in their
spare time, which I know is not easy. By having separate interests, you can get
to your &quot;grind&quot; better. As teachers, we tend to be masochists or
attempt to be superman/woman. In the big picture, some time for yourself will be
most helpful for your students, as well as yourself. Believe me, I have spent
too many 7-day weeks at my teaching, which eventually became counterproductive.</P>
<P>In the classroom, take charge. Kids appreciate discipline. Unorganized chaos
ends up negatively. Kids will respect you and you can guide them into better
learning.</P>
<P>Make yourself available as much as possible to students. Take advantage of
that one student who is seeking help. You can make a difference.</P>
<P>Teaching is all the negatives that Janet noted in her article, and more so
the joys that she described. Stick to it -- be the best you can be -- and GO
WITH YOUR GUT REACTION. When that retirement day comes, hopefully you will also
say: &quot;It has been a great career.&quot; </P>
<HR>
