<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Professional Exchange</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H1><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Teacher bashing keeps me up at night</FONT></H1>
<P><B>By Diane Alberts, French, English and drama teacher at Canaan High
School
</B>
</P>
<P>I didn't sleep well last night. Though I went to bed at 10:00, I wasn't
asleep at 11:45 and I woke up again at 4:10 a.m. 
</P>
<P>Why was I so restless? I had listened to a Republican candidate for governor
of Vermont on Vermont Public Radio's &quot;Switchboard.&quot; Taking cues from
his national mentor, Bob Dole, candidate John Gropper decided to bash teachers
in Vermont's public schools.  
</P>
<P>I called VPR and commented on his remarks about vouchers, public education
funds going to private schools. Mr. Gropper jibed that maybe with vouchers the
public schools would &quot;get off their heels&quot; and do something about the
sad state of education in Vermont. Like his national mentor, Mr. Gropper
described teachers' unions as &quot;terrified&quot; that competition will make
them do their jobs better. I asked him if he would apply the same principle to
the Pentagon: i.e., cut the budget to the point of virtually crippling
operations so they would &quot;get off their heels&quot; and stop buying $7,000
coffee pots and $300 toilet seats. &quot;If everybody scrutinized the schools as
much as they pick on the Pentagon...&quot; he replied. Alas, my line went dead,
but I couldn't forget those words. 
</P>
<P>The American public schools have been under constant assault since the early
days of the Reagan administration, and it has been documented that the Bush
administration would suppress good news about public schools to avoid losing a
favorite whipping boy. I grant you that in 1982 public education was falling far
short of where it should be. Rather than to pitch in and support our public
schools &#151; the backbone of a democracy &#151; politicians have ignored the
spiraling expectations placed on public schools and teachers, parental
indifference, the poor behavior of a large segment of the younger generation,
and the relentless anti-intellectuality rampant in this country which makes a
hero of Jeff Foxworthy's &quot;redneck&quot; while vilifying school educators
and their values. We have spent the last 13 years trying to re-invent the school
and the teacher, as if teachers taught school in a social vacuum. 
</P>
<P>I began to teach in the early eighties. At that time my bachelor's degree in
teaching plus four years experience garnered me roughly $12,000 less per year in
salary &#151; not to mention benefits &#151; than most recent college grads in
any other profession. That gap has narrowed. Thirteen years later I am only $4-8
thousand behind a recent college grad. What progress I've made in being able to
support myself and two children on my teacher's salary, I owe to a teachers'
union. Judging from Mr. Gropper's remarks about how much more cheaply a private
school could educate kids, those unions are just as necessary now as they were
back in the days when teachers were working for $2,000 per year and the women
were forced to quit when they married.  
</P>
<P>How can those private schools operate on so much less money? Check their
teacher salaries and ask yourselves if it's reasonable for the millions of
public school teachers putting in 11-hour days to work for salaries which enable
families to qualify for welfare and food stamps.  
</P>
<P>I do <I>not</I> exaggerate. A single mother who taught with me when I
returned to teaching in 1983 supported three children abandoned by a dead-beat
dad and actually did qualify for food stamps and other low-income programs. She
and I both lived in used trailers and cut every corner we could. Is that what we
want for our teachers?  
</P>
<P>Mr. Gropper is mouthing words sent down to him from the national level, and
I am strongly suspicious about why teachers are being made the &quot;Willy
Horton&quot;s of 1996. Why is it that the improved SAT scores are not in the
public eye? Or the fact that a much broader cross-section of students now take
the SAT from the days when white, prep-school males represented the bulk of the
testing sample? Or the success of American kids, second only to Finland (!) in
reading? I found this statistic in the back pages of the &quot;Sport&quot;
section of <I>The Manchester Union Leader</I>, a paper which routinely backs
the most conservative of Republican candidates.  
</P>
<P>These questions keep nagging at me, sometimes at night when I can't sleep.
Why doesn't it ever get on the front page that today's culturally diverse school
population has a much higher graduation rate than back in those &quot;Good Old
Days&quot; when only white upper-class males (and a few pushy females) were ever
expected to graduate? Where are those sweet, heart-warming stories about all the
good things teachers routinely do for their students which change their lives
for the better? (I could give lots of examples on a personal level, and I know
I'm not the Mother Theresa of education.) And why, why, why does no one ever
question the unfairness of pitting regulation-burdened public schools against
private schools where only a minimum of regulation exists? Does no one care that
these schools can be run by just about anybody with just about any
political-religious agenda?  
</P>
<P>Can it be that the same society which shakes its head in disbelief at
stories of child abuse taking place in unregulated child care centers whose
credentials were never scrutinized can turn around and dump public money into
not just a private school, but any private school the parents choose? This is
supposed to improve our kids and make them competitive with kids on an
international level? Think about it. Under this concept just about anybody can
call himself a teacher, regardless of education and past history. It seems that
what the Doles, Groppers, and Ralph Reeds of the country are saying is that,
despite the regulations placed on schools and teachers, there are slip-ups,
sometimes egregious ones. Therefore, let's start our own schools and we won't
have any of those safeguards and curricular concerns. That's just about as
logical as cutting the funds of an institution that historically is underfunded
so it will work better. 
</P>
<P>I can't help thinking what an inner city school system could do with the
funds for just one B-1 bomber. Maybe we should follow the Republican voucher
concept to its logical conclusion and, indeed, apply it to the Pentagon. That
way those of us who aren't pleased with Pentagon waste and foul-ups can just get
a defense voucher and choose the local militia we think can do a better job.
Imagine that! 
</P>
<HR>
