<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Professional Exchange</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H1><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Rotten apples that spoil the barrel</FONT></H1>
<P><B>By Franci Farnsworth, Parent, Brandon, Vermont
</B>
</P>
<P>I'm a parent, not a public school teacher.   I've read a couple of the
Teacher Exchange essays that were written by people who exemplify what the
profession should be.  </P>
<P>Fortunately my children have had many such teachers and I know that probably
most of the teachers in Vermont have the same professionalism, commitment,
enthusiasm, and caring as the writers of those essays. What concerns me is those
few teachers who don't &#151; and I know that most school systems have a few of
these folks. People who may have been great teachers once but who have &quot;burned
out,&quot; who don't have the energy anymore to adapt and change.  People who
never should have been teachers at all.  People who are in the wrong teaching
situation (a subject they don't love, a school size or environment in which
they're uncomfortable, students to whom they can't relate). People who think of
teaching as a &quot;job&quot; rather than a &quot;profession&quot; (put in your
hours and go home, take courses or go to conferences only because it's required
for re-certification, etc.).   </P>
<P>These teachers are the rotten apples that spoil the barrel.  Parents and
other members of the public will tend judge all teachers by the bad ones they
see.  And those teachers who do not live up to the standards expressed in these
Teacher Exchange essays are not only hurting your cause, they are hurting the
students in their charge. And that's even worse. </P>
<P> I think it is time for the majority, the truly professional teachers, to
figure out a way to rid your profession of the minority, those &quot;teachers&quot;
who are not worthy of the title and whose actions lend credence to the
accusations of the citizens and politicians attacking public education. 
</P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="vtnea10.htm">Professional Exchange Contents</A> |
<A HREF="index.htm">Home</A></P></BODY></HTML>
