<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Green-2</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#80FF00">
<H1><FONT COLOR="#004000">Green Up Vermont &#151; Tradition with a History</FONT>
</H1>
<P><B>By Melinda Vieux</B>
</P>
<P>Over a quarter century ago, the people of Vermont lead the rest of the
country in keeping their natural surroundings clean and beautiful by launching
the largest cleanup operation of its kind in the nation -- Green Up Day. This
fine tradition started in 1969, on a clear spring day, when Robert Babcock, Jr.,
became appalled as he drove to work in Montpelier from his home in Waterbury.
The melting snow revealed miles of unsightly litter along the roadside. He went
directly to Governor Deane C. Davis, who readily sanctioned the idea of a
statewide effort to be supported by the State Highway Department and large
groups of volunteer citizens to clean up the highways of the state. 
</P>
<P>As planning began and citizens around the state heard about the project,
mounting interest indicated they had &quot;a bear by the tail,&quot; as
described by Davis. Rather than act in haste, the date for the first Green Up
Day was set for April 18, 1970. As it turned out, this was just prior to the
first Earth Day.</P>
<P><B>The first Green Up
</B></P>
<P>On that first Green Up Day, over 70,000 volunteers (75% of whom were youth)
came out and cleaned up litter on 95% of the 2,400 miles of state and interstate
highways and on 75% of the 8,300 town roads. The interstate was closed to the
traveling public from 9:00 to noon, with state police guarding every access.
Although 240,000, 30-gallon-capacity bags were distributed, by mid-morning more
were needed. Some 12,000 additional bags were airdropped by the Civil Air Patrol
to key airports throughout the state. Results far exceeded expectations. As the
Congressional Record reports in the words of Senator George Aiken, volunteers
collected virtually every glass bottle, metal can and scrap of paper cast on to
the roadsides by careless and unthinking people. Several hundred thousand cans
and bottles, filling five tractor trailer trucks, were taken away for recycling.
This massive effort helped in passing a returnable bottle law in Vermont. In
all, the collected trash totaled 40,000 cubic yards.
</P>
<P>By 1979, Green Up had been so successful that Governor Snelling decided it
should become a private non-profit organization, separate from state government.
All the living governors at the time were among the original incorporators of
Vermont Green Up, Inc., and governors since have served as honorary presidents.
Today, Vermont Green Up depends on donations to continue its work.
</P>
<P><B>Poster Contest</B>
</P>
<P>A poster design contest for Green Up Day -- sponsored by Vermont-NEA since
1994 -- offers students of all ages throughout the state a chance to picture the
message each year. The contest, with entries due late January, is open to all
students and carries a cash award for the design winner and winners in each
grade category. This activity connects students with the community, as well as
raising sensitivity to the importance of caring for Vermont's lovely landscape
environment.
</P>
<P>Green Up Vermont is the Vermont community taking care of its home by
cleaning up road and stream side debris and greening up by planting trees and
flowers and sprucing up public sites. In 1996, an estimated 20,000 Vermonters
kept the green up spirit soaring.  Green Up is more than an activity for a day.
It is an attitude for a lifetime -- an attitude toward our environment and
working together to keep Vermont a clean, safe and beautiful place to live,
visit and enjoy. It culminates on Green Up Day, the first Saturday each May, and
includes Green Up spirited actions throughout the year.</P>
<P>You can protect Vermont's lovely landscape -- be a Vermont Green Up
volunteer. Green Up needs town and county chair people, school organizers,
volunteer workers of all ages, contributions for funding the work, and the
stories about what happens in your community. Please contact Green Up Vermont,
802-229-5686.
</P>
<P><FONT SIZE="-2"><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>Melinda Vieux is Executive
Director of Green Up Vermont.
</I></FONT></B></FONT></P>
<HR>
