<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Schools That Work - Environment</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="sw-3.htm"><I>Schools That Work</I> Contents</A> |
<A HREF="index.htm">Home</A></P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#800000">I - ENVIRONMENT OF LEARNING  </FONT></H2>
<P><B>Key #1  Strengthen student behavior standards  
</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion 
</B></P>
<P>Educators are finding it increasingly difficult to maintain the order and
discipline necessary for them to teach and for students to learn. Student
language, clothing, interpersonal behavior and respect for property should
reflect a level of decorum that promotes learning. Our schools reflect wider
social currents: to the extent there is an erosion of civility in the community,
it will appear in our classrooms. In fact, expectations regarding acceptable
student conduct have declined in many schools.  </P>
<P>All educators and students know that disruptive behavior by just one student
can hurt the learning process for everyone present in a classroom. This is often
the case when a student, whether or not identified as having a behavioral
disorder, disrupts class.   </P>
<P>Our schools have the authority to balance the needs of students with
behavioral disorders against those of other students. Too often, those with such
authority either don't use it or are not sufficiently trained in how to use it.
As a result, some disruptive behavior continues, to the detriment of both the
misbehaving student and other students in the classroom.  </P>
<P><B> Recommendations  </B></P>
<P>a.  Each school district should establish and enforce a policy for student
decorum which: </P>
<OL>
<LI> promotes a safe, orderly, and civil school environment where learning can
take place;  </LI>
<LI>establishes plain expectations for students regarding behavior, language,
clothing, and treatment of property; and   </LI>
<LI>places clear responsibilities on all members of the school community &#151;
educators, administrators, school board members, and parents, as well as
students.</LI></OL>
<P>  b.  The provisions of such a policy relating to members of each group
should address: </P>
<OL>
<LI> their role in developing, enforcing, and/or complying with the decorum
policy; </LI>
<LI>the behavior expected of them; </LI>
<LI>their responsibility to model and promote high quality student behavior;
and </LI>
<LI>their responsibility to hold students and others accountable for high
standards of behavior.  </LI></OL>
<P>c.  Policy provisions for students should balance the principles of
individual responsibility and the good of the community with the rights of
individuals.  </P>
<P><B>Key #2  Enforce classroom attendance expectations</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion  </B></P>
<P>Students are absent from class or school too often, and too often the
absences are not warranted:  </P>
<P>The mission of public schools is educational and revolves around the
curriculum. There are occasions when a student is absent from class or school
for reasons unrelated to health, family emergencies, or other legitimate
purposes.   </P>
<P>There are other occasions when a student is absent from class for school
activities that are non-academic. Most extracurricular programs and events well
serve and complement the mission of the schools. Some activities do not: they
should be weighed carefully against the importance of classroom instruction. 
</P>
<P>Finally, our schools are not equipped and must not be expected to be the
primary providers of social services. Teachers are trained to teach, not to be
social workers. At a time when responsibility for social services is
increasingly pushed onto our schools, it is all the more important that we
protect the educational program from the distractions and disruptions that arise
when students' personal and family problems seize center stage.   </P>
<P><B>Recommendations </B>  </P>
<P>a.  Each school district should adopt and enforce a class and school
attendance policy which: </P>
<OL>
<LI>does not excuse students from attending classes for matters, apart from an
emergency or illness,  not directly linked to their program of curricular and
extracurricular activities and graduation requirements;   </LI>
<LI>distinguishes social from educational services and assures that its social
services enhance its educational services; 
</LI>
<LI>requires school personnel, working with students on matters unrelated to
their curricular and extracurricular program, to schedule time with them in a
way which avoids intruding into their classroom obligations;  </LI>
<LI>restricts the circumstances under which teachers may seek to excuse
students from the classes of other teachers; and   </LI>
<LI>establishes specific consequences for students  whose unexcused absences
from class exceed a specific number.   </LI></OL>
<P><B>Key #3  Improve the use of instructional time</B>   </P>
<P><B>Discussion</B>  </P>
<P>The variety and number of interruptions during presently available
instructional time increasingly damage the ability of teachers to teach. More
and more student extracurricular activities have intruded into instructional
time, and more and more mandated meetings and other additional responsibilities
have been thrust onto teachers and administrators.  </P>
<P>Teachers generally have inadequate time in which to prepare lessons and
attend to professional development needs. In addition, they spend countless
hours at committee meetings, at staff meetings, meeting with students and
parents, taking courses of their own, complying with government mandates, and
preparing for their daily classes.  </P>
<P>The expanded activities of students and staff have intruded into the
essential academic function of our schools. The amount of time in a school year
for all functions has increased in only a minority of school districts. More
academic and professional development time is needed without eroding the more
recent additional responsibilities placed on students and staff alike. As a
result, our schools need to make better use of instructional time and, perhaps,
to make more time for schooling available.  </P>
<P>Finally, virtually all reputable research concludes that limiting class size
enables teachers to provide more personal attention to individual students and
that individual attention contributes to greater learning.   </P>
<P><B>Recommendations   </B></P>
<P>a.  Each school district should adopt a policy to optimize the teaching time
in the present school day by scheduling those activities not related to teaching
and learning to occur after school hours.   </P>
<P>b.  Each school district, in cooperation with its local teachers
association, should study the actual amount of time its teachers are involved in
non-instructional activities. This study should examine:  </P>
<OL>
<LI>the extent to which those activities, such as planning lessons, are
directly or indirectly related to instruction; </LI>
<LI>the extent to which they occur during or before and after regular school
hours (whether or not paid); </LI>
<LI>the appropriateness of that use of time; and  </LI>
<LI>ways to address any uncovered imbalance.  </LI></OL>
<P>c.  Each school district, in cooperation with its local teachers
association, should develop a formal plan to improve the use of existing school
time for teaching. Once that improvement has occurred, they should determine
together if the amount of available instructional time is insufficient and, if
so, how to increase it and how to afford any increase.  </P>
<P>d.  Each school district should  establish class size policies which assure
that teachers can provide an appropriate amount of individual attention to all
students.  </P>
<P><B>Key #4  Assure all students enter school each day ready to learn    
</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion  </B></P>
<P>Parents are the first and most important life-long teachers of their
children. Some parents need help to make sure that their children are socially,
intellectually, and physically ready to begin schooling or are ready for school
from day to day. Communities have an obligation to their children to help
parents fulfill the basic components of child-rearing. In our society, that
includes readying their children for school. At the same time, all adults should
exhibit for children respect for learning and their schools.  </P>
<P>The most important issue generally unspoken in discussions of finance reform
and education quality is the degree of poverty affecting our students. It
affects, of course, those who themselves are poor. It also affects the fabric
and culture of our schools, whether reflected in the increased provision of
social services within our school buildings or the impaired emotional and
physical ability of students to focus on learning and study. While we may not be
able to have an effect directly on how policy makers at the State and federal
levels act, we can state for them what we know to be true:  </P>
<OL>
<LI>Children who are developmentally ready for formal schooling are more
attentive students than children who are not, and </LI>
<LI>Children who are well-rested, appropriately clothed, and adequately
nourished are more attentive students than children who are not.</LI></OL>
<P><B>Recommendations   </B></P>
<P>a.  Each community should assist its schools by offering  parent education,
information, and training programs for parents needing assistance meeting the
basic needs of their children so that, when they arrive at school, they are
socially, intellectually, and physically prepared. </P>
<P>b.  All parents should demonstrate respect for their children's schooling by
discussing with them school events on a daily basis, becoming involved through
parent conferences, initiating contact with teachers about their children, and
attending and participating in school activities, including school board
meetings.  </P>
<P>c.  In addition to private community and religious agencies such as Girl and
Boy Scouts, 4-H, and churches, such programs as Healthy Babies, Head Start,
Essential Early Education, Child Nutrition Programs, and pre-school and
after-school programs have all contributed to the capacity of our children to be
attentive students. They should be the focus of increased and sustained societal
and financial support.  
</P>
<HR>
