<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Schools That Work - Educators</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="sw-3.htm"><I>Schools That Work</I> Contents</A> |
<A HREF="index.htm">Home</A></P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#800000">II - EDUCATORS  </FONT></H2>
<P><B>Key #1  Raise the professional qualifications required to obtain a
teaching license  
</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion 
</B></P>
<P>One important way to assure teacher competence is to establish clear and
substantial entry level professional qualifications. To enter the teaching
profession, whether directly from college or from another profession,
individuals logically should be expected to possess sufficiently high levels of
expertise in their content area as well as in the areas of pedagogy and child
development and psychology. 
</P>
<P>While teachers themselves typically bear the brunt of criticism for &quot;bad
apples&quot; in the classrooms, they often are not given a role either in
determining how teachers are prepared for the content and pedagogical demands of
their profession or in teacher hiring and evaluation. 
</P>
<P>We sometimes confront an attitude that &quot;anyone can teach.&quot; We do
not believe just anyone can teach. Most would scoff at an experienced paralegal
who presumes competence to manage litigation. So, too, with the seasoned EMT who
suggests filling in for a physician for a year or two. Yet, we regularly listen
straight-faced to suggestions that those skilled in &quot;the private sector&quot;
ought to be afforded an easy transition from the board room to the classroom.
The quality of instruction we seek cannot be attained by lowering licensing
requirements.  
</P>
<P><B>Recommendations </B> 
</P>
<P>a.  The State Board of Education should raise teacher licensing standards to
assure that individuals wishing to enter the teaching profession have the
following qualifications: 
</P>
<OL>
<LI>a bachelor of arts or science degree from an accredited college or
university, which, for secondary teachers, shall be in a field of concentration
other than education; 
</LI>
<LI>a grade point average of no less than 3.0 or other indication of superior
undergraduate academic performance; 
</LI>
<LI>undergraduate or graduate training in pedagogy and child development and
psychology; 
</LI>
<LI>successful completion of a student teaching or internship experience at
least one school year in duration; and  
</LI>
<LI>a passing score, established by the Board, on the National Teacher
Examination. 
</LI></OL>
<P>The Department of Education should assure that the National Teacher
Examination is administered at  convenient times and places.  
</P>
<P><B>Key #2  Establish a two-year probationary period for newly licensed
teachers  
</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion 
</B></P>
<P>Persons new to a profession generally do not know if they are cut out for a
career in that profession until they have spent a period of time testing their
career choice. The members of most professions in Vermont serve a probationary
period before their license becomes permanent, and teachers in most other states
serve a probationary period as well. Vermont should provide its permanent
teaching certificate to those persons who successfully demonstrate through an
initial period of employment that they are well-suited for a career in teaching.
 
</P>
<P>We expect any person new to a profession to require guidance and oversight
for an initial period. Vermont should assure that individuals new to teaching
receive professional attention to develop their skills. 
</P>
<P>Whether an experienced teacher should serve a probationary period with a new
employer has been and should remain a matter negotiated by local school
districts with their local teachers association.       </P>
<P><B>Recommendations 
</B></P>
<P>a.  The Legislature should establish for newly licensed teachers a two-year
period of probation with the following characteristics: 
</P>
<OL>
<LI>Successful completion is affirmed by the local superintendent (or school
board, if there is no superintendent); 
</LI>
<LI>A qualified individual will provide formal evaluations to the teacher no
fewer than four times;  
</LI>
<LI>An employing school district which has complied with its responsibilities
to provide the teacher formal evaluations and any required notice may, without
being required to provide a statutory hearing, decide for performance reasons
not to renew the teacher's contract; and 
</LI>
<LI>A teacher who, for alleged performance reasons,  does not successfully
complete an initial two-year period of employment, may extend probation for one
additional two-year period, during which he or she is subject again to the
requirements of a teacher with an initial probationary license.  
</LI></OL>
<P><B>Key #3  Conduct frequent performance evaluations of education personnel
throughout their careers   
</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion 
</B></P>
<P>Useful evaluation of education personnel contributes to high caliber
performance. A school's evaluation system should reflect its education goals,
management style, general philosophy of instruction, and the values of its
community.  
</P>
<P>Rarely are teachers and other school personnel evaluated regularly or well
enough. Most evaluation systems are not developed with sufficient staff
involvement. It is unusual as well for evaluators, who may be well-versed in
theories of child development and learning, to have adequate knowledge of the
subjects or specialty areas taught by the teachers they evaluate. Almost nowhere
are the training, time, and resources necessary to develop and implement a good
evaluation system recognized.      
</P>
<P><B>Recommendations 
</B></P>
<P>a.  By February 15, 1997, Vermont-NEA should call upon the Vermont School
Boards Association, the Vermont Superintendents Association, the Vermont
Principals Association, and the Vermont Parent-Teacher Association to appoint a
delegation to work jointly with Vermont-NEA in conducting a study, without
unneeded legislation, regarding: 
</P>
<OL>
<LI>the training, time, and resources needed to conduct high quality
evaluations of administrators, teachers, and support staff;  
</LI>
<LI>aspects of school administration which might be reduced to free the time of
supervisory personnel to conduct high quality evaluations; and 
</LI>
<LI>various methods and processes for use by school districts in conducting
personnel evaluations. </LI></OL>
<P>Those engaged in this study should consult with, among others, persons from
the private sector who have expertise in human resources generally and personnel
evaluation specifically. They should present their joint findings and
recommendations to their governing bodies, local school districts, the
Department of Education and the General Assembly, as appropriate.    
</P>
<P><B>Key #4  Provide educators career-long professional development
emphasizing subject matter knowledge and student learning  
</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion 
</B></P>
<P>An educator's professional development is primarily the educator's own
responsibility. In order to attain a high level of proficiency early in their
careers, all teachers should engage in sufficient professional development to
attain an advanced degree (or equivalent) within a reasonable period of time.
Teachers' daily work schedules should be arranged so that more professional
interaction is possible.   
</P>
<P>A good professional development program should have the following
characteristics: 
</P>
<OL>
<LI>the primary objective is improved student learning; its structure and
substance survive administrative turnover; 
</LI>
<LI>its substance flows from the school district's curriculum and long-term
plan for the education of its community's children;
</LI>
<LI>it focuses on content and curricular needs as well as on methodology;  
</LI>
<LI>it is directed by a standing committee of professional educators who are
encouraged to subject it to open and critical analysis;  
</LI>
<LI>it has access to sufficient resources; and</LI>
<LI>it addresses the needs of support staff as well as teachers. 
</LI></OL>
<P>The usual in-service programs commonly in place in our schools do not meet
these standards.    
</P>
<P><B>Recommendations  
</B></P>
<P>a.  All teachers should acquire a masters degree, or its equivalent in
additional course work,* within 7 years of receiving a permanent license. For
this purpose, each school district should enhance its efforts to make
appropriate course work and necessary payment for it accessible to its own
staff.     
</P>
<P>b.  Each school district should arrange the schedules of its teachers to
enable them to interact during the course of the school day, through such
mechanisms as shared preparation periods.    
</P>
<P>c.  In all school districts, local professional development committees
should develop and oversee professional development programs, which should: 
</P>
<OL>
<LI>extend over 5-year periods;
</LI>
<LI>reflect the priorities and curriculum developed by the school district; 
</LI>
<LI>encourage ongoing and open critical analysis of it by district staff; and 
</LI>
<LI>provide incentives to teachers and support staff to engage in those
professional development activities which assist the district in the attainment
of its educational goals.
</LI></OL>
<P><FONT SIZE="-1">*   Except where industry standards apply.  
</FONT></P>
<HR>
