<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Schools That Work - Academics</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="sw-3.htm"><I>Schools That Work</I> Contents</A> |
<A HREF="index.htm">Home</A></P>
<H2><FONT COLOR="#800000">III - ACADEMIC PROGRAMS AND STANDARDS</FONT></H2>
<P><B>Key #1  Elevate the importance of academic content  
</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion 
</B></P>
<P>The curriculum of each public school should emphasize content and skills
that have shaped or defined our culture, are essential to the well-being of our
communities, and are fundamental to the development of thoughtful, principled
and hardworking citizens. Parents and taxpayers should have regular access to
the content and goals of the curriculum. 
</P>
<P>The method of learning makes academic content accessible. The best teaching
and the best learning occur where a proper balance is struck between the
substance of lessons and the method through which that substance is learned. A
teacher's primary role should balance imparting knowledge and facilitating
learning.   
</P>
<P>Self-esteem is a necessary ingredient in enhancing student academic and
intellectual growth. Self-esteem, however, is not an end in itself but rather a
by-product of mastery of intellectual and social challenges.     
</P>
<P><B>Recommendations 
</B></P>
<P>a.  Each school district should routinely schedule programs for parents
describing its curriculum and prepare for public distribution the contents and
planned schedule it uses in presenting that curriculum to its students. 
</P>
<P>b.  Each school district should publicly examine the balance in its
curriculum between method and content. To the extent that it determines there is
too great a focus on method, it should take steps to restore academic content to
its proper standing. 
</P>
<P>c.  Each school district should assess the extent, if any, to which
otherwise well-founded concern for the self-esteem of our students has
supplanted concern for their academic attainments. To the extent it has, the
school district should take steps to re-establish the primacy of academic
learning in ways which foster the long-term self-esteem provided by attainment
and knowledge.  
</P>
<P><B>Key #2  Provide rigorous academic program choices   
</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion 
</B></P>
<P>Students entering Vermont's public schools are endowed with different
intellects, abilities, interests, and family and other support. Not all students
can master &#151; nor should they be expected to master &#151; the same kinds or
amounts of knowledge. Yet, school boards are expected to respond to the growing
number of parents and students in Vermont demanding a greater number of
instructional programs and academic choices within the curriculum:</P>
<OL>
<LI>Students have different learning styles. Schools are expected to and should
attempt to accommodate legitimate interest in different teaching approaches.
</LI>
<LI>Students have different learning abilities. Schools are expected to and
should attempt to provide courses that impose differing demands on students to
reflect this fact. 
</LI></OL>
<P>It is extremely difficult, however, for a school district to meet the widely
disparate expectations of all members of its community. Nevertheless, while the
public must temper the demands it would place on schools with a recognition of
the limit of both money and other resources, our schools cannot turn deaf ears
to whole constituencies. They must be more open to providing several alternative
curricular paths of equal rigor. The availability of resources to accomplish
even this does vary across school districts and is a particular problem in small
schools in low wealth districts.  
</P>
<P><B>Recommendations  
</B></P>
<P>a.  Each school district should establish, for secondary education, grades 7
- 12, multiple programs of study within each grade that: 
</P>
<OL>
<LI>enforce clear academic and behavioral standards students must meet to enter
a program and performance objectives for students to remain in it; 
</LI>
<LI>provide parents and students information to help them understand the
varying skills, intellectual development, and workload each course requires;
</LI>
<LI>allow students with a demonstrated high commitment to learning and a record
of high achievement to be taught more demanding subject matter at an accelerated
pace; 
</LI>
<LI>provide a rigorous and appropriate academic program for all students;
</LI>
<LI>assure that all student work, regardless of  the depth taught, demonstrates
high academic standards regarding content and skill development;
</LI>
<LI>provide ongoing and comprehensive remediation to any child who needs it,
especially in the areas of literacy and math computation; and
</LI>
<LI>where there is clear community interest, offer distinct instructional
programs reflecting differing approaches to education and different learning
styles.</LI></OL>
<P> b.  Each school district should investigate ways to join with other public
school districts to allow a wider choice of educational options. 
</P>
<P><B>Key #3  Uphold grade advancement and graduation requirements   
</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion 
</B></P>
<P>The traditional graded approach to schooling, to some analysts, is outdated
and can impede high level learning. The graded system, however, is the one in
which educators function. Teachers face incredible pressures, for a variety of
reasons, to allow students to advance from one grade to the next whether they
have mastered the curriculum or not.  
</P>
<P>Despite inadequate resources, public school educators have an unparalleled
commitment to retaining students who, in earlier times or in other countries,
would have dropped out of or been dropped from school programs. That commitment
to universal retention makes it appear to some observers that programs and
standards are somehow watered down.  
</P>
<P>Public schools, nevertheless, should permit students to advance from one
grade to the next, or to graduate, only if they master the skills and content
required by their school district's curriculum. It is the mission of the public
school system to provide the resources needed to make that possible.  
</P>
<P>If students can learn to read, for example, they should be expected to, and
we must not permit them, after a certain point, to pass through grade after
grade unless they do learn to read. To the extent that we are not providing a
sufficient range and depth of services to achieve this basic objective, we must
do so.    
</P>
<P><B>Recommendations 
</B></P>
<P>a.  <B>Assessment.</B> Each school district should provide to all students
comprehensive assessments, including reliable standardized tests, at regular
intervals to:</P>
<OL>
<LI>measure their academic achievement;
</LI>
<LI>identify any need for remediation; and
</LI>
<LI>determine their eligibility for grade advancement and graduation.
</LI></OL>
<P> b. <B><B> Elementary school programs. </B></B>Each school district should
establish, as a condition of successful completion of 4th grade, that each
student not diagnosed with a disability which inhibits the capacity to learn to
read must be able to read at no lower than a 4th grade reading level. Each
school district should add services needed for this end and establish comparable
performance requirements in other curricular areas for all grade levels.    
</P>
<P>c.  <B>Secondary school programs.</B> All middle and secondary school
programs should have in place rigorous academic programs through which their
students advance toward graduation as a result of their academic performance.
Secondary school programs should be characterized by:
</P>
<OL>
<LI>course offerings with uniformly high academic standards;
</LI>
<LI>emphasis on reading, writing, math, history, science, and other components
of the State minimum course of study; and
</LI>
<LI>clear standards for any student's admission and retention.
</LI></OL>
<P><B>Key #4  Provide regular planning and guidance for all students  
</B></P>
<P><B>Discussion 
</B></P>
<P>We believe students' performance improves when they understand their role
and the expectations being placed upon them.  
</P>
<P>In elementary schools, it is important that all students and their parents
have a clear understanding of the behavioral and performance expectations
teachers and their schools have for their students. 
</P>
<P>It is also important for the curricula of elementary schools to be
coordinated with their middle and high schools. 
</P>
<P>In secondary schools, it is important for students to have a clear
understanding, not just of their school's expectations, but also of the
fundamental role secondary education has on their future.  
</P>
<P><B>Recommendations  
</B></P>
<P>a.  Within the first several weeks of each school year, all parents of
primary school students should attend parent conferences for the purpose of
obtaining a clear understanding of the expectations classroom and other teachers
have for their children, with respect to both behavior and academic performance.

</P>
<P>b.  All school boards should establish as an objective the integration of
their curricula with that of their designated high school, so as to assure their
school children are prepared for the substance as well as increased rigor
associated with secondary school. 
</P>
<P>c.  Each school district should assure that, beginning in the 7th grade, all
students annually are provided academic and career planning guidance which
involves them and their parents and which is designed: 
</P>
<OL>
<LI>to ensure that students and their parents are aware of educational
opportunities, programs and graduation requirements;
</LI>
<LI>to assist students and their parents in monitoring and planning academic
development and social growth in a consistent and comprehensive fashion from the
7th through the 12th grade; and
</LI>
<LI>to support students and their parents in making career planning and
post-secondary decisions.
</LI></OL>
<HR>
