<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Reading List - Summer 1994</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFF80">
<H2><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Recommended  Summer Reading  for Kids, 1994  
</FONT></H2>
<P>This reading list for  the summer of 1994  was compiled by  Vermont school
librarians,  members of the  Vermont Educational  Media Association.  VEMA is an
affiliate of the  Vermont-National  Education Association. </P>
<P><B>1994 Newbery Award </B></P>
<P>Lois Lowry, <B>THE GIVER</B>. Houghton. </P>
<P><B>1994 Caldecott Award</B> </P>
<P>Allen Say, <B>GRANDFATHER'S JOURNEY</B>. Houghton.   </P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Recommended Titles for Grades K-5  - Compiled by
Debbie Chamberlin, Ferrisburg and Addison Central Schools </FONT></B></P>
<UL>
<LI>Blume, Judy. <B>THE PAIN AND THE GREAT ONE</B>. Bradbury. A story of
sibling rivalry, told with humor from each child's point of view.
</LI>
<LI>Byars, Betsy. <B>THE MOON AND I</B>. Simon and Schuster.  While describing
her humorous adventures with a black snake, Byars recalls her childhood and
describes her own writing process and techniques for authorship. </LI>
<LI>Dahl, Roald.
<B>THE BFG. FSG</B>.  After the big friendly giant kidnaps Sophie from her bed
in the orphanage, the two of them conspire to end the loathsome activities of
nine other giants. Quentin Blake's drawings humorously enhance the telling of
this tale. </LI>
<LI>Dobson, Clive. <B>FRED'S TV</B>. Firefly.  When Fred's television set
blows up after being left out in the rain, the empty cabinet becomes a handy
bird-feeding station and shelter. </LI>
<LI>Hoban, Russell.  <B>A BARGAIN FOR FRANCES</B>. Harper.  Frances and her
sometime best friend Thelma find a way to bargain for what they really want in
this humorous exploration of true childhood situations. </LI>
<LI>Kline, Suzy. <B>HERBIE JONES</B>. Putnam.  Herbie's promotion to a higher
reading group causes a temporary rift with best friend Raymond. </LI>
<LI>Lehan, Daniel. <B>WIPE YOUR FEET</B>. Dutton.  Nancy finds footprints
everywhere in her house -- on the floor, the bath mat and even the walls. She
can't figure out where they came from. </LI>
<LI>Lewison, Wendy Cheyette. <B>GOING TO SLEEP ON THE FARM</B>.  Dial.  A
father explains to his young son how each animal goes to sleep on the farm. The
comfortable rhyming text has a soothing effect. </LI>
<LI>Mazer, Anne. <B>THE SALAMANDER ROOM</B>. Knopf.  A young boy finds a
salamander and thinks of many things he can do to make a perfect home for it.
</LI>
<LI>	Meddaugh, Susan. <B>MARTHA SPEAKS</B>.  Houghton.  When Martha the dog
learns to speak after eating alphabet soup, the family can't stop her from
saying too much. </LI>
<LI>Peck, Robert Newton. <B>SOUP</B>.  Knopf.  The movies cost 10 cents and
Burlington, Vermont was the biggest place in the whole world. The adventures of
Soup and Rob are told with humor and directness. </LI>
<LI>Prelutsky, Jack. <B>FOR LAUGHING OUT LOUD: POEMS TO TICKLE YOUR FUNNY BONE</B>.
 Knopf.  A collection of humorous poems by various authors about such creatures
as the Ogglewop, the Gooloo, and the Dinosore. </LI>
<LI>	Rylant, Cynthia. <B>HENRY AND MUDGE AND THE HAPPY CAT</B>.  Bradbury. 
Henry's family takes in a strange looking stray cat who develops a loving
relationship with Henry's big dog Mudge. </LI>
<LI>Sis, Peter. <B>BEACH BALL</B>. Greenwillow.  While at the beach, Mary and
her mother explore letter and number concepts. The detailed illustrations will
appeal to Waldo fans. </LI>
<LI>Van Allsburg, Chris. <B>JUMANJI</B>.  Houghton.  Two bored and restless
children find more excitement than they bargained for in a mysterious jungle
adventure board game.  </LI></UL>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Recommended Titles for Grades 5-8 - Compiled by
Pamm Shelton, Shelburne Middle School</FONT></B>  </P>
<UL>
<LI>Armstrong, Jennifer.  <B>STEAL AWAY</B>. Orchard. In 1855, two
thirteen-year-old girls, one white and one black, run away from a southern farm
and make the difficult journey north to freedom. They live to recount their
story 41 years later to two similar young girls. </LI>
<LI>Avi. <B>NOTHING BUT THE TRUTH</B>. Orchard. A ninth grader's suspension
for singing &quot;The Star Spangled Banner&quot; during homeroom becomes a
national news story. </LI>
<LI>Banks, Lynn Reid. <B>MYST ERY OF THE CUPBOARD</B>. Morrow. After his
family moves to the country to a house recently inherited by his mother, Omri
finds many secrets revealed when he discovers the link between the house and the
magic cupboard. A sequel to the Indian in the Cupboard.
</LI>
<LI>Byars, Betsy.  <B>WANTED...MUD BLOSSOM</B>. Delacorte. Junior Blossom is
convinced his dog Mud is responsible for the disappearance of the school hamster
Junior was taking care of for the weekend. Junior is determined that the dog
should be tried for his &quot;crime.&quot; </LI>
<LI>Coville, Bruce. <B>JEREMY THATCHER, DRAGON HATCHER</B>. HBJ. Small for his
age but artistically talented, twelve-year-old Jeremy unknowingly buys a
dragon's egg and his whole life changes.
</LI>
<LI>Coville, Bruce. <B>JENNIFER MURDLEY'S TOAD</B>.  HBJ. When an ordinary-
looking fifth grader purchases a talking toad, she embarks on a series of
extraordinary adventures. </LI>
<LI>Hahn, Mary Downing. <B>STEPPING ON THE CRACKS</B>. Clarion. In 1944, while
her brother is overseas fighting in World War II, eleven-year-old Margaret gets
a new view of the school bully when she helps him hide his older brother, an
army deserter. </LI>
<LI>Hesse, Karen. <B>LETTERS FROM RIFKA</B>. Holt. In letters to her cousin, a
young Jewish girl chronicles her family's flight from Russia in 1919. </LI>
<LI>Jacques, Brian. <B>REDWALL</B>. Philomel. When the peaceful life of
ancient Redwall Abbey is shattered by the arrival of an evil rat and his
villainous hordes, Matthias, a young mouse, determines to find the legendary
sword of Martin the Warrior, which he is convinced will help destroy the enemy.
</LI>
<LI>James, J. Alison. <B>RUNA</B>. Atheneum.  A series of accidents and a
discovery in a medieval church suddenly change Runa's summer on a Swedish island
as she finds her life caught up in the rites of her Viking ancestors. </LI>
<LI>Lowry, Lois. <B>ALL ABOUT SAM</B> and <B>ATTABOY SAM</B>. Houghton. The
adventures of Sam, Anastasia Krupnik's younger brother, from his first day as a
newborn through his mischievous early years. </LI>
<LI>Lowry, Lois. <B>THE GIVER</B>. Houghton.  Given his lifetime assignment at
the Ceremony of Twelve, Jonas becomes the receiver of memories shared by only
one other in his community, and discovers the terrible truth about the society
in which he lives. </LI>
<LI>Naylor, Phyllis Reynolds. <B>SHILOH</B>. Atheneum. When he finds a lost
beagle in the hills behind his West Virginia home, Marty tries to hide it from
his family and the dog's real owner, who has mistreated the dog.
</LI>
<LI>Paterson, Katherine. <B>LYDDIE</B>. Lodestar. Impoverished Vermont farm
girl Lyddie Worthen is determined to gain her independence by becoming a factory
worker in Lowell, Massachusetts in the 1840s. </LI>
<LI>Spinelli, Jerry. <B>MANIAC MAGEE</B>. Little, Brown. After his parents
die, Jeffrey Lionel Magee's life becomes legendary as he accomplishes athletic
and other feats which awe his contemporaries.
</LI>
<LI>Wallace, Bill. <B>BUFFALO GAL</B>. Holiday. Fifteen-year-old Amanda's
refined life in early 20th century San Francisco is disrupted when she
grudgingly accompanies her mother to the Oklahoma Territory on a crusade to save
the buffalo.  </LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Recommended Titles for Grades 9-12 - Compiled by
Dan Greene, U-32 High School </FONT></B> </P>
<UL>
<LI>Arnett, Peter. <B>LIVE FROM THE BATTLEFIELD: FROM VIETNAM TO BAGDAD</B>.
Simon and Schuster.  As a youth in New Zealand, Arnett knew that journalism
would be his ticket to the world.  He has helped shape our knowledge of history
through his reporting from Bangkok, Laos, Thailand, and beyond.  This is an
exciting first-hand account of history in the making. </LI>
<LI>Ashe, Arthur. <B>DAYS OF GRACE: A MEMOIR</B>.  Knopf.  In this remarkable
memoir, Ashe takes us on a journey from his childhood in Richmond, Virginia,
through the segregated south and into the white world of tennis.  His story
continues as he learns he has contracted AIDS (in the aftermath of an
operation), and is forced to go public with details about his health. </LI>
<LI>Bosse, Malcolm.<B> DEEP DREAM OF THE RAIN FOREST</B>.  Farrar, Straus &amp;
Giroux.  While on an expedition with his uncle in the jungles of Borneo in 1920,
fifteen-year-old Harry Windsor is captured by a young Iban tribesman who
believes that Harry has a special power that will help the tribesman and his
companion - an outcast Iban girl - on their dream quest.
</LI>
<LI>Coyle, Daniel. <B>HARDBALL: A SEASON IN THE PROJECTS</B>. Putnam. 
HARDBALL is the powerful story of a team's struggle against enormous odds.  From
an inner city Chicago housing project, the Kikuyus have a triumphant season and
show us both the troubling image of the way things are and a hopeful glimpse of
the way things might be. </LI>
<LI>Garcia Marquez, Gabriel. <B>THE GENERAL IN HIS LABYRINTH</B>. Knopf.  This
is the story of the turbulent life of Simon Bolivar -- a liberator and dreamer
-- told in magical narrative. </LI>
<LI>Grisham, John. <B>THE FIRM</B>. Doubleday.  A roller coaster ride of a
story. A brilliant fresh-out-of-law-school lawyer is recruited by a firm that
everyone wants to join, but no one ever leaves...alive.  Great trash. </LI>
<LI>Ishiguro, Kazuo. <B>THE REMAINS OF THE DAY</B>. Vintage.  The story of a
life dedicated to civility and manners, of love repressed and missed
opportunities. </LI>
<LI>Kingsolver, Barbara. <B>PIGS IN HEAVEN</B>. HarperCollins.  A deeply felt
novel of love despite the risks; of tearing apart and coming together. 
Six-year-old Turtle Greer and her mother travel the roads from rural Kentucky
and the urban southwest to Heaven, Oklahoma and the Cherokee nation. </LI>
<LI>Laird, Elizabeth.<B> KISS THE DUST</B>. Dutton.  Her father's involvement
with the Kurdish resistance movement in Iraq forces thirteen-year-old Tara to
flee with her family over the border into Iran, where they face an unknown
future.
</LI>
<LI>MacLean, Norman. <B>YOUNG MEN AND FIRE</B>. University of Chicago Press.
On August 5, 1949, a crew of fifteen of the US Forest Service's elite airborne
firefighters stepped into the sky above a remote forest fire in the Montana
wilderness.  Less than an hour later all but three were dead or mortally burned.
 Through thorough detective work, Norman MacLean has brilliantly put back
together the scattered pieces of this tragedy. </LI>
<LI>Meyer, Nicholas. <B>THE CANARY TRAINER; FROM THE MEMOIRS OF JOHN H. WATSON
M.D.</B> as edited by Nicholas Meyer. Norton.  In this exciting sequel to <B>The
Seven Percent Solution</B>, Sherlock Holmes pits wits against a musical maniac.
Alone in a strange and wonderful city, Holmes has an adventure unlike any he has
had before. </LI>
<LI>Rylant, Cynthia. <B>I HAD SEEN CASTLES</B>. Harcourt.  Now an old man,
John is haunted by memories of enlisting to fight in World War II, a decision
which forced him to face the horrors of war and changed his life forever. A
novel small in size (97 pages) but big in its message. </LI>
<LI>Voigt, Cynthia. <B>THE WINGS OF A FALCON</B>. Scholastic. 
Fourteen-year-old Oriel and his friend Griff flee the slavery of Damall's Island
and seek a new life on the mainland, where they face raiding Wolfers, rival
armies, and other dangers.  Part of the trilogy that includes <B>Jackaroo</B>
and
<B>On Fortune's Wheel</B>. Many of these titles are available in paperback.
</LI></UL>
<HR>
