<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vermont-NEA Reading List - Holidays 1994</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFF80">
<H2><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">1994 Holiday Booklist</FONT>  	</H2>
<P><B><I>Give a book over the holiday season to a child you love.  These
books are some of the best published in 1994. Several are by Vermont authors.
Most bookstores will order titles not in stock. </I></B></P>
<P><FONT COLOR="#0000FF"><B>Picture Books</B> </FONT></P>
<UL>
<LI>Meddaugh, Susan. <B>MARTHA CALLING</B>. Houghton. A sequel to <B>Martha
Speaks</B>, in which Martha the dog developed an amazing ability to talk. Here,
she wins a call-in radio contest and manages to change the &quot;no dogs allowed&quot;
policy at a resort. </LI>
<LI>Chapman, Cheryl. <B>SNOW ON SNOW ON SNOW</B>. Dial. The author uses
repetitive word play to tell the story of a boy who loses and then recovers his
dog while sledding. </LI>
<LI>Isaccs, Anne. <B>SWAMP ANGEL</B>. Dutton. Along with other amazing feats,
Angelica Longrider, also known as Swamp Angel, wrestles a huge bear to save the
winter supplies of the settlers in Tennessee. </LI>
<LI>Lester, Alison.
<B>MY FARM</B>. Houghton. An affectionate, funny and engaging memoir of a year
in the author's childhood on a farm in Australia. </LI></UL>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Primary Grades</FONT></B></P>
<UL>
<LI>Lester, Julius.
<B>JOHN HENRY</B>. Dial. Lester retells the life of the legendary hero who
raced against a steam drill to cut through a mountain. </LI>
<LI>Florian, Douglas. <B>BEAST FEAST</B>. Harcourt, $14.95. 21 poems play with
words in this collection of humorous poems about animals such as the walrus,
anteater, and boa. </LI>
<LI>Rylant, Cynthia. <B>MR. PUTTER AND TABBY WALK THE DOG</B>. Harcourt. When
their neighbor Mrs. Teaberry hurts her foot, Mr. Putter and his cat agree to
walk her dog for a week. They don't know what they're in for. For beginning
readers, also see <B>Mr. Putter and Tabby Pour the Tea</B>, and <B>Mr. Putter
and Tabby Bake the Cake</B>.</LI></UL>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Middle Grades </FONT></B></P>
<UL>
<LI>Haas, Jessie. <B>UNCLE DANEY'S WAY</B>. Greenwillow. When his great-uncle
Daney comes to live with Cole's family after being crippled in a logging
accident, the two work together all summer to find a way to make enough money to
buy feed so they can keep Daney's old horse. </LI>
<LI>Hesse, Karen. <B>SABLE</B>. Holt. Tate Marshall is delighted when a stray
dog turns up in the yard one day, but Sable, named for her dark, silky fur,
causes trouble with the neighbors and has to go.</LI>
<LI>George, Jean Craighead. <B>JULIE</B>. Harper Collins. A sequel to
<B>JULIE OF THE WOLVES</B>. When Julie returns to her father's Eskimo village,
she struggles to find a way to save her beloved wolves in a changing Arctic
world, and she falls in love with a young Siberian man. </LI>
<LI>Krull, Kathleen. <B>LIVES OF THE WRITERS: COMEDIES, TRAGEDIES (AND WHAT
THE NEIGHBORS THOUGHT)</B>. Harcourt. The lives of twenty writers, ranging from
Dickens, the Brontes and Poe to Twain, Sandburg and Langston Hughes, are
profiled in this eclectic, humorous and informative collection. A companion
volume to <B>LIVES OF THE MUSICIANS</B>. </LI>
<LI>Paterson, Katherine. <B>FLIP-FLOP GIRL</B>. Lodestar. Uprooted following
the death of their father, nine-year-old Vinnie and her five-year-old brother
cope in different ways &#151; one in silence &#151; but both with the help of
Lupe, the flip-flop girl. </LI>
<LI>Marrin, Albert. <B>UNCONDITIONAL SURRENDER: U.S. GRANT AND THE CIVIL WAR</B>.
Atheneum. An account of Grant's life and his role in the Civil War. An
outstanding portrait. </LI></UL>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Older Readers 		</FONT></B></P>
<UL>
<LI>Cushman, Karen.	<B>CATHERINE, CALLED BIRDY</B>. Clarion. The
thirteen-year-old daughter of an English country knight keeps a journal in which
she records the events of her life &#151; particularly her longing for adventure
beyond the usual role of women, and her efforts to avoid being married off.
</LI>
<LI>Fine, Anne.<B> FLOUR BABIES</B>. Little. When his class of underachievers
is assigned to spend three torturous weeks taking care of their own &quot;babies&quot;
in the form of bags of flour, Simon makes amazing discoveries about himself,
while coming to terms with his long-absent father. </LI>
<LI>Casey, Maud. <B>OVER THE WATER</B>. Holt. Fourteen-year-old Mary feels
like a misfit, both in England where her family lives and in Ireland where they
come from,  until she visits Ireland and gains a better understanding of her
background, her mother, and herself. </LI></UL>
<P><B><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">All Ages </FONT></B></P>
<UL>
<LI>Rogasky, Barbara, selector. <B>WINTER POEMS</B>. Illus. by Trina Schart
Hyman. Scholastic, $15.95. A nonsectarian collection of poems about winter, from
many times and places. Illustrations are set in Lyme, NH. 
</LI></UL>
<HR>
