   <TITLE>
RIT's College of Business - Dean's Message
   </TITLE>

</head>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#0000FF" vlink="#800080" alink="#FFAE5E">
<table width=590>
<tr>
<td>

	<!-- Start Header Information here -->
<center>
<IMG align=left  WIDTH=75 HEIGHT=98 SRC="images/rit_tiger_small.gif" alt="RIT Tiger">


<IMG  WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=40 SRC="images/banner_cob_medium.gif" alt="RIT's College of Business" border=0>
<br>
	<!-- Section Banner -->
<IMG  WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=35 SRC="images/banner_welcome.gif" alt="Welcome to the College of Business" border=0>
<br>
<br clear=all>
<hr noshade size="1">
</center>
	<!-- End Header Information -->

	<!-- Begin Page Content -->

<TABLE width=550 border=0 cellspacing=1 cellpadding=0>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN="Center"><IMG  WIDTH=114 HEIGHT=151 SRC="images/dean.gif" alt="Dr. Nowlin" border=0> </TD>
	<TD><h2>Message from the Dean</H2>
<STRONG><A HREF="faculty_staff/nowlin.html">Dr. William A. Nowlin</A>, Interim Dean</STRONG><br>
<BR>
<A HREF="#welcome">Welcome</A><BR>
<A HREF="#mission">Our Mission</A><BR>
<A HREF="#vision">Our Vision</A><BR>
<A HREF="#values">Our Values</A><BR>
<A HREF="#quality_ed">Quality Management Education</A><BR>


 </TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD colspan=2>
<HR>
<a name="welcome">
	
<font size="+1"><b>Welcome</b></font>
<BR>
<BR>

In pursuit of our vision and in keeping with our values, the
RIT College of Business:

<ul>
<li>forms mutually beneficial partnerships with employers
who share our vision and values. Their requirements are reflected
in our educational programs and they, in return, offer our
graduates appropriate opportunities for cooperative education and
employment.

<li>cooperates with secondary schools and Two-year colleges
in preparing their students for the employment opportunities our
employer partners offer.

<li>is committed to continuous improvements in its services
to students, both in and outside the classroom.

<li>encourages, supports, disseminates and rewards
scholarship focused on Quality Management, including its
foundation and its applications in all the disciplines of
business.
</ul>

</a> 
<hr>



<a name="mission">
<font size="+1"><B>Our Mission</B></font><br>
<br>
The RIT College of Business will fully prepare its graduates to manage organizations committed to continuous improvement, quality and customer satisfaction.<BR>
<BR>
We, through our curriculum, our teaching and our service to students will relentlessly pursue our own commitment to this objective.
<br>
</a> <hr>



<a name="vision">
<font size="+1"><B>Our Vision</B></font>
<br>
<br>
The RIT College of Business will distinguish itself nationally and internationally as the premier source of graduates fully prepared for employment by organizations committed to Total Quality Management.

<br>
</a> <hr>

<a name="values">
<font size="+1"><B>Our Values</B></font>
<br>
<br>

Our conduct must command respect for its integrity.  We must set an example for our students and for all our colleagues in higher education.  These are the values to which we commit ourselves.
<UL>
	<LI>Continuous Improvement
	<LI>Teamwork
	<LI>Openness and Mutual Trust 
	<LI>Frequent Two-way Communication
	<LI>Immediate Action
	<LI>Forthright Dealing
</UL>


<br>

</a> 
<hr>

<a name="quality_ed">
<font size="+1"><B> Quality Management Education</B></font><br>
<P><B><font size="+1"> Why implement Quality Management Education? </font></b><p>

"Employers including those that hire the largest numbers of our
graduates, are telling us that in this century, nothing more
fundamental and pervasive than TQM has transformed the practices
of management. They are pleading with business and engineering
colleges to integrate TQM into their curricula. But to teach it,
we must practice it."<p>

<font size="+1"><B> How are the Faculty involved in the change?</b></font><p>

"In 1991, faculty conducted an extensive review in preparation
for a complete revision of the curriculum. Though not every
course calls for complete revision, TQM affects most courses and
every business discipline. In September 1991, faculty were formed
into curricular teams and began the revision. As the process
evolved, the focus of the college shifted from the
discipline-centered curriculum teams. This led, in the spring of
1992, to abolition of the academic departments as a natural step
in the transformation of the college into a customer-oriented
college."<p>

<font size="+1"><B> TQM implies qualities of both cooperation and leadership.
How are these treated in the business curriculum?</b></font><p>
"Throughout the program, students work in teams and cooperate
with one another in learning. They are taught the skills of
leadership: how to present their ideas effectively, orally and in
writing, and how to interact well with others. These qualities are
essential in today's work place.<p>

RIT business students practice these skills throughout the
program".<p>

<font size="+1"><B>How does business at RIT differ from other universities
that offer courses and programs in TQM?</b></font><p>

"The key word is 'pervasive.' TQM affects everything we do. The
concepts of TQM are incorporated into everything we teach.
Teaching, itself, is a systematic process, to which the
principles of TQM can be applied. Process control applied to
teaching means that professors receive continuous feedback from
their students, allowing the professor to monitor students'
progress and equally important to correct and improve his or her
own approach to teaching. In the RIT College of Business, we expect every faculty member to make excellent teaching the primary goal."<p>

<font size="+1"><B>What can students expect in a TQM environment?</b></font>
<p>
" Quality Management Education means that students and faculty work together toward the goal of giving every student complete mastery of the knowledge and skills required for Total Quality Management. We want Malcolm Baldrige winners and contenders to be 
eager to hire our graduates. To achieve that, we need constant, immediate feedback from our students. Our students need our immediate response. We need to know when they require help. Academia can no longer assume that every failure to learn is a student 
failure. We need to know when we are doing something wrong. We need to know immediately so that we can get it right."

</a>
</TD>
</TR>

</table>




          <!-- End Page Content -->
