<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN//3.2">
<html>
<head>

   <TITLE>
RIT: COB: Accounting
   </TITLE>

</head>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<table width=590>
<tr>
<td>

	<!-- Start Header Information here -->
<center>
<IMG align=left  WIDTH=75 HEIGHT=98 SRC="../images/rit_tiger_small.gif" alt="RIT Tiger">



<IMG  WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=40 SRC="../images/banner_cob_medium.gif" alt="RIT's College of Business" border=0>
<br>
	<!-- Section Banner -->
<IMG  WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=35 SRC="../images/banner_degree.gif" alt="Section" border=0>
<br>
<br clear=all>
<hr noshade size="1">
</center>
	<!-- End Header Information -->

	<!-- Begin Page Content -->
<CENTER><H1>Accounting</H1> </Center>

<p>
Often referred to as the language of business, accounting is the art of measuring, communicating, and interpreting financial activity. Modern businesses must have accurate, timely and dependable financial information in order to remain competitive.
<p>
RIT's accounting major is designed to prepare students to meet the financial information needs of the ever-changing business world.  Students learn how to interact with other business disciplines and the business community in order to interpret and provide the informational needs of profit-making, non-profit and governmental business operations and regulatory agencies.
<p>
Successful accountants are those who serve their clients with both competence and integrity. Total Quality Management, the foundation of the accounting program at RIT, emphasizes the mastery of the subject, ethical behavior and quality client service. 
<p>

<HR width=300> <CENTER><FONT size="+2">
<A HREF="accounting_sequence.html">Course Sequence</A><BR>
<A HREF="accounting_descripts.html">Course Descriptions</A><BR>
<A HREF="../faculty_staff/main_department.html#accounting">Accounting Faculty</A><BR>
</FONT>
<HR width="50%">
<P>

<TABLE width="80%" border=0 cellspacing=1 cellpadding=0>
<TR><TD><FONT size="+1"><STRONG>Required Courses</STRONG></font><BR>
Accounting graduates receive a bachelor of science degree in business administration.  In addition of required business core courses, students
may choose between two tracks: CERTIFIED MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING (CMA) and
CERTIFIED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING (CPA). <br>

Both tracks require the following courses:<BR>
<ul>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#408">Financial Reporting and Analysis I</a>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#409">Financial Reporting and Analysis II</a>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#431">Cost and Managerial Accounting</a>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#320">Business Law</a>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#539">Accounting for Complex Organizations</a>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#541">Analytical Skills in Accounting</a>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#550">Financial Accounting and Reporting Issues</a>
<LI>Managing Corporate Assets and Liabilities
</UL><P>
CMA majors take the following additional courses:<BR>
<ul>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#410">Taxes for Decision Making</A>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#432">Advanced Cost Accounting</A>
</UL><P>
CPA majors take the following additional courses:<BR>
<ul>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#522">Tax Accounting I</a>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#523">Tax Accounting II</a>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#530">Auditing</a>
<LI><a href="accounting_descripts.html#560">Not-For-Profit and Governmental
Accounting</a>
</UL>
</TD></TR></table>
</center>
          <!-- End Page Content -->
<p>
