   <TITLE>
RIT: COB: Management
   </TITLE>

</head>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<table width=590>
<tr>
<td>

	<!-- Start Header Information here -->
<center>
<IMG align=left  WIDTH=75 HEIGHT=98 SRC="../images/rit_tiger_small.gif" alt="RIT Tiger">



<IMG  WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=40 SRC="../images/banner_cob_medium.gif" alt="RIT's College of Business" border=0>
<br>
	<!-- Section Banner -->
<IMG  WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=35 SRC="../images/banner_degree.gif" alt="Section" border=0>
<br>
<br clear=all>
<hr noshade size="1">
</center>
	<!-- End Header Information -->

	<!-- Begin Page Content -->
<CENTER><H2>Management</H2> </center>

<center><table  border=0><tr><td> 

<P>
Total Quality Management is the philosophy that underpins the management
major at RIT.  Because business leaders tell us that the effective
manager in today's organization needs both knowledge and personal
leadership skills, our curriculum is designed to train managers who can
satisfy the need with a comprehensive understanding of the world of
business.  RIT's management program encourages a high level of personal
development through a comprehensive program of liberal studies, a solid
business core and courses tailored to the student's major.

</table></center>

<HR width="50%">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE="+2">
<A HREF="management_sequence.html">Course Sequence</A><BR>
<A HREF="management_descripts.html">Course Descriptions</A><BR>
<A HREF="../faculty_staff/main_department.html#management">Management Faculty</A><BR>
</FONT>
<HR width="50%">
<P>

<TABLE width="80%" border=0 cellspacing=1 cellpadding=0>
<TR><TD><FONT size="+1"><STRONG>Required Courses</STRONG><BR></font>
<br>
Management graduates receive a bachelor of science degree in business administration.  In addition to the required core courses, which include courses in all functions of business, management majors take the following courses:
<UL>
<LI><a href="management_descripts.html#455">Human Resource Management</a>
<LI><a href="management_descripts.html#460">Management and Leadership</a>
<LI><a href="management_descripts.html#520">Seminar in Total Quality Management (TQM)</a>
</UL>
Within their major, students may concentrate their elective in areas of
entrepreneurship, management development, international management, 
organizational performance or the management of technology.  Those who
study in the entrepreneurship area have an opportunity to complete a
field studies course in their senior year and act as consultants to a
local small business.
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>


          <!-- End Page Content -->
