<TR>
	
<td>
<CENTER><H2>Masters of Business Administration (MBA)</H2></CENTER>
<P>
To give students the background essential in today's business
environment, faculty and staff have dedicated themselves to incorporating
the concepts, models, and processes of Total Quality Management
into the college's curriculum and operations. RIT's
College of Business has been recognized for its efforts in this
area and was one of eight universities nationwide chosen to participate in
the TQM University Challenge.
This program was developed by Motorola, Xerox, Proctor &amp; Gamble,
IBM, and Milliken to assist universities with the integration
of Total Quality Management into curricula. RIT's College
of Business also received a TQM grant of $1.28 million from IBM. 
<BR clear="all">
<HR>

<TABLE width="100%" border=0 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=10>
<TR><TD><UL>
<LI><A HREF="mba_admissions.html">Admissions Procedures</A> 
<LI><A HREF="mba_international_students.html">International Students</A> 
<LI><A HREF="mba_fin_aid.html">Financial Aid</A>
</UL></TD>
<TD>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="mba_credits.html">Credit Hour Requirements</A> 
<LI><A HREF="mba_program.html">Program Completion Requirements</A> 
<LI><A HREF="mba_curriculum.html">Curriculum</A>
<LI><A HREF="mba_concentration.html">Concentrations</A>
</UL>
</TD></TR>
	
</TABLE>
<HR>
The purpose of the MBA program is to enhance students'
depth and breadth of general management capabilities. Student take a
basic core of course work in the disciplines of management,
marketing, operations, economics, statistics, finance, and accounting. 
These are followed by advanced elective courses, some of which are
directed toward an area of concentration. Concentrations are available in
corporate accounting, public accounting, finance, marketing, management,
the management of technology, manufacturing management, and international
business.
<P>
The MBA program requires 72 quarter credit hours (18 courses)
and is designed so that a student will progress through the program
in a logical sequence while having some program flexibility. Those
students with previous course work in business may be eligible
for the waiver of specified foundation courses, thereby reducing
the length of their program. Students entering the MBA program
have widely varied academic backgrounds. 
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>




          <!-- End Page Content -->
