	<!-- Begin Page Content -->

<center> <table border=0> <tr> <td>

<h2><center>Master of Science in International Business</center></H2>
<p>
Rochester Institute of Technology's master of science degree in
international business addresses the growing demand for global managers
who understand the international business environment.
<p>
The program emphasizes both a global perspective and the interrelationships
among such business functions as marketing management and finance, and
cross-boundary business processes in a worldwide environment.
<p>
The curriculum combines international business theory and practice using
academic courses and employer focused research projects addressing global
corporate strategies.
<p>
The program is especially designed to:<br>
<ul>
<li>prepare business specialists for both small companies entering the
global market and corporations with extensive international markets<br>
<li>provide relevant international business related work experience
through the field practicum or thesis<br>
<li>provide a focused, innovative and interdisciplinary approach that will
allow you flexibility to meet your specific career goals.
</ul>
<P>
The interdisciplinary master of science program in international business,
combines related professional concentration courses with breadth of field
electives and a thesis or practicum, and enabling candidates to focus on
unique international business issues and concerns.
<p>
The program is designed for those with undergraduate business degree or
other business programs. Candidates for the MS in international business
will be able to improve their skills and understanding of global business
operations.<br>
<br>
<b>Required Courses:</b>
<dl>
<dd>Multinational Business Operations and Environment
<DD>International Business Seminar
</dl>
<b>Two courses from the following:</b>
<dl>
<dd>International Marketing
<dd>International Finance
<dd>International Management
</dl>
<b>Plus:</b>
<dl>
<dd>Four Breadth of field courses
<dd>Two research courses
<dd>A thesis or Practicum
</dl>
<p>
The four breadth of field courses for the MS in International Business are
often concentrated in marketing, Finance, information systems, management,
accounting or technology management. This breadth is necessary since most
MS in International Business graduates obtain professional employment in a
functional area with an international assignment.
<p>
The two research courses typically include Statistical Analysis for
Decision Making, Customer Satisfaction Research, Business Forecasting or
Design of Experiment I.
<p>
A thesis or practicum related to International Business issues and
concerns will be required of each candidate.
<p>
<hr> 
<B><H3>Curriculum</H3></b>
<p>
The graduate program of study consists of 48 credits or 12 courses, which
can be completed in one academic year of full-time study or in six
quarters of part-time study. 
<p>
<H4><b>Program Design</b></h4>
<p>
The program is composed of 4 courses in International Business major field
(16 quarter hours)
<p>
<b>Required:</b>
<dl>
<dd>Multinational Business Operations and Environment
<dd>Seminar in International Business
</dl>
<b>Choose any 2 of the following:</b>
<dl>
<dd>International Management
<dd>International Marketing
<dd>International Finance
</dl>
<p>
<b> 4 courses in the  breadth of field</b> (16 quarter hours)
<p>
The breadth of field courses comprise four courses from the College of
Business functional course offerings, i.e., accounting, finance,
marketing, management, information systems, as well as a course from
outside the College of Business.
<p>
<b> 2 courses in  research</b> (8 quarter hours)
<p>
These courses are designed to expose the candidate to procedures of
research methodology, data gathering and data analysis:
<p>
<b> Thesis</b>
<p>
The thesis is a conceptual and theoretical research project designed by
the candidate and a member of the graduate international business faculty.
In addition, the director of the program can aid the candidate in
selecting a thesis topic that has current international business relevance.
This is done to explore a salient international business oriented issue. 
<P>
<b>Practicum</b>
<p>
When the practicum option is selected, the candidate must complete an
applied corporate-oriented research project designed by the candidate and
international business faculty to explore an applied international
business issue.


<P>
<hr>
<h4> Admission Requirements</h4>
RIT operates on a quarter system calendar, thus part-time students may
apply for entry into the MBA program in the fall, winter, spring, or
summer. However, applicants planning full-time study must begin their
studies in the fall quarter. Completed applications for admission should
be on file in the Office of Admissions five weeks prior to registration
day for the upcoming academic quarter to ensure adequate time for
consideration by the Graduate Review Committee.
<P>
Admission to the MBA program will be granted to graduates of accredited
baccalaureate degree programs who, in the opinion of the Graduate Review
Committee of the College of Business, have demonstrated their potential to
successfully complete graduate business studies through their achievements
in their undergraduate program and professional career development.
<P>
All applicants who are admitted prior to the conclusion of their
baccalaureate programs are required to submit their final transcripts by
the end of the first quarter of graduate work. Students who have been
accepted into a program are allowed to defer their enrollment (admission)
for up to one year. If a student wishes to defer enrollment beyond one
year, a new application must be submitted, and credentials will be
reevaluated on the basis of current admission standards.

</Table>

</center>

