<center><IMG  align=right  WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=189 SRC="../images/praguemain.gif" BORDER=0 alt="U.S. Business School at Prague"> </center>
	

<H2><FONT FACE="Arial">UNITED STATES BUSINESS SCHOOL IN PRAGUE</FONT></H2>

<H3><FONT FACE="ARIAL"><i>Overview</i></FONT></H3>

<FONT FACE=ARIAL>
The U.S. Business School in Prague was established in December 1989, and
it was incorporated as  a not for profit educational organization in May
1990 in the State of Missouri in the United States. The masters of
business administration (MBA) degree is awarded to successful U.S.
Business School candidates by the Rochester Institute of Technology (RIT).
RIT is accredited by the State of New York and the Middle State
Association of Colleges and Schools, and RIT's College of Business is
accredited by the prestigious American Assembly of Collegiate Schools of
Business.
</FONT>
<br>
<HR>
<TABLE border=0 width="100%" cellspacing=5 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td>
<FONT FACE=ARIAL>
<ul>
	<li><a href="prague_curriculum.html">Curriculum</a>
</ul>
</font>
</td><td>
	<FONT FACE=ARIAL>
<ul>
	<li><a href="prague_faculty.html">Faculty</a>
</ul>
	</FONT>
</td></tr>
</table>
	
<p>
Richard N. Rosett, President of the U.S. Business School, also is dean
of the Rochester  Institute Of Technology's College of Business. Rosett
and Jack H. Purnell, chairman and chief executive officer of
Anheuser-Busch International, Inc., teamed with others to found the
school. The U.S. School of Business was established with the consent of
Milan Adam, former Czech minister of education, and with the support of
Vaclav Klaus, prime minister of the Czech Republic and former minister of
finance for Czechoslovakia. Prime Minister Klaus has served as an academic
adviser to the school since its inception.
<p>
In April 1995, the AACSB reaffirmed its accreditation of RIT's College of
Business and here is how they described RIT in their report:
<p>
<blockquote>"The College of Business is to be highly commended for its
dedication to quality.  It is undoubtedly one of the nation's leaders in
bringing Total Quality principles to the university."</blockquote>
<p>
<blockquote>"In effect, the college's approach to continuous improvement
is the embodiment of the spirit of the AACSB standards."</blockquote>
<p>
Most western MBA programs begin their advanced business studies already
familiar with how a free market economy works. But students at the
U.S.Business school at Prague first needed to be taught the fundamentals
of a free-market economy and then be taught how to succeed in the new
marketplace. U.S.Business School professors focus on teaching the
underlying factors that lead to an efficient, innovative, adaptable and
prosperous free-market economy. In essence, The U.S. Business School
offers Western-style advanced Graduate study of business, trade and
economics, customized to meet the needs of Central and Eastern European
students.
<p>
<hr>
<H3>TUITION, SCHOLARSHIPS AND FUNDING</H3>
As the U.S. Business School is a not-for-profit corporation, funding for
professors, travel, textbooks and administrative expenses in the United
States and Czech Republic is provided by a variety of U.S. foundations and
companies. Operating expenses also are funded in part by student tuition
of 55,000 crowns (approximately US $1930) per student for the one year
program. Tuition for non-Central and European students is US $15,000. This
fees are for the 1995-1996 academic year.
<p>
The School was established with an initial grant of $100,000 from
Anheuser-Busch International, Inc., Initial operating funds of $700,000
came from the Anheuser-Busch Foundation and the Lynde and Harry Bradley
Foundation. Other companies that have provided funding for the school
include  Price Waterhouse, Johnson and Johnson, Andersen Consulting, Credit
Swiss/ First Boston, Roland Berger, Ceska N.Y. and Helios. For information
about making a financial contribution to the U.S. Business School, contact
Richard N. Rosett in Rochester, New York 716-475-6915 
<p>
Scholarships are available and are awarded based on merit. Student
applications for the 1995-96 academic must be submitted by April 15, 1995.
The 1995-96 program begins September 4,1995, and ends June 30, 1996. For
additional information about the school or about the school or about
available housing, or to receive an admission/ Scholarship application,
please write:
<p>
<pre>
   Dr. Ivana Prosserova             Ms.Peggy Tirrell
   Jose Marti 2                     Max Lowenthal Building
   160 41 Praha 6-Veleslavin        104 Lomb Memorial Drive
   Tel : (422) 368-307              Rochester, NY 14623
   Fax : (422) 316-4770             Tel: 716-475-2795
   E-mail: Prosser@CDM.VSE.CZ       Fax: 716-475-7450
                                    E-mail: PAT2644@rit.edu
</pre>
<hr>
<H3>EMPLOYMENT OPPORTUNITIES</H3>
Graduates of the U.S. Business School in Prague have advanced into
management positions with a variety of companies, both in the Czech
Republic and elsewhere around the world. The schools graduates have
averaged 10 job offers per person. Companies that have hired U.S. Business
School graduates include: 
